<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos-Murders     12-15 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos-Murders,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos Knew of Conspiracy That Led to Murders, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ferdinand Marcos had ``full knowledge'' of an
intelligence conspiracy that led to the 1981 murders of two
anti-Marcos activists in Seattle, a lawyer told jurors Thursday.
   But a defense attorney said that although it's easy to see the
late Philippines dictator as ``the personification of excess and
evil,'' no evidence indicates the deaths of Silme Domingo and Gene
Viernes were caused by anything other than a local union dispute.
   The lawyers' comments came during closing arguments in a civil
lawsuit accusing Marcos, his widow, Imelda, and others of running
an intelligence network that harassed and intimidated anti-Marcos
elements in this country.
   Plaintiffs claim defendant Dr. Leonilo Malabed of San Francisco
ran an intelligence slush fund for Marcos that paid for the
murders, and that the payoff was delivered to the killers by
defendant Tony Baruso, who was president of the Alaska Cannery
Workers Union.
   Domingo and Viernes, who were reformist officers of the union,
were shot in its offices on June 1, 1981.
   Marcos' intelligence network ``ran amok'' and Marcos did nothing
to stop it, plaintiffs' attorney Michael Withey said.
   Marcos ``had full knowledge of the conspiracy and not only
foresaw but condoned acts of harassment and physical violence''
against his opponents in the United States, Withey told the U.S.
District court jury that is hearing the case against the Marcoses.
   Judge Barbara Rothstein will judge the liability of five other
defendants in the lawsuit, which seeks millions of dollars in
damages for the victims' survivors.
   Withey said the murders were ``made to look like a union dispute
_ hot-headed Filipinos shooting it out, vicious thuggery.'' But
evidence clearly showed Marcos headed an extensive intelligence
network not only in the Philippines but in the United States, he
said.
   ``We're talking about so many spy agencies you can't even count
them all,'' Withey said.
   At the start of the trial Thanksgiving week, Marcos defense
lawyer Richard Hibey had painted Domingo and Viernes as small fry
in the anti-Marcos movement, laboring in ``a smaller vineyard''
than more prominent activists.
   But Withey noted Viernes had traveled to the Philippines to meet
with ``the largest and most threatening labor organization Marcos
had ever encountered,'' and that both men had sponsored a
resolution critical of Marcos at a Hawaii labor convention.
   ``Mr. Hibey may have thought the vineyard was small, but
Ferdinand Marcos knew better,'' Withey said.
   Three men linked to a Filipino gang were convicted of murder on
the theory that Domingo and Viernes were victims of an internal
union dispute over work assignments and gambling in Alaska fish
canneries.
   ``There was turmoil in this union. There were bribes, there was
violence, there were gangs, there was murder,'' Hibey said.
   ``Sure, it's easy to look upon Ferdinand and Imelda Marcos as
the personification of excess and evil. That's what the case
panders to,'' he said.
   ``Don't be so blinded by it to seize on the target of two
incredibly unpopular people and hold them accountable for that
which is not theirs to account.''
   But Withey said evidence didn't support that explanation.
   ``The evidence establishes that Domingo and Viernes were far
more than anti-Marcos activists who happened to be killed in an
unrelated dispute,'' he said. ``They were very active and effective
anti-Marcos activists.''
   The jurors must decide whether the Marcoses were part of a
conspiracy that led to the murders and whether they were negligent
in exercising control over their intelligence network.
   Rothstein on Thursday granted a motion by the Philippines
government to be dismissed from the suit.
   In a videotaped deposition made before his death last September,
Marcos, who was overthrown in February 1986, took the Fifth
Amendment privilege against self-incrimination when asked about his
connections with Malabed.
</TEXT>
