<FIRST>r w PM-Gingrich-Ethics     12-15 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gingrich-Ethics,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gingrich Asking Campaign Contributors to Help Pay $125,000 in Legal
Fees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Whip Newt Gingrich is
appealing to his past campaign contributors to help pay more than
$125,000 in legal fees for preparing his defense against ethics
charges.
   Rich Galen, a spokesman for the Georgia congressman, said
Thursday that Gingrich sent an urgent fundraising letter last week
to some 12,000 previous contributors seeking help with his legal
bills.
   Two Washington attorneys, former Arkansas Rep. Ed Bethune and
Dan Swillinger, have been preparing a defense so Gingrich will be
ready if the House ethics committee decides to launch a formal
investigation of two complaints filed against him by Rep. Bill
Alexander, D-Ark., Galen said.
   ``It's like buying insurance,'' the spokesman said. ``You hope
you don't have to use it.''
   The ethics committee has taken no formal action on either
complaint. The first alleges that Gingrich violated House rules and
federal campaign finance laws by getting 21 investors to put up
$5,000 each to promote his 1984 book, ``Window of Opportunity.''
   An outside counsel hired to evaluate that complaint concluded in
October that there were not sufficient grounds for the panel to
investigate Gingrich, who was elected House GOP whip after filing
the ethics complaint that led to the resignation last June of
former Speaker Jim Wright.
   After the outside counsel made its recommendation, Alexander
filed another complaint, along with 670 pages of supporting
documents, accusing Gingrich of ethics and campaign finance
violations in seven new areas.
   Galen said Gingrich sent out the fundraising appeal because he
does not have enough money in his campaign account to pay the
attorneys' bills.
   Gingrich reported to the Federal Election Commission on June 30
that he had $35,847 in leftover debts from his 1988 re-election
campaign and a cash balance in his 1990 campaign account of $50,297.
</TEXT>
