<FIRST>r a AM-PECOSettlement     12-15 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-PECO Settlement,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>PECO Fined for Improperly Cutting Off Electricity to Customers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY MUTCHLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Public Utility Commission Thursday
fined Philadelphia Electric Co. $50,000 for improperly cutting off
electricity to customers, including a family who resorted to using
candles that started a fatal fire.
   The PUC said the utility also must contribute $400,000 to an
energy assistance fund for needy families as part of a settlement
regarding customer service violations over a two-year period.
   The most publicized case was last April, when PECO cut off
electricity to a Philadelphia family who used candles to light
their home.
   Eleven days later, a fire started in their row home in the
city's Fairmount section and killed seven-year-old Robert
Blackwell. His five-year-old brother Jason Blackwell received
third-degree burns over 35 percent of his body.
   An PUC investigation determined PECO did not alert a
``responsible adult'' in the family that service would be
terminated but instead told a neighbor.
   The commission said the utility also did not provide a 48-hour
termination notice and would not agree to payment plan offered
twice by the family to clear up the delinquent bill.
   Mitchell Miller, chief of the PUC's consumer research, said the
Blackwells owed $738.01. PECO terminated service and wanted $338 to
reconnect the electricity and asked the family to pay $20 a month
afterwards.
   The Blackwells received state assistance and could not afford
the amount, Miller said. He said PECO would not accept any other
payment arrangements.
   ``They treated this family like they were Mellon Bank,''
Commissioner Joseph Rhodes Jr. said. ``They didn't take into
consideration, as required by law, (the Blackwell's) ability to
pay.''
   After reading the PUC's report, Rhodes said he concluded
``PECO's violations of regulations directly and significantly
contributed to the death of Robert Blackwell and the maiming of
Jason Blackwell.''
   PUC Chairman William Shane said he believes the utility's
violations and sloppy administration contributed to the fatal fire.
He said Philadelphia Electric had been fined $50,000 for similar
violations in 1987. PECO was also forced to pay $150,000 to an
energy assistance fund.
   PECO spokesman Neil McDermott said the fatal fire cannot be
linked to the company's termination of service.
   Shane said it is ``quite disturbing'' that PECO did not modify
its behavior after the 1987 fines.
   ``I think a $400,000 fine has good possibilities for behavior
modification,'' Shane said, noting that the greatest driving force
for change ``is the death.''
   ``Without question, if you look at the report of the Bureau of
Consumer Services in this case, the company has made substantial
progress from where it was two years ago,'' McDermott said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
