<FIRST>r w PM-RuralHousing     12-15 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Housing,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rural America Has Low-Income Housing Crisis, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly three of every four rural households
pay more for housing than the government considers affordable, with
about a quarter of all rural residents living in substandard
dwellings, says a new report.
   ``To many Americans, the low-income housing crisis is primarily
an urban problem, calling up visions of homeless men and women
sleeping on steam grates and of families in city welfare hotels,''
said Robert Greenstein, director of the Center on Budget and Policy
Priorities.
   ``Yet in rural America, too, there is a crisis in housing for
low-income people,'' Greenstein said.
   His organization and the Housing Assistance Council coauthored
the report released Thursday.
   Sen. Terry Sanford, D-N.C., said the report demonstrates the
need for his rural housing legislation.
   Sanford has introduced a bill that would increase funding for
Farmers Home Administration rural housing programs by $500 million
over two years, targeting rural communities that traditionally do
not get much help from the federal government.
   ``In my home state of North Carolina, 12 rural counties have
poverty rates over 20 percent and occupied substandard housing
rates over 10 percent,'' said Sanford. ``Some 100,000 North
Carolina households still use outhouses.''
   The report found that 42 percent of rural poor households spent
at least half of their income on housing in 1985, the most recent
year for which data is available. It said 26 percent spent 70
percent or more for housing.
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development has standards
that say housing is not considered affordable unless it is 30
percent or less of a family's income.
   While an earlier Department of Agriculture study showed it's
more expensive to live in urban areas, the study released by the
two organizations Thursday says more rural residents live in
substandard housing than city dwellers.
   According to the report, the worst rural housing is in the South.
   The study showed that 83 percent of all rural housing units with
rats were in the South, as were 79 percent of the homes with
inadequate waste disposal, 73 percent with holes in the floor, 61
percent with inadequate heating, 53 percent with cracks in the
walls and 52 percent with inadequate water supplies.
   The study was based on data released in February 1989 by the
Bureau of the Census and HUD in a study called the American Housing
Survey of the United States in 1985.
   The Center for Budget and Policy Priorities is an independent
research organization that specializes in issues affecting low- and
moderate-income groups.
   The Housing Assistance Council promotes development of
low-income rural housing through seed-money loans, technical
assistance, research and information.
</TEXT>
