<SECOND>PM-Impounded Pets,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dog and Cat Returned To Owner In Rent Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A landlord's lawyer plans to appeal the
release of Iris the dog and Whitehill the cat, who had been
impounded in a dispute over back rent.
   Civil Court Judge Thomas Early signed an order this week
releasing the animals, seized Dec. 6 with Lynell Zelenka's car as
security for the money.
   ``The nightmare is over,'' said Zelenka, hugging her 7-year-old
Saluki, and her 11-year-old mixed-breed cat.
   Landlord John Chambers said she owes him $12,000 in rent, which
he agreed to let go unpaid while her lawsuit over a back injury was
pending. He claims she settled the injury suit recently and failed
to tell him.
   But Zelenka, who admits owing Chambers $6,000, ended up with
only $750 after paying attorney fees and medical expenses, Early
was told Tuesday.
   The judge said he has yet to decide how much rent Zelenka owes.
But he ruled Zelenka's pets have value only to her and, unlike a
cow or a horse, would bring no money if put up for sale.
   ``This is a form of hostage, so to speak, to take the dog and
the cat ... Why should the dog and the cat be pulled into the
middle of this thing and deprived of the love of their master?''
Early said.
