<FIRST>r a AM-LookingGlass     12-15 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Looking Glass,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon to Halt Round-the-Clock Flights of Airborne Command Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has proposed halting
round-the-clock flights of an airborne command post that since 1961
has had orders to take charge of nuclear forces if the president
and other leaders were killed, The New York Times reported Friday.
   According to Pentagon officials, the Defense Department is
instead proposing that the planes be changed to ``continuous ground
alert with specified number of sorties per week.''
   The Pentagon recommendation, made amid growing defense budgetary
restraints and the belief the threat of a surprise Soviet nuclear
attack is diminishing, needs President Bush's authorization.
   One official told the Times the plan has not drawn strong
objections from within the Defense Department, where some
preliminary defense budget recommendations were reversed after
debate.
   The Air Force maintains on a rotating basis a fleet of planes
collectively known as ``Looking Glass'' that has been under the
command of the Strategic Air Command in Omaha, Neb. In the event
U.S. leaders were killed during nuclear war, a SAC general would
assume command of nuclear forces.
   The proposal, which originated at SAC, would save about $20
million in fiscal 1990. The plan is one of several recommendations
to change defense planning and spending.
</TEXT>
