<FIRST>r w PM-Durenberger-Ethics     12-15 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Durenberger-Ethics,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Durenberger Made 40 Trips to Earn $100,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dave Durenberger, R-Minn., made at least
40 expense-paid speaking appearances to earn $100,000 through a
book contract he's accused of using to launder honoraria, records
show.
   His Minneapolis publisher said Thursday the speaking fees
enabled him to show a profit on Durenberger's two books on health
and defense policy and allowed the senator to record the earnings
as salary.
   The Senate Ethics Committee, which has hired a special counsel
to determine whether Durenberger used the book deal to circumvent
Senate honoraria limits, has subpoenaed records from organizations
that paid the fees as well as from publisher Gary L. Diamond.
   Durenberger amended his Senate financial disclosure statements
in recent months to list the 40 expense-paid speaking appearances,
many of them in such locales as Bermuda and Palm Springs, Calif.
   The speaking appearances include an engagement with the American
Podiatric Medical Association in Chicago in 1986 where ``there was
not even a mention of the book or books,'' said John Carson,
director of government affairs for the group.
   Carson said a $2,000 check was sent to Diamond's Piranha Press,
but he considered it ``from day one up to the current moment as a
fee for the purpose of the senator making a speech to our
audience.''
   Durenberger, who says he cleared the book deal through the
Federal Election Commission, contends he broke no Senate rules.
Aides said he would not respond to questions about the deals now
under investigation.
   The book deal is one of three plans Durenberger had for boosting
his income at a time he was having financial and marital
difficulties. Two of the arrangements are being looked at by the
Ethics Committee _ the book matter and allegations that Durenberger
arranged speeches in 1985 and 1986 to coincide with appointments he
and his wife had with a marriage counselor in Boston.
   The committee also could be asked to look at payments the Senate
made to Durenberger for his rental of a Minneapolis condominium in
which he owned an interest.
   Diamond says it was his idea, not Durenberger's, to have
Diamond's Piranha Press division publish the two books _ ``Neither
Madmen Nor Messiahs'' and ``Prescription for Change.''
   But it was the senator's idea to use Piranha Press as a
speaker's bureau to make money for both men from Durenberger's
appearances, Diamond said.
   He sold 13,000 copies of his books, not enough to cover the cost
of printing them, Diamond said. The $200,000 earned from the
senator's speaking appearances enabled the publisher to net a
$50,000 profit, said Diamond.
   ``That was not the intent. At the time we went into it we
thought most of the money would be from the sales, but it just
didn't work out that way. I thought we would sell more than we
did,'' Diamond said in a telephone interview.
   Diamond estimates special interest groups paid Piranha Press
about $200,000 to hear Durenberger speak over the two-year period.
   Durenberger ended the contract because of the criticism he
received, although the FEC concluded that payments from his
publisher would constitute a stipend rather than speaking fees, he
said.
   ``I believe I made a good faith effort to comply with the law by
contacting the FEC and seeking its opinion in advance of any work I
did under the agreement,'' Durenberger said in a statement his
office issued recently.
   The complaint before the Ethics Committee contends Durenberger
misrepresented the deal to the FEC.
   Durenberger lists 23 appearances in 1985 in connection with the
books, including trips to New Orleans, Hilton Head, S.C., and four
cities in Florida. His 17 engagements in 1986 took him to Palm
Springs twice and Bermuda and Monterey, Calif., once each.
   Durenberger filed the amendments to his financial disclosure
statements as a result of discussions between his aides and the
Senate Ethics Committee staff, said his press secretary, Carrie
Collins.
   The Ethics Committee staff has refused to comment on the
investigation, but the senator's office confirmed the panel
subpoenaed records about the speaking engagements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
