<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     12-15 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poindexter Says Reagan Fighting Subpoenas For Political Reasons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran-Contra defendant John Poindexter says
former President Reagan is trying to avoid political criticism in
attempting to quash a subpoena for his diaries.
   Poindexter's lawyers challenged both Reagan and President Bush
to invoke executive privilege in their attempts to quash defense
subpoenas for the former president's diaries and papers.
   Reagan and the Justice Department moved to quash the subpoenas,
but on legal grounds other than executive privilege.
   ``Obviously their legal position is carefully calculated to
avoid subjecting them to the political consequences of their
invoking the privilege, including the consequent public perception
that Mr. Reagan and Mr. Bush are still attempting to hide the true
facts regarding their involvement in the so-called Iran-Contra
affair,'' Poindexter's lawyers said in a court filing.
   Poindexter, who is accused of lying to congressional inquiries
about his involvement in the arms-for-hostages deals and covert
assistance to Nicaraguan rebels, underscored his desire to call
Reagan as a witness at the trial.
   ``Documents produced in response to the defendant's subpoena are
no substitute for Mr. Reagan's live testimony. Indeed, that live
testimony may be essential to the jury's understanding of those
documents,'' the defense brief said.
   Poindexter's filing in U.S. District Court was made in response
to motions by Reagan and the Justice Department to quash subpoenas
for documents in the possession of the former president and the
National Archives.
   In its brief, the Justice Department told Judge Harold H. Greene
``the unique and sensitive nature of the documents sought by
defendant mandates extreme prudence in fashioning a procedure
governing their potential disclosure.''
   Poindexter received the judge's permission to subpoena the
documents to try to show that he believed his actions in the
Iran-Contra affair were legal and authorized by Reagan so that he
would have no motive to lie about them.
   ``If Mr. Reagan or Mr. Bush is concerned about the impact of
this case upon the prerogatives of the presidency, then they should
invoke executive privilege,'' Poindexter's lawyers said.
``Otherwise, they are just wasting the court's and the defendant's
time.''
</TEXT>
