<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0238EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     12-15 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0585</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINONA, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What was thought to be a raven attacking
kids at the Winona Day Care Center in southeastern Minnesota turned
out to be a crow that seemed to just care a lot about people.
   On Wednesday, a group of preschoolers sang and danced around the
bird, which played tug-of-war with sticks and tried to land on
toddlers' heads.
   ``When a crowd of kids goes out on the playground, he feels he
has to come over and play,'' said teacher Nancy Hoffmaster.
   Hoffmaster and receptionist Debbie Stark said the bird also
liked to pick up pencils and other items, which it dropped on cars.
   But because the crow scared many of the children, it was
captured later Wednesday by security guard Art Kreisher Sr. and
Hoffmaster and put into a cage.
   Kreisher said he plans to free the bird unless it is claimed in
the next couple of days.
   ``I figure he's got a right to live. He really never hurt
anybody,'' Kreisher said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rachel Vital needed help getting up from
her chair to take the Oath of Allegiance to the United States. Once
she did, the 90-year-old woman stood proudly and became a U.S.
citizen.
   ``It's always been her dream to become a citizen,'' Victor Vital
said as he watched his mother take the oath Wednesday in the
courtroom of U.S. District Judge Robert Renner.
   After the ceremony, Mrs. Vital, a native of Salonica, Greece,
smiled and joined the applause for herself and 48 others from
Europe, Asia and Africa who became citizens.
   Victor Vital said his mother tried to become a citizen when he
did back in 1973, about six years after she came to this country,
but she couldn't pass the test because of a language problem.
   ``She can speak Greek, Italian, Spanish and French, but not
English. But after 20 years, even if you don't speak English, you
can become a citizen as long as you know the main laws,'' he said.
``My mother always had the dream to become a citizen because her
children are. We love Greece, but this is our home.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children who are frightened by the big,
bad image of gun-toting TV cops may find it easier to deal with
state police carrying the latest weapon in their arsenal _ a
uniformed teddy bear.
   Indiana hopes to have the 10-inch stuffed bears in its cars by
January, and several other states have similar programs.
   ``Trooper Teddy'' began riding shotgun in all Kentucky State
Police cars this month.
   Troopers carry the bears to give to children who are victims of
auto accidents, sexual abuse or other traumatic crimes.
   ``Many children aren't used to seeing the uniform, the badge,
the gun,'' said Capt. John Lile, commander of public affairs for
the Kentucky State Police. ``We're trying not to be so
intimidating.''
   The Indiana State Police Alliance is working to raise at least
$3,000 to buy 500 bears to carry in police cars.
   ``It's like falling off a log to raise money for sick and dying
children,'' said Ernie Alder, director of youth services for the
Indiana State Police. ``No one can say no.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>___</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Donations of $10 to purchase a bear for an Indiana police car
may be sent to Ernie Alder at Box 89, Cambridge, Ind., 47327.
</TEXT>
