<DOCNO> AP891215-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0242EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Nicaragua     12-15 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Observers Describe Violence at Nicaraguan Election Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House says a bipartisan panel's
report on bloody violence at a rally in Nicaragua raises the Bush
administration's concerns that the Sandinistas don't intend to hold
a fair election.
   Members of the panel on Thursday gave President Bush a firsthand
account of the bloodletting last weekend that they said was caused
by Sandinista supporters wielding machetes.
   Democratic and Republican members of the delegation met with
Bush for 30 minutes, displaying photographs and videotapes of
people whose arms had been severed. At least one person was killed
in the violence, officials have said.
   ``Our point was that unless something is changed dramatically
now ... people will be afraid to vote'' in the Feb. 25 election,
said delegation member Bob Beckel, a political consultant who was
Walter Mondale's 1984 presidential campaign manager.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the group's
report ``only heightens'' concerns that the Sandinistas won't hold
a fair election as scheduled in February.
   Fitzwater said the White House gave additional credence to the
group's report because Beckel opposes aid to the U.S.-backed
Contras. Beckel told reporters although he was disturbed by the
events, he remained opposed to Contra aid.
   The group said Bush agreed to help arrange a meeting with the
Contras in an effort to get a pledge that the rebels won't
instigate violence during the election.
   Members of the group said supporters of the leftist government
violently disrupted a Sunday rally held by backers of opposition
presidential candidate Violeta Chamorro in the town of Masatepe and
that a Sandinista police chief refused entreaties to stop the
fracas.
   Cecilia Lopez, a spokeswoman for the Nicaraguan Embassy in
Washington, called the Masatepe violence ``an isolated incident''
and said the opposition has held more than 50 peaceful rallies
since campaigning began.
   Ambassador Luigi R. Einaudi, the U.S. representative to the
Organization of American States, said Thursday that there had seven
incidents of violence or intimidation since Nov. 1, when the
Sandinistas lifted their unilaterally declared cease-fire against
the Contra rebels.
   ``Despite many fine words about good intentions, the reality of
the violence is ... preventing the elections from channelling the
conflict into the political foms that could give Nicaraguans hope
for a more peaceful future,'' Einaudi said in a speech to a regular
session of the OAS Permanent Council.
   Members of the American group said OAS observers missed most of
the violence and later deliberately downplayed the Sandinista
involvement by saying it was impossible to say who started the
violence or who played a major role.
   The delegation said in its report that observers arrived to find
a rock-throwing battle involving about 100 people. The American
delegation and two OAS observers ``moved through the crowd, urging
calm.''
   One of the OAS observers told the Americans the fracas began
when opposition supporters were set upon by a small group of
Sandinista backers who taunted them and threw rocks.
   After the nearby political rally concluded, several bands of
Sandinista youths charged into the crowd with rocks, nail-studded
sticks and machetes, the report said.
   The observers said they tried to help break up the fracas and
later sought out the police chief to intervene. The police chief
said he didn't want to intervene because he feared he would be
accused of interrupting an opposition rally, but finally agreed to
accompany them to the site of the fracas, the report said.
   The trip by the 15-member American delegation was sponsored by
the non-profit Center for Democracy, which has sent election
observers to Panama, El Salvador and the Philippines. Nicaragua
invited the center to send a team to monitor election preparations.
</TEXT>
