<FIRST>r a PM-American-CBS     12-15 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-American-CBS,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Airline In-Flight News to Lack Air Crash Video</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airline flights will feature taped CNN
newscasts without pictures of plane crashes, after CBS balked at
the airline's request that it cut such stories from its in-flight
programs.
   American did not renew its six-year contract with the ``CBS
Morning News'' and the last program will be shown on the airline
before Feb. 28, said David Berman, a vice president at CBS
Broadcast International.
   Under American's guidelines, he said, CBS has pulled entire news
programs with reports of airline crashes or ``virtually anything
detrimental to the airlines.''
   But CBS refused American's request to delete adverse airline
news ``and deliver the remainder of the show,'' he said.
   American's rationale may be to avoid alarming passengers, but
``it's like passing out newspapers with holes cut in them,'' Berman
said Thursday.
   American's decision to drop CBS was financial and wasn't based
on an editorial dispute, said Mary O'Neill, a spokeswoman for the
airline, ``We didn't feel we were earning enough profit from our
agreement with CBS,'' she said.
   But she said the new CNN arrangement, in which video portraying
airline crashes will be deleted, was worked out after American's
surveys showed that its passengers complained that pictures of
airline crash scenes disturbed them.
   American's new in-flight agreement for Cable News Network
newscasts is with Turner Home Entertainment, a division of Ted
Turner's Atlanta-based cable empire that merchandises CNN programs
and other ventures.
   CNN said it hopes to have news programs aboard 144,000 American
flights annually by the end of 1990. Its newscasts will begin in
March with eight domestic flights. He declined to disclose the
value of the contract.
   Steve Chamberlain, a vice president of Turner's merchandising
division, said the American-CNN contract is expected to be signed
next week, and editorially ``is limited to (stories about) air
crashes.''
   ``There will not be any other wholesale editing of our
product,'' he said. ``Above all, we have to preserve the
journalistic integrity of our network.''
   Chamberlain called the agreement ``a common-sense approach to
crashes aboard those jets.''
   ``It is unreasonable to expect airline passengers to sit and
watch a graphic portrayal of an airline tragedy,'' he said.
   But Ed Turner, a senior vice president at CNN, said, ``As a
passenger, it would probably make me feel better, but as a
journalist, it doesn't.''
   Chamberlain said none of the other 10 airlines using CNN have
asked for edited versions of the news, which is recorded from live
feeds.
   O'Neill, in a telephone interview from American headquarters in
Dallas, said the agreement wouldn't mean a complete blackout of
such stories.
   ``What the contract with CNN calls for is that CNN will not show
the video,'' she said. ``They will talk, in the audio portion,
about these kinds of incidents. But they will not show the video.''
   Barry Sherman, chairman of the telecommunications department at
the University of Georgia, said the agreement could hurt CNN's
reputation as being free from taint and bias.
   ``What CNN has built its reputation on has been that it has not
avoided the hard issues. They've never, to my knowledge, edited
news content,'' Sherman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
