<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-15 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Market Hits New High, Dollar Climbs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed at
another record high on Friday despite a morning setback, while the
dollar rose against the Japanese yen.
   The dollar closed at 144.30 yen, up 0.23 yen from Thursday's
close of 144.07 yen. After opening at 144.30 yen, the dollar ranged
betwen 144.25 and 144.38 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 90.34
points for a record closing of 38,271.04. The index's previous
record closing was the 38,180.70 points set Thursday.
   Trading was inactive because of the expected release later
Friday of monthly U.S. economic figures, including trade data for
October and producer prices and industrial production data for
November, dealers said.
   The Nikkei slipped shortly after trading began as market
players, who were already worried about the speed of recent rises
in the index, stepped to the sidelines. But it recovered later
after intermittent index-buying by foreign securities firms, the
dealer said.
   Index-buying is a tactic that involves the purchase of at least
1,000 shares in all 225 Nikkei issues.
   In currency dealings, currency rates moved narrowly in inactive
trading, in which market players awaited the U.S. economic data,
said Toru Kanai, a foreign exchange analyst with New Japan
Securities Co.
   ``The dollar-yen rate moved very tightly, while market players
were just making position adjustments on the West German mark,'' he
said.
   Kanai added that investors in general become reluctant to make
major moves toward the end of the year to avoid possible risks
during the Christmas and New Year holidays.
</TEXT>
