<DOCNO> AP891215-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i BC-Sakharov-LastStatement     12-15 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sakharov-Last Statement,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Text of Sakharov's Final Public Statement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a text of Andrei D. Sakharov's final
public statement, a call to create a formal opposition to the
Soviet Communist Party. It was made hours before his death Thursday
to opposition members in the Congress of People's Deputies. It was
translated from Russian by The Associated Press:
   
   I support the formula of opposition. What is opposition? First,
we cannot take on ourselves responsibility for what the leadership
is doing now. It is leading the country to catastrophe, prolonging
the process of perestroika many years. It will leave the country in
a condition in which everything progressive will be destroyed
during these years. All the plans for transition to a market and
perestroika-type economy appear to be unrealistic. Dissatisfaction
is growing in the country, and this dissatisfaction makes the
revolutionary path of development impossible.
   The only possible path of revolutionary development is the
radicalization of perestroika. At the same time we declare
ourselves an opposition, and take the responsibility for the
solutions we suggest. This is another side of the same term
(opposition), which is extremely important as well.
   At this moment, we live in conditions of a deep crisis of trust
in the party and the leadership. This can be eliminated only by
resolute political measures. The exclusion of Article 6 of the
constitution and of the articles in line with Article 6 is a
political move, not purely juridicial or organizational. This is a
most significant political act right now in this country, and not
in a year when work over the new text of the constitution will be
completed. Then all this will no longer be in doubt. We need to
accelerate the process of perestroika now.
   The last thing we need is to make certain the position of our
Inter-Regional Group. The population of the country puts great hope
in the group. But we began losing the trust of the people.
   The last matter I wanted to speak about is whether the political
strike was a present for right-wing forces, and whether an
opposition group will be one as well. I categorically disagree with
both statements. What happened in the past week is the most
powerful politicalization of the country. Discussions embrace the
entire country. It is not important whether there were a lot of
strikes or not. They were quite numerous, including strikes in the
Don Basin, Vorkuta, Lvov and many other places. But this fact is
not of principal importance. It is important that the people at
last have found a means to express their will and readiness to
support us politically. And we cannot lose this support. The only
possible response from us is our political position. They do not
need anything else.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
