<DOCNO> AP891215-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0306EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Casolo-Homecoming Bjt   12-15 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casolo-Homecoming, Bjt,0694</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jennifer Casolo Gets Hero's Welcome Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto HF1, NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LIGHTFOOT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THOMASTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jennifer Casolo received a hero's
welcome and proclaimed she was innocent of hiding munitions in her
yard in El Salvador as she greeted 350 residents who turned out in
freezing cold to cheer her return.
   Casolo, who said she maintained neutrality while giving visiting
Americans tours of El Salvador during four years there, said
Thursday night she will speak out against U.S. aid to the
Salvadoran government now that she has been expelled.
   Casolo arrived in Miami on Wednesday, then flew Thursday to New
York, where she fielded questions from reporters at LaGuardia
Airport before being driven the 75 miles to Thomaston in a Cadillac
with Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who had lobbied for her
release from a Salvadoran prison.
   Casolo embraced her father, John Casolo, and met close friends
and relatives, including her brother, John, who were waiting for
her in the Town Hall of the town of 7,000 people.
   ``I want to thank each and every one of you from the bottom of
my heart for all the prayers and letters,'' John Casolo told the
crowd outside. ``You've really made this the merriest Christmas
we've ever had.''
   Jennifer Casolo, standing on a flatbed truck draped in red,
white and blue bunting, wished the crowd ``Feliz Navidad'' and _
when a sound system failure forced her to use a big megaphone _
joked about her days as a cheerleader at Thomaston High School.
   She left El Salvador Wednesday after a judge dropped terrorism
charges against her for lack of evidence and ordered her deported.
   Casolo, who worked in El Salvador for the Christian Educational
Seminars since 1985, was arrested Nov. 26 after authorities raided
her rented house and unearthed dynamite, grenades and more than
20,000 rounds of ammunition from the garden.
   She said her tribulations were minor compared to those of the
Salvadoran people, 70,000 of whom have died in a decadelong civil
war. But the disrespect with which U.S. authorities dealt with her
case demonstrated their cynicism toward El Salvador's people, she
said
   ``It's shameful. It's disgraceful,'' she said in New York. ``How
can the Bush administration say they're working to create a just
society in El Salvador when they can't even treat an American
citizen with the rights of a just society?
   ``I tried to convey to the Salvadoran police that a person is
innocent until provent guilty but I didn't know that American
officials weren't giving me that right.''
   Bush administration officials did not press for her release and
had said they thought she was probably guilty.
   Casolo said she had a great love for the Salvadoran people and
would not ``feel free'' until all political prisoners were released
there.
   The Salvadorans ``deserve a country where they can eat, where
their children can go to school, where they don't have to worry
about being dragged away in the middle of the night,'' Casolo said.
   Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani said he was convinced of
her guilt, despite her release. Asked about that Thursday night,
Casolo said simply, ``I'm innocent.''
   She went on: ``Maybe those weapons were there. Maybe a
Salvadoran guerrilla tipped them off ... but there's just as much
possibility that they beat the hell out of someone to get them to
say it _ and excuse my language.''
   Of the weapons cache, she said, ``I don't know if it was there,
if they put it there or if someone else put it there and I don't
think I'll ever know.''
   Casolo urged an end to U.S. military aid to El Salvador.
   ``For four years I worked in El Salvador. ... During that time I
kept my mouth shut,'' she said. ``It's time for me to talk, so that
others better understand what has happened.''
   After the official homecoming at Town Hall, Casolo headed for a
private reunion with her mother, Audrey Casolo, who did not attend
the welcome ceremony because she wanted to greet her daughter
privately.
</TEXT>
