<FIRST>r a PM-TylerCase     12-15 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tyler Case,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disputed Murder Sentence the Product of Racial Tension, Attorney
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY COATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The imprisonment of a former black civil
rights activist resulted from racial polarization in the state,
Gary Tyler's lawyer said after a racially split vote by a pardon
board to reduce his sentence.
   The board voted 3-2 Thursday to recommend that Gov. Buddy Roemer
reduce the life sentence for Tyler, who at 16 was condemned to die
for the 1974 slaying of a white student during a racial
confrontation.
   The death sentence was automatically changed to life when the
U.S. Supreme Court overturned Louisiana's old death penalty law in
1976.
   Tyler's conviction has withstood all appeals, but the vote would
make him eligible for parole in five years. Roemer will make a
decision within a few weeks, his aides said.
   Parole eligibility isn't the same as freedom for Tyler, 31,
whose entire adult life has been spent in the state prison at
Angola, said attorney Mary Howell.
   ``If Gary was white we wouldn't be here today,'' she told
reporters after the pardon board meeting. ``We still don't see the
kind of justice we want in this state.''
   The vote _ three black members for reduction in sentence and two
whites against _ is representative of ``racial polarization,'' said
Howell.
   ``It's pretty amazing,'' she said. ``In 1985 in Ascension Parish
a white kid shot to death an unarmed black kid at a school and was
indicted for manslaughter. He was placed on probation and told to
finish his education and pay the funeral costs of the victim.
   ``And, then we have Gary Tyler, a black kid who police said had
a `smart mouth.'''
   Amnesty International and other human rights organizations have
urged freedom for Tyler, as have more than 12,000 people who signed
petitions to the pardon board. The British reggae band UB40
recorded a song about Tyler and he was described by the Soviet
Communist Party newspaper Pravda in 1978 as a political prisoner.
   Tyler's mother, Juanita Tyler, said she was happy with the
decision, but believes board members would have voted for an
immediate release had they interviewed him. Board members routinely
do not interview inmates unless they are facing death.
   Tyler was active in a school desegregation battle in October
1974 that drew the Ku Klux Klan and state police to Destrehan, a
small town on the Mississippi River 25 miles north of New Orleans.
   One day, whites surrounded buses of black students at Destrehan
High School, shouting and hurling bottles, cans and rocks. A shot
was fired from one of the buses. Timothy Weber, a white student
standing with his mother across the schoolyard, fell dead.
   Witnesses said the pistol was held by a gloved hand. Tyler was
the only one on the bus wearing gloves, said police.
   Those who believe Tyler was framed say that a student who
testified against him was known as a liar and that police planted a
pistol found in the stuffing of the torn seat where Tyler had sat.
</TEXT>
