<FIRST>r i PM-Chile 1stLd-Wriththru   12-15 0767</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile, 1st Ld - Wriththru,a0454,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Wins Big in Vote For Pinochet Successor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS one graf to INCLUDE regional movement to democracy. No
pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Patricio Aylwin told
his jubilant supporters today that Chileans have regained their
freedom by electing him president, ending the dark era of military
rule under Gen. Augusto Pinochet.
   Chileans danced, waved national flags and set off fireworks to
celebrate Aylwin's landslide victory Thursday over Hernan Buchi, a
pro-government candidate. Celebrations lasted into the morning in
Santiago and cities nationwide.
   The election was intended to bring back democracy to the last
South American country still ruled by the military.
   Pinochet was forced to call the election after losing a
referendum in October last year, in which voters rejected a
military proposal that he remain as president until 1997.
   Speaking to hundreds of supporters early today from the
third-floor balcony of a downtown hotel, Aylwin referred to the
generations of democracy enjoyed by Chileans until Pinochet
overthrew elected President Salvador Allende in a bloody 1973 coup.
   ``Chile has refound her history. Chile has regained liberty.
Chile has regained democracy,'' said Aylwin, who promised a
government of national unity to repair the political and social
divisions under the Pinochet regime.
   Pinochet's government officially recognized Aylwin's triumph.
Interior Minister Carlos Caceres said in a nationally broadcast
address that authorities would abide by it.
   Official results from 93 percent of all polling stations in
Thursday's election gave Aylwin 3,577,669 votes or 55.2 percent of
all valid ballots. He was supported by a coalition of 17 parties
ranging from right to left.
   Buchi, Pinochet's former finance minister and architect of a
free market economy, had 1,901,668 votes or 29.4 percent. A third
candidate, populist businessman Francisco Errazuriz, had 998,786
votes, 15 percent.
   Buchi and Errazuriz visited Aylwin to congratulate him on his
victory.
   His absolute majority and 2-1 advantage over his nearest
pro-government challenger appeared to give him the mandate for a
possible upper hand in future relations with Pinochet, who has
vowed to remain on as army commander.
   Aylwin, 71, a Christian Democrat and former Senate president, is
to begin a four-year term on March 11, when Pinochet's term ends.
   Much of his future authority was expected to depend, however, on
results from Thursday's voting for the 38 elected Senate seats and
120 House of Deputies seats. Up to 10 more senators are to be
designated by the Supreme Court, National Security Council and
other government bodies.
   Conclusive returns in the congressional races were not expected
until later today. However, there were indications from
preliminary, unofficial returns that the pro-government forces may
have fared better in the congressional vote than in the
presidential race.
   From the moment Aylwin's victory became evident, supporters took
to the streets, dancing and chanting or roaming in noisy caravans
of buses, trucks and automobiles. They waved Chilean flags and
party banners, blowing on horns and shooting off fireworks.
   Similar celebrations were reported in other large cities, and in
the Pacific resort city of Vina del Mar, national police used water
cannons to clear the streets.
   Demonstrations are legally banned on election day. Police in
Santiago, who had blocked many anti-Pinochet protests and fired
water cannons and tear gas at demonstrators in the past, did not
intefere with the celebrations and even suspended traffic on the
city's main boulevard to allow Aylwin supporters to listen to their
leader's victory speech.
   ``It's forbidden,'' said a police lieutenant at the scene, ``but
there's no problem.''
   Ending his speech, Aylwin urged the demonstrators to return
peacefully and to attend a celebration rally tonight.
   Pinochet, in a bref conversation with reporters, said he was not
disturbed by Aylwin's victory. ``They were better organized. They
know how to do things,'' he said.
   The election was peaceful, with voters arriving early at the
polls and waiting patiently in long lines, sometimes for hours, to
cast their ballots. Nearly all 7.5 million elegible voters cast
their votes.
   Caceres said Chileans should take pride on the peaceful manner
the election took place and for the high turnout, and praised the
armed forces for maintaining order.
   Aylwin lauded the ``maturity'' of the population, and also said
the armed forces deserved praise for carrying out a clean election.
   Chile becomes the eighth South American nation in a decade to
return to civilian rule. Others include Ecuador, Peru, Bolivia,
Argentina, Uruguay and Brazil. In February, Paraguayan Andres
Rodriguez ended more than three decades of rule by Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner, overthrowing him and declaring a presidential election,
which Rodriguez won.
</TEXT>
