<FIRST>r i PM-Chile-Democracy     12-15 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chile-Democracy,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile Eighth South American Nation in a Decade to Return to Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chileans elected a new president, in a
process that brought civilian government back to the last country
in South America still ruled by the military. With the election
Thursday, Chile becomes the eighth nation to undergo such a
transition in the last decade.
   The others are:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ecuador _ 1979. President Jaime Roldos Aguilera takes office,
ending a decade of military dictatorship.
   Peru _ 1980. Fernando Belaunde Terry wins election and reassumes
the presidency, ending a 12-year period of military rule that began
with his overthrow in a coup 12 years before.
   Bolivia _ 1982. The election of veteran former president Hernan
Siles Suazo puts an end to a series of military governments,
including one that blocked him from taking office after an election
two years earlier.
   Argentina _ 1983. After seven years under four successive
military juntas, the nation elects civilian President Raul Alfonsin.
   Uruguay _ 1985. Julio Maria Sanguinetti, elected in late 1984,
takes office to restore civilian rule in one of south America's
most traditional democracies. The armed forces had seized power 11
years earlier.
   Brazil _ 1985. Jose Sarney becomes president, replacing Tancredo
Neves, who died hours before he was to take office, having been
picked by an electoral college. More than two decades of military
control came to an end.
   Paraguay _ 1989. After more than three decades of authoritarian
rule by Gen. Alfredo Stroessner, another general, Andres Rodriguez
toppled him in a coup. Rodriguez then wins election as the new
president.
</TEXT>
