<FIRST>u i PM-Sakharov-LastDays     12-15 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sakharov-Last Days,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov Fought Until the End to Reform Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Sakharov, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An increasingly radical and disillusioned Andrei
D. Sakharov fought until the end to keep the Soviet Union on the
path of reform started by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   He died late Thursday while writing a speech to the Soviet
Congress demanding the Communists' constitutional guarantee to
power be revoked, his family said. His last words to them were:
``Tomorrow there will be a battle.''
   Hours earlier, Sakharov made an uncompromising, if not eloquent,
appeal to create a formal political opposition to the Communist
Party and to build a multiparty democracy.
   ``We cannot take on ourselves responsibility for what the
leadership is doing now,'' Sakharov told the Inter-Regional group.
``It is leading the country to catastrophe, prolonging the process
of perestroika many years.''
   Sakharov's high-pitched voice, rambling style and stammer made
him a poor public speaker, and despite the group's respect for him,
the hum of other conversations in the hall increased as Sakharov
spoke.
   Sakharov spent his last several days working in the seat of
Soviet power where, until just a few short years ago, he was
roundly and regularly condemned.
   Having supported Gorbachev's reforms in 1987 after the Soviet
leader brought him back from internal exile, Sakharov had taken an
increasingly critical view recently that brought him into conflict
with his president.
   He and other radicals had called for a two-hour general strike
Monday to press for elimination of Article 6 of the Soviet
Constitution, which makes the Communist Party the ``leading and
guiding force of Soviet society and the nucleus of its political
system.''
   His last exchange with Gorbachev, shown on live television
several hours after the opening of the Congress' winter session on
Tuesday, was a bitter one.
   Having cut off another deputy who wished to take the podium,
Gorbachev invited Sakharov to address the 2,250-member Congress.
   Sakharov urged the Congress to strike ``all the articles
hindering the passing of laws on land, property and other bills
promoting perestroika.''
   When he began to speak about the party's monopoly on power,
Gorbachev halted him with a curt ``thank you.''
   ``I am under the impression that neither you nor we will know
how to realize your suggestion,'' Gorbachev said. ``Who is to
define what articles to exclude?''
   When Sakharov turned to Gorbachev and handed him a stack of
telegrams in support of his position, the Soviet leader retorted:
``You come to me, I will give you three files of telegrams.''
   Undaunted, Sakharov continued to press the issue.
   Sakharov was elected one of five leaders of the Inter-Regional
Deputies Group when it was formed in August, and he recently had
become one of its more radical and outspoken members.
   Dressed in a brown suit, he sat at the end of the head table,
his chair pushed back and forehead in hand, at the group's meeting
Thursday. With him at the table were the group's other leaders:
historian Yuri Afanasyev, Communist maverick Boris N. Yeltsin and
economists Gavriil Popov and Viktor Palm.
   The general strike he pressed for on Monday failed, and that
tactic was widely criticized by Inter-Regional deputies Thursday.
One deputy said the strike call was ``present No. 1'' to the
conservatives controlling the Congress, and that the formation of a
political opposition would be ``present No. 2.''
   Historian Roy Medvedev, a long-time acquaintance who also serves
in the Congress of People's Deputies, said in an interview that
Thursday had been a ``difficult day'' for Sakharov.
   ``He wasn't a politician, and didn't always realize the
consequences of his actions, but he never gave in to
circumstances,'' Medvedev said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
