<FIRST>r a PM-Tranquilizers-HipFractures     12-15 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tranquilizers-Hip Fractures,0586</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Hip Fractures Judged Preventable With Switch in Tranquilizers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-CDC--Smoking Survey, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of elderly people fall and fracture
their hips because they take long-lasting sleeping pills, mainly
Valium, Librium and Dalmane, instead of shorter-acting drugs, a
researcher says.
   The long-acting drugs are no more effective than related,
shorter-acting drugs, but the long-acting drugs were developed
first, and some doctors still are prescribing them to the elderly,
said epidemiologist Wayne A. Ray.
   Ray is co-author of a study published in today's edition of the
Journal of the American Medical Association that found people over
65 who took the long-lasting benzodiazepine drugs were 70 percent
more likely to sustain hip fractures than those who took no such
drugs.
   But shorter-acting benzodiazepines carried no higher risk, the
study said.
   ``Hip fracture is a serious injury,'' Ray said.
   He noted that about 250,000 elderly people fall and break their
hips annually in the United States, resulting in monetary costs of
$6 billion.
   The human costs are even higher, Ray said: a 20 percent
increased death rate in the year after the fracture; a loss of
ability to walk unassisted among up to half the victims; and entry
into nursing homes among up to a third of victims.
   Hip fractures mark ``the beginning of the end'' for many elderly
people, Ray, an associate professor of preventive medicine at
Vanderbilt University School of Medicine in Nashville, said in a
telephone interview Thursday.
   He estimated that 10 percent to 15 percent of people over 65
take benzodiazepine drugs, the most commonly prescribed
tranquilizers and sleeping pills because of their effectiveness and
relative safety.
   ``All have the side effects of reducing coordination and
alertness,'' Ray said, but long-acting benzodiazepines require days
to be eliminated while shorter-acting ones are largely eliminated
in hours.
   He estimated thousands of hip fractures could be prevented each
year if older people stopped using the long-acting drugs.
   Ray's team studied all the hip fractures reported among people
65 and older between 1977 and 1985 in Saskatchewan, Canada, an area
chosen because its health-care system has unusually complete
records.
   The researchers compared use of benzodiazepine tranquilizers and
sleeping pills among 4,501 victims of hip fracture and a control
group of 24,041 Canadians matched for comparison.
   Ray said patients should be encouraged to seek non-drug
alternatives that will help them relax or sleep, such as reducing
caffeine intake, getting more exercise and going to bed later.
   Three drugs accounted for 95 percent of the long-acting
medications taken by study subjects: diazepam, marketed as Valium;
flurazepam, marketed as Dalmane; and chlordiazepoxide, marketed as
Librium. All are manufactured by Roche Laboratories of Nutley, N.J.
   Nancy Mattison, a spokeswoman for Roche, said Thursday, ``It's
been generally recognized that there are some adverse effects like
this on the elderly.''
   But side effects of the short-acting drugs are less well-known
and less predictable than those of longer-acting ones, she said.
   ``Research needs to be completed to identify geriatric patients
that may be at highest risk of hip fracture at the same time as
taking benzodiazepines,'' Ms. Mattison said.
   Short-acting benzodiazepines that accounted for 95 percent of
those taken by subjects in the study were: triazolam, marketed as
Halcion by the Upjohn Co. of Kalamazoo, Mich.; oxazepam, marketed
as Serax by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories of Phildelphia; and
lorazepam, marketed as Ativan by Wyeth-Ayerst.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
