<DOCNO> AP891215-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RitterInvestigation     12-15 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ritter Investigation,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ritter Denies Allegations by Male Prostitute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former prostitute who accused the priest who
founded a runaway shelter of financial and sexual improprieties is
welcome to come back in off the streets, the Rev. Bruce Ritter said
after denying the charges.
   ``If he came back today we would welcome him back to Convenant
House,'' Ritter said at a news conference Thursday. ``There are
many people here who care very deeply about him.''
   Prosecutor Robert Morgenthau confirmed Wednesday he was
investigating the man's charges of financial improprieties by
Ritter. The 20-year-old former Covenant House resident also
reportedly claimed he had a sexual relationship with the Franciscan
priest.
   ``I categorically deny these allegations,'' Ritter said. ``They
are simply nonsense.''
   Ritter and the authorities have not publicly identified the man,
but a law enforcement source identified him as Timothy Warner.
   Ritter said the charges were ``deeply offensive to me,'' and had
seriously harmed the image of the charitable organization. An
audit, he said, ``found our books in perfect order. Every penny is
accounted for.''
   Ritter founded Covenant House for homeless teen-agers in 1969
and has built it into an $85 million-a-year operation with seven
shelters in the United States, one in Toronto and four in Latin
America. More than 90 percent of its funding is private.
   Covenant House directly serves about 25,000 children annually,
and its national telephone line gets about a million calls for help
a year.
   Ritter said the young man came to the agency early this year
saying he was a runaway prostitute being pursued by organized crime.
   Covenant House in Manhattan currently has about 150 other
runaways in similar straits, he said. They are given special
attention and a personal mentor.
   ``I chose to become his mentor because, frankly, I had more
experience than anyone else,'' he said.
   Staff members took the man to their homes on special occasions,
and Ritter acknowledged traveling with him on a few occasions, but
said there were no sexual relations.
   The man was enrolled at Manhattan College, but eventually
dropped out and lapsed back into prostitution.
   Ritter blamed himself for not spending enough time with the
young man.
   ``We tried so very hard, and we failed,'' he said. ``It is
probably better to say that I failed. ... I thought I knew more
than I did.''
   Asked why the man would have accused him of such transgressions,
Ritter replied, ``I honestly, simply do not know.''
   He said he last spoke with the man in early November, telling
him to either go back to college or get a job. The man refused
either option and left the apartment Covenant House had provided
him on Dec. 5, he said.
   The priest said he was most concerned that supporters ``have had
their faith in me shattered,'' and would not be willing to continue
their aid.
   Ritter, who has pursued a vigorous travel schedule in recent
years despite a bout with cancer, calls Covenant House ``an
intensive care unit for dying children.''
   ``We help about one-third of the kids that come in,'' he said in
an interview last year. ``We lose the rest.''
</TEXT>
