<FIRST>r a PM-ToyotaLawsuit     12-15 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Toyota Lawsuit,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toyota Seeks to Set Aside Multimillion Dollar Award</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. and Toyota Corp. will
ask a judge to set aside a $43.2 million judgment for a woman whose
husband and two daughters burned to death in a 1982 car fire,
officials said.
   Jurors in a state district court awarded $18.2 million in actual
damages and $25 million in exemplary damages _ the largest ever
against Toyota _ to Nike Adegbite, 36, who watched as her family
and two others were killed in the fire.
   Douglas West, vice president and general counsel for Toyota
Motors in Torrance, Calif., said the company was surprised and
disappointed by Wednesday's verdict, and will ask for a new trial.
   If the judge refuses, Toyota will appeal the judgment, West said.
   Mrs. Adegbite escaped with only minor burns and cuts from the
1973 Toyota Corona station wagon when it caught fire after being
rear-ended by a van.
   Her husband, Adeyemi, 35, and her daughters, Yetunde, 7, and
Adeloa, 8 months, were killed. The van's driver, Boyo Adetoye,
received minor injuries, but his wife and child were killed.
   Mrs. Adegbite's attorney, Stan Pfeiffer, said the lawsuit
claimed Toyota was negligent in its design of the station wagon and
failed to recall it. The trial lasted six weeks.
   The attorney said Mrs. Adegbite and her family were in the back
seat of the station wagon when it was struck on a Houston highway
Sept. 26, 1982. The van's impact pushed the station wagon's
gasoline tank forward, Pfeiffer said, and the tank was punctured by
an empty spare tire carrier and a valve on the rear axle.
   Adetoye was not involved in the case because he had reached a
settlement on a similar lawsuit about a year ago, Pfeiffer said.
The settlement amount was not disclosed.
   West said Toyota has never had any other claims against the
design of the vehicle. He added the company denies any defects or
negligence in the vehicle's design.
   Lawyers on both sides expressed surprise at the size of the
judgment.
   ``We were of course surprised at the verdict _ not only by the
extraordinary amount, but that the jury decided against us,'' West
said.
   Previously, the largest award against Toyota was about $5
million, he said.
   Ms. Adegbite was surprised, too, said Pfeiffer.
   ``I think everybody was. It was an emotional moment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
