<FIRST>r a PM-RetirementHomeFire     12-15 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Retirement Home Fire,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fatal Fire Prompts New Call for Study of Va. Elderly Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that killed four retirement home
residents _ the fifth blaze in six months at a Virginia nursing or
retirement home _ renewed a call for a study of fire safety in the
state's housing for the elderly.
   The fire Thursday at Shenandoah Homes Retirement Community was
the third fatal fire there in 13 years. It injured 23 people, but
residents, rescue workers and TV cameramen ushered others to safety
in early-morning cold.
   A preliminary report on the cause of the fire probably would be
released today, said Capt. Mark Light of the Roanoke County fire
and rescue department.
   After an Oct. 5 fire killed 12 residents of a nursing home in
Norfolk, state Sen. Stanley Walker, D-Norfolk, drafted the bill
calling for the fire-safety study. Lawmakers will consider it next
year.
   ``It's sad that it takes a tragedy to get people to move,''
Walker said Thursday.
   The fire broke out shortly after 2 a.m. in a third-floor
apartment at Shenandoah Homes.
   Only the second floor of the six-story building is licensed as a
home for adults and regulated by the state. The remaining floors
are considered a boarding home because residents require less
medical care than in adult homes and nursing homes, state officials
said.
   Residents, many wearing only pajamas, streamed out of exits into
the 19-degree cold. Some were aided by wheelchairs and walkers and
others were helped by fellow residents, rescue personnel and even
TV cameramen.
   ``I left my walker, got my cane and everybody helped each other
get out,'' said Marjorie Branson, 78, wrapped in a blanket.
   ``It was just a marvel how these elderly people reacted under
pressure,'' said Ottis Burgher, administrator of the 190-occupant
facility.
   In 1976, a fire killed four residents of the Shenandoah home.
Three months earlier, a blaze started by a dropped cigarette killed
a woman.
   Fires struck a nursing home in Albemarle County on Dec. 6, a
retirement home in Charlottesville on Oct. 25 and a nursing home in
Chesapeake on June 30. The fires prompted evacuations but caused no
major injuries.
</TEXT>
