<FIRST>r i PM-Brazil     12-15 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brazil,0596</SECOND>
<UNK>Presidential Candidates Clash in TV Debate Two Days Before Vote ^By
TODD LEWAN ^Associated Press Writer</UNK>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two candidates vying to become
Brazil's first popularly elected president in nearly three decades
traded barbs and insults in a crucial nationwide debate.
   The 2{-hour showdown between Fernando Collor de Mello, a
center-right former governor, and leftist Luis Inacio Lula da Silva
comes in the stretch drive of Sunday's election. New polls show
that da Silva has erased a 15-point deficit in the last two weeks
to make the race almost dead even.
   Both candidates ducked questions about inflation, expected to
rise 50 percent in December alone. Instead they traded personal
barbs during the debate that began Thursday and ended early today.
   Collor de Mello, shouting and shaking his fists in the air at
times, called his socialist rival ``intolerant'' and ``backward''
and said the election of da Silva would prompt nationwide strikes
and economic chaos.
   Da Silva labeled Collor de Mello as ``emotionally unstable'' and
a member of the ``archaic upper class.''
   Da Silva, 44, a congressman of the Workers Party and former
labor leader, instead focused on issues such as redistribution of
land and wealth and state-funded health care and educational
reforms.
   Da Silva said if elected he would suspend payments on Brazil's
$110 billion foreign debt, the Third World's largest, and invest
the money for social programs.
   Brazil paid $14 billion last year servicing its foreign debt,
according to the Central Bank.
   Collor de Mello, 40, the scion of a wealthy political clan and
former governor of the tiny northeastern state of Alagoas, said a
debt moratorium would hurt foreign investment and stunt economic
growth.
   Instead, the National Reconstruction Party candidate favored
cuts in state spending and supported making several state-run
companies private.
   ``The idea of turning our backs on our debt is flawed,'' Collor
de Mello said. ``The present government has already stopped
payments and where has it gotten us?''
   Brazil has effectively halted all interest payments on its
commercial debt since September.
   Da Silva called land reform and housing programs essential for
development in Brazil.
   He said his government would donate plots of land to homeless
families in cities and subsidize the construction of homes. He did
not specify how the government _ strapped with an enormous internal
debt and the burden of paying a bloated government staff _ would
pay for these projects.
   Collor de Mello proposed offering incentives to private
developers to ease the housing cruch.
   On Sunday, an estimated 82 million voters will go to the polls
to choose Brazil's first popularly elected president since 1960.
   Analysts say the election rides on how well each candidate
portrays himself as the defender of the poor, who make up a
majority of the electorate.
   Collor de Mello's promises to clean up corrupt government and
sharp attacks on discredited President Jose Sarney have been
popular with poor Brazilians and gave him a plurality but not the
required majority in elections last month.
   In the last two weeks, opinion polls say da Silva has closed the
gap rapidly, in part because of a strong performance in the
candidates' first nationwide debate Dec. 3.
   The last popular election for president was in 1960, when Janio
Quadros was elected. In 1964, the armed forces took power in a coup
and ruled the country until 1985.
   Sarney, a civilian, was chosen in an electoral college vote
coordinated by the country's top generals.
</TEXT>
