<FIRST>r a PM-ExhaustDeaths     12-15 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exhaust Deaths,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Bus Passes By as Three Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILIPPI, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man, his adopted teen-age daughter and
her friend succumbed to carbon monoxide poisoning as they waited in
a car for a school bus that passed without stopping to help them,
authorities said.
   James Richard McClain, 42, had driven his daughter, Misty, 15,
and her friend, Billy Payne, 16, to a bus stop Thursday to wait for
the regular 7 a.m. bus, Barbour County Sheriff Guy Steerman said.
   All three apparently had lost consciousness by the time the bus
stopped on U.S. 119 and moved on at 7:22 a.m., Steerman said.
   Jeff Maxson, owner of Maxson's Salvage, a service station where
the car was parked, said the 1977 Pontiac station wagon was
``steamed up'' and covered with a thin layer of snow when he and a
co-worker found the bodies at about 8 a.m. as they opened for
business.
   ``It was pretty cold and they lived up the hollow and he
(McClain) just brought them down for the bus as he did every day,''
Steerman said. ``They usually had to wait about seven or eight
minutes, but the bus got hung up on a secondary road by the snow
and the slick roads and it was late approximately 20 minutes.''
   Steerman and Maxson said those aboard the school bus apparently
did not aid the three even though they waited in the same car every
day at the service station.
   ``They was supposed to stop and look but the car was steamed up
so bad they couldn't see in it,'' Maxson said.
   ``I thought he was asleep,'' Maxson said. ``I beat on the
windows ... and tried to get them awake. I shoved the guy and he
wouldn't wake up. I hollered at him and called him by name.''
   Steerman said he believed the fatal fumes came from a rusted
exhaust pipe.
   Misty McClain had been adopted earlier this year, authorities
said.
   Steerman said authorities were ``pretty sure'' the deaths were
caused by carbon monoxide poisoning, and did not know whether an
autopsy was planned.
   Philippi, a town of about 3,100 people, is about 120 miles south
of Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
