<DOCNO> AP891215-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0516EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Cocaine-HairTests     12-15 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine-Hair Tests,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Hair Sample Better Than Urine Sample for Detecting Drug Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tests to detect cocaine use should be done on
hair samples as well as urine samples because a hair analysis will
detect drug abuse months afterward, a study published today says.
   But an editorial accompanying the study in the Journal of the
American Medical Association said hair analysis is unreliable and
unwieldy.
   The study said hair sampling cannot completely replace urine
testing since it won't detect cocaine use in ``the recent few
days'' as urinalysis does, but hair analysis can uncover whether
someone has long used drugs.
   ``While a urine test may be negative, this hair test will make
it very difficult to hide a history of drug use,'' Dr. Gideon
Koren, an author of the study, said in a telephone interview
Thursday.
   Koren and colleagues at The Hospital for Sick Children in
Toronto did an analysis in 1987 of urine and hair samples from 21
healthy adults who reported no cocaine use.
   They compared results of the test with an analysis of urine and
hair samples from seven pregnant admitted cocaine users who got
prenatal counseling at the Motherisk Clinic in Toronto and nine
cocaine addicts from the medical ward at the Addiction Research
Foundation in Toronto.
   Urine samples from the groups tested negative.
   Hair tests for the users, some of whom participated in a
treatment program and had quit, reflected that they had once used
the drug but later had quit, Koren said.
   ``If an adult chooses to stop taking the drug several days
before the (urine) test _ and chooses to tell you that he didn't
use the drug _ there is no way you can tell,'' said Koren, an
author of the study. ``But there is one place in the body where
cocaine gets in and does not know how to get out, and that's the
hair.''
   In the editorial, however, Dr. David N. Bailey of the University
of California School of Medicine said hair analysis is ``unwieldy
for use by most laboratories other than research laboratories.''
   He questioned the reliability of hair analysis, saying dyeing or
bleaching hair could taint test results, as could exposure to
automobile exhaust fumes or other substances that might cause the
drugs to deteriorate.
   ``While, at first glance, this practice may seem to be an
efficacious one, it likely will not become standard for some time,
if at all,'' he said.
   Koren said he has heard that hair analysis is being used on the
West Coast of the United States by a firm which does testing for
industries. He had no other information and said he had seen no
previous studies on the method.
   In the test, a hair sample is subjected to a chemical process
called radioimmunoassay, which reduces it to a solution that can be
analyzed for a cocaine derivative.
   ``Hair grows about 1 centimeter per month, so we can tell if
someone stopped the cocaine a couple of months ago _ the new hair
near the scalp will not have the cocaine anymore,'' Koren said.
   He said the researchers' main target was to find a way of
determining drug use in pregnant women who do not admit it.
   ``If there is a baby that looks very sick or has problems that
cannot be explained by other factors, we can tell with this test,''
he said. ``This means that in the future, if we find cocaine in the
hair of a baby, even if the mother does not admit using it, that
means she did use it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Judge-Sentencing     12-15 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge-Sentencing,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disclosure Shows Judges' Resentment of New Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new federal drug law that imposes
mandatory prison sentences is drawing complaints from California
judges who say their authority is being undermined.
   ``I don't think it's the world's most popular thing with
judges,'' said William Ingram, chief federal judge for the Northern
District of California.
   ``We get in this business and over the years presumably develop
some educated discretion with respect to disposition of criminal
cases, and that just takes discretion away. You have to comply with
the statute, but I think many judges wish the statute would be
repealed.''
   Two weeks ago, the issue came to a boil in the courtroom of U.S.
District Judge Robert Schnacke, a former longtime federal
prosecutor and 1970 judicial appointee of President Richard Nixon.
   The case was one where a crack cocaine prosecution in state
court, with a maximum 12-year sentence, was transferred by
prosecutors to federal court where penalties are stiffer _ in this
case, a mandatory life term without parole because of defendant
David Hamilton's two prior convictions.
   As jurors prepared to deliberate, Schnacke said he would
normally tell them to ignore possible penalties because those were
up to him. But since he had no choice of sentence, he said, they
should know that a conviction would be punished by life without
parole.
   On Dec. 1, the jury acquitted Hamilton, 30, of San Francisco, of
the drug charge, convicting him only of a gun-possession charge
that has yet to be sentenced. Schnacke thanked the jurors ``for
what I take to be an expression of concern about the nature of the
compelled sentencing process that Congress has imposed upon the
courts.''
   The new federal drug law, effective last November, requires
prison sentences without parole for certain types of drug crimes _
decisions that were formerly left up to the sentencing judge.
   A first offender who possessed over 50 grams of crack cocaine
for sale, for example, must serve at least 10 years without parole.
With a prior felony drug conviction, the minimum sentence is 20
years, and with two prior drug felonies the mandatory sentence is
life without the possibility of parole.
   ``Mandatory minimum (sentences) applied to some kinds of cases
result in shocking injustice,'' said federal Judge William
Schwarzer. ``Judges are going to struggle to find ways to perform
their sworn constitutional duty to do justice.''
   Federal judges at all levels in the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals, which covers California and eight other Western states,
voted overwhelmingly earlier this year to urge Congress to repeal
the mandatory sentencing laws.
   But U.S. Attorney Joseph Russoniello said Schnacke's action was
unprecedented and had virtually dictated the verdict, although
Hamilton's lawyer quoted jurors as saying the prosecution had
failed to prove drug possession. Russoniello complained to U.S.
Solicitor General Kenneth Starr, but conceded there was nothing he
could do because an acquittal cannot be appealed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
