<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0542EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AngeloTrial     12-15 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angelo Trial,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurse Faces 50 Years to Life for Deaths of Patients</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors wept as they heard the testimony
of a patient who survived a dose of a paralyzing drug from a
hospital nurse, then convicted Richard Angelo for causing four
deaths.
   Angelo stared straight ahead Thursday during the reading of the
verdict finding him guilty of murder in two deaths, manslaughter in
a third and criminally negligent homicide in a fourth.
   ``What this guy did to all of these people is beyond words,''
said a sobbing Kieran Greene, 24, whose father, Anthony, was one of
Angelo's victims. Greene hugged prosecutor John Collins after the
verdict was announced.
   Angelo, 27, faces a maximum of 50 years to life for the murders
when sentenced Jan. 17.
   Less than an hour before the verdict, jurors in the eighth day
of deliberations listened to testimony by former patient Gerolamo
Kucich, a 75-year-old Yugoslavian.
   ``I was actually putting myself in his shoes,'' juror Michael
Loguercio said of Kucich. ``I walked out of there in tears this
morning.''
   Kucich testified during the trial that while he was a patient
Angelo had given him an injection saying it would ``make me feel
better.'' Instead, Kucich was left fighting for breath.
   ``This is probably a fair verdict,'' said defense attorney Eric
Naiburg.
   The injections, lethal doses of muscle relaxants, occurred at
Good Samaritan Hospital in West Islip on Long Island in the fall of
1987.
   Angelo, who was a nurse in the intensive care unit for about six
months, admitted to police he had planned to inject the patients,
then be first on the scene to revive them and be seen as a hero.
   The jury also convicted Angelo on Thursday of assault charges in
the deaths and in the injections he gave Kucich. He was acquitted
of assaulting two patients whose deaths were not proved to be from
the drugs.
   Naiburg had conceded in his closing statement that Angelo
injected the patients and that he may have caused some of their
deaths. But he had argued that Angelo was not aware that the
injections presented a grave risk to the patients, a condition
necessary for a murder conviction.
   He had urged the jurors to find Angelo guilty of criminally
negligent homicide, a lesser charge punishable by up to four years
in jail.
   The prosecutor, John Collins, calling Angelo ``a monster in
nurse's whites,'' had argued that Angelo had to know the risks
involved, especially after the first victim died.
   Suffolk County officials exhumed 33 bodies of patients at Good
Samaritan who died suspiciously during Angelo's tenure. The medical
examiner found traces of Pavulon in six of the bodies exhumed. A
Pavulon-laced syringe was found in Angelo's apartment the day
before his arrest.
   County Court Judge Alfred Tisch remanded Angelo without bail
Thursday to the county jail, where he has been held since his
arrest.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
