<DOCNO> AP891215-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CleanerCars     12-15 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cleaner Cars,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan for More Smog-Free Cars Approved in California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Air Resources Board has approved a
plan that could lead to widescale use of alternative fuels in
California vehicles after 1997.
   The proposed requirements _ would have major implications for
auto makers and oil companies, as well as for consumers _ go far
beyond 1994 emission limits for conventional gasoline-powered cars
that were adopted in June.
   The new regulations would probably require use of such fuels as
methanol, compressed natural gas and electricity. New emission
control technologies would also be required.
   ``This is the first time we've started to wean people away from
gasoline and cars as we know them,'' Air Resources Board spokesman
Bill Sessa said Thursday.
   The limits were contained in a board staff proposal that would
have to be approved by the board next September.
   Without a new generation of motor vehicles, the board said,
Southern California air will not be able to meet federal clean air
standards.
   Beginning in 1997, one out of every four cars sold in the state
would have to emit 70 percent fewer hydrocarbons than required by
the 1994 standard, under the proposal. By 1998, half of all cars
sold would be required to meet the tougher standard.
   In effect, this would mean two tailpipe standards _ one for
conventional gasoline cars, based on the 1994 standard, and another
for so-called ``low-emission cars,'' which the state would require
to be sold in California.
   The 1997 standard limits hydrocarbon emissions to 0.075 grams
per mile. The 1994 standard limits them to 0.25 grams per mile.
   Federal standards now set hydrocarbon limits at 0.41 grams per
mile. Over time, the market share of low-emission cars would grow
from less than 10 percent in 1994 to 100 percent of new cars sold
in the year 2000, officials said.
   Oil companies would be required to sell alternative fuels at
their service stations as a condition for continuing to sell
gasoline in the state. Automobile makers would be required to make
the lower-emission vehicles in order to meet the tougher standards.
   Industry representatives said the proposed timetable was
unrealistically fast and may not be technologically feasible.
   The Air Quality Management District, which regulates air quality
in the Los Angeles area, said that next year it will consider a
rule requiring operators of fleets of more than 15 vehicles to
begin purchasing alternative, cleaner-fueled vehicles.
   The district's goal is to have 40 percent of all cars, 70
percent of all trucks and 100 percent of buses running on cleaner
fuels by 2000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
