<SECOND>PM-Kettle Caper,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Admits Swiping Salvation Army Kettle Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager who claimed he was beaten and
robbed while tending a Salvation Army Christmas kettle has admitted
he took the money and fabricated the story, authorities said.
   The 17-year-old took the money Dec. 4 and spent some of it on
taxi fare and a ticket to a rock concert two days later, police
said.
   ``It breaks your heart and kind of takes some of the spirit out
of Christmas,'' said Capt. Robert Hartsook, area manager for the
Salvation Army. ``It's theft any way you look at it.''
   Hartsook said the boy also spent some of the money on a coat.
   ``He did a stupid thing. All he had to do was call me and say,
`Hey, Captain, I need a coat.' I could have helped,'' Hartsook said.
   The boy admitted to fabricating the story when detectives
questioned him Thursday, police said. Detective Capt. R.E. Bingman
said charges are pending.
   The youngster's name was being withheld because he is a juvenile.
   Police said they received a tip from someone who said the boy
was seen exchanging a large number of coins for paper money.
   Hartsook said the boy apologized and agreed to make restitution,
but ``he'll never work for the Salvation Army again.''
   He also said he hoped the incident would not deter people from
donating to the organization's traditional Christmas fund-raising
drive.

