<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0651EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Autopsies     12-15 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Autopsies,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Tests to be Done on NYC Autopsies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every autopsy at the New York City medical
examiner's office will include an AIDS test in an effort to inform
other people if they may be infected with the virus, according to a
published report today.
   The test results will be used in statistical research and in
``contact-tracing,'' the tracking of an AIDS sufferer's sexual
partners or drug-needle sharers, The New York Times said.
   Officials at the Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta said
they were unaware of any other such program in the country.
   About 8,000 autopsies are performed every year by the medical
examiner's office. Dr. Charles S. Hirsch, the chief medical
examiner, said he expected to detect the AIDS virus in about 1,000
of the autopsies.
   The testing has been approved by Mayor Edward I. Koch and was
authorized Monday by the medical examiner's advisory board.
   The results and the names of people who have been contacted will
be kept confidential.
   Hirsch said testing would begin by year's end after he discussed
the program with groups involved with AIDS issues.
   Some people have expressed concern that contact-tracing may lead
to invasion of privacy.
   But Stephen C. Joseph, the city's health commissioner, denied
that.
   ``What argument can anyone make to not warn the unsuspecting
partner of someone who is dead?'' he said. ``It's very compelling _
the absolute need to warn people at risk who might not learn any
other way.''
   He said the program will be useful in evaluating the extent of
the virus's spread in the city and be an ``extremely useful tool
for epidemiologic control and prevention.''
   There are 75,000 deaths every year in New York City. Autopsies
are carried out for unusual or unexplained deaths, and are required
in homicides, suicides and deaths from drug overdose.
   Many of those who die for unexplained reasons are believed to
carry the AIDS virus, particularly intravenous drug users.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
