<DOCNO> AP891215-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Congress     12-15 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Congress,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Congress Reconvenes, Deputies to Decide on Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>PM-Obit-Sakharov, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Congress briefly halted work on
reforming the economy today to pay tribute to Andrei D. Sakharov,
the colleague who was the ruling Communist Party's most severe
critic.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and the 2,250 members of the
Congress of People's Deputies stood for a moment of silence to
remember the scientist whose challenge to the Kremlin's human
rights policies led to nearly seven years of internal exile.
   The 68-year-old physicist, who died Thursday night in his Moscow
apartment, was the ``people's conscience,'' said Boris N. Yeltsin,
the maverick deputy who along with Sakharov was a leader of a group
considering whether to form an alternative political party.
   ``All honest people in the U.S.S.R. and throughout the world
will grieve for him,'' Yeltsin said.
   At the time of his death, the Nobel Peace Prize winner was
preparing a speech he was to give to Congress demanding that the
Communists' constitutional guarantee on power be revoked, a move
made by Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Hungary in recent weeks.
   In other developments in Eastern Europe:
   _ East Germany has established its first contacts with the
International Monetary Fund. West Germany's foreign minister,
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, says in an interview published today that
``closer ties between the two German states contribute to stability
in Europe.''
   _ In Sofia, Bulgaria, up to 50,000 people jeered and whistled
Thursday outside that hall where Parliement delayed legally
repealing the Communist monopoly on power.
   _ Elsewhere, NATO foreign ministers meeting in Brussels today
endorsed a plan to allow unarmed military jets from Eastern bloc
countries to fly over their territory as part of efforts to further
reduce East-West military tensions.
   Vitaly I. Vorotnikov, a member of the Presidium of the Congress,
opened today's session by announcing the death of Sakharov, who won
the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his human rights work. Vorotnikov
paid tribute to Sakharov both as a scientist and public figure.
   ``All that he did was dictated by his sleepless conscience, his
deep humanitarian convictions,'' said Vorotnikov, a member of the
ruling Communist Party Politburo and president of the Russian
Federation.
   Dmitri Likhachev, another scholar-deputy, told the chamber,
``With Sakharov, a part of our heart has departed from us. We could
agree or disagree with him, but he was a man of absolute sincerity
and absolute purity, and this led him to achievements in sicence
and his position in public life.''
   The course of Sakharov's independent group of delegates, the
400-member Inter-Regional Deputies Group, was unclear.
   A strike that Sakharov tried to organize Monday had fizzled, and
deputies outvoted the independents to cut off debate on possibly
changing an article of the Soviet Constitution that guaranteed the
Communist Party's role as the leading force in society.
   Sakharov and historian Yuri Afanasyev said in an emotional
three-hour meeting Thursday that it was time to call for a
multiparty democratic system. Sakharov said Thursday that Gorbachev
and the Communist Party leadership were ``leading the country to
catastrophe, prolonging the process of perestroika many years.''
   Thursday's meeting came as the Congress began dissecting the
government's blueprint for economic reform, with progressives
complaining that it was not daring enough to improve the country's
grim financial condition.
   Premier Nikolai Ryzhkov announced Wednesday that the Kremlin
believes it can revive the economy without resorting to such
radical moves as legalization of private property and selling off
money-losing state enterprises.
   Progressives in Congress reacted with scorn to Ryzhkov's speech,
which promised five more years of bureaucratic control of such
mundane details of life as the number of eggs produced per person.
   The government proposal does shift the emphasis of traditional
central planning away from heavy industry to consumer goods and
services. Such enterprises are to quadruple in the next five-year
plan, from 1991-1996.
</TEXT>
