<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     12-15 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington in Brief,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gonzalez Pledges to Reform Fed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Banking Committee chairman says he
will begin an effort to reform the Federal Reserve Board, saying
the ``splendid isolation'' of the central bank ``won't continue
forever.''
   ``I recognize the need to give the Federal Reserve room to
operate and make objective judgments,'' Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez,
D-Texas, a longtime critic of the Fed, said Thursday.
   ``But, this doesn't have to mean ... (it) operates as some
separate government, free to veto economic policy spelled out by
the administration, the Congress _ and the American people at the
voting booths.''
   On another matter, Gonzalez prodded President Bush to
re-evaluate the administration's ``Pollyannaish'' view that a $50
billion savings and loan bailout is sufficient.
   Bush suggested earlier this week that the $50 billion the
government is borrowing to close S&amp;Ls through September 1991 may
fall short. However, a day later, his spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater,
backtracked, saying the president had no plans to ask Congress for
more money.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>College Presidents Urged to Back NCAA Disclosure Plan</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidents of colleges and universities with
NCAA programs are being urged to support a proposal requiring
disclosure of graduation rates among athletes as an alternative to
a government-mandated program.
   ``Federal intrusion in this area would set a very dangerous
precedent and would open a door that we will never be able to close
again,'' James Whalen, chairman of the American Council on
Education board of directors, said Thursday.
   Whalen said that if the proposal is not approved at the NCAA
annual meeting Jan. 7-9, ``the Congress of the United States will
do it for us.''
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., and Rep. Tom McMillen, D-Md., are
sponsoring legislation that would require colleges to disclose how
many of their athletes graduate.
   Bradley and McMillen, both former professional basketball
players, contend the legislation would improve education standards
for college athletes and provide students and their parents with
valuable information about the school they plan to attend.
   Whalen, president of New York's Ithaca College, said the
proposal has little chance of passing unless the majority of the
presidents attend the meeting. Many presidents have traditionally
sent a representative, such as the athletic director.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Accord Reached on $15.2 Billion in Loans for Poorest Countries</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and 31 other governments
have agreed on $15.2 billion worth of easy loans for more than 50
of the world's poorest countries over a three-year period.
   ``Ninety percent of the money will go to countries where the
average annual income is $400 a year or less,'' said World Bank
President Barber B. Conable on Thursday.
   The money will come from the 32 countries with the United States
furnishing the largest share. The total U.S. contribution was put
at $3.18 billion by George A. Folsum, deputy assistant secretary of
the treasury for developing nations.
   Conable said he expects President Bush to ask Congress for the
first $1.08 billion in his next budget, early in the new year. The
overall package of loan money will be available starting next July
1.
   For the previous three years, the United States made the same
contribution.
   The new money will be lent out by the bank's International
Development Association for as long as 40 years, at only nominal
interest. With repayments made on loans from earlier years, the
bank expects to have to have about $5.5 billion a year for this
type of loan, Conable said.
   Japan's contribution will be a close second: $3.05 billion at
the exchange rate Folsum used, up from $2.76 billion for the
previous three years.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Wetlands Agreement Between EPA and Corps of Engineers May Be</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Delayed
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An EPA spokeswoman says a planned agreement
between the Environmental Protection Agency and the Army Corps of
Engineers aimed at carrying out President Bush's campaign pledge to
preserve wetlands may be put on hold for 30 days.
   The memorandum of agreement, which was scheduled to take effect
today, has sparked an intense struggle within the administration.
The departments of Energy and Transportation oppose it and the
Council on Environmental Quality and the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration favor it.
   Congressional sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, also
said the Interior Department has split, with the Fish and Wildlife
Service favoring immediate implementation and the Minerals
Management Service opposed.
   Environmentalists are keeping a close watch on the dispute,
which has been growing since EPA and the Corps initialled the new
agreement early last month.
   ``I think this is a real litmus test of Bush's commitment to
wetlands protection,'' said Jan Goldman-Carter, counsel to the
National Wildlife
   In last year's presidential campaign, Bush endorsed a policy of
``No net loss'' of wetlands like swamps, bogs, fens, marshes and
tidal estuaries, often craved for residential, commercial and
agricultural development. The goal emerged from recommendations of
the Conservation Foundation, whose then head, William Reilly, was
appointed EPA administrator by Bush.
   In recent years, environmentalists have come to recognize the
value of these areas for wildlife habitat, purification of polluted
waterways, flood control and other purposes.
