<SECOND>PM-Producer Flees,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hollywood Producer Facing Abuse Charges Flees Courthouse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Hollywood producer charged with soliciting
children for sex fled from a courthouse after learning he was about
to be arrested on a second, similar complaint, his lawyer said.
   A judge revoked David MacLeod's $6,000 bail and issued a warrant
for his arrest after he disappeared Thursday.
   ``I'm waiting for a call when he comes to his senses. This isn't
a guy to be a fugitive,'' MacLeod's lawyer, Barry Asness, said
later Thursday. He said MacLeod apparently panicked at the thought
of being returned to jail.
   MacLeod, 45, who produced ``The Pick-Up Artist'' in 1987 and was
an associate producer of ``Ishtar'' the same year, was arrested
Dec. 8 on charges of criminal solicitation and endangering
children. Police alleged he had been cruising housing projects in
the Bronx and Brooklyn boroughs of New York, offering boys money
for sex.
   He appeared at state Supreme Court in the Bronx with his lawyer
Thursday for a routine hearing. But he learned that police from the
Queens borough were there to arrest him on similar charges. Before
his case was called, MacLeod said he was going out to make a
telephone call and never returned, Asness said.
   MacLeod had been held for three days after his last arrest
because of processing delays in the overloaded jail system, and was
harassed by other prisoners because of the nature of the charges
against him, Asness said.
   ``For three days this guy was in hell,'' he said. ``He feared
that again.''
