<FIRST>r a PM-EastGermany-US     12-15 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East Germany-US,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Leader Asks U.S. to Help Keep Germanys Separate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new leader of East Germany's Communist Party
said the United States should work to keep the two Germanys
separate in the interests of Europe's stability, The New York Times
reported today.
   Gregor Gysi, chairman of the once-dominant party, said in an
interview Thursday that if East Germany were united with the more
powerful West Germany, his country would become ``the poorhouse''
of the new country.
   But if unification is to happen, he said, ``It should happen
quickly _ and simply.''
   Gysi, a 41-year-old lawyer, was elected Communist Party chairman
Saturday. The party relinquished its monopoly on power last month.
   Gysi told the Times the United States should not give up its
responsibilities in Europe.
   ``If the continued independence of the German Democratic
Republic is in the interests of stability in Europe, then you
should think about whether you want to leave help for the GDR up to
a single neighbor country, and thereby create dependency, or
whether it wouldn't be better to share the responsibility, to
prevent the re-emergence of greater Germany,'' he said.
   Gysi said the absorption of East Germany into what he described
as greater Germany would create a dangerous economic imbalance in
Western Europe and lead to right-wing nationalistic fervor. He said
that frenzy could lead to demands that borders established after
World War II be realigned to include former German territories now
in Poland.
   ``I am utterly against a special German solution before such a
process of European unification is completed,'' Gysi said.
</TEXT>
