<FIRST>u i PM-France-Comoros 1stLd-Writethru a0481 12-15 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Comoros, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0481,0571</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Troops Land on Comoros; Merenaries Reported Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with mercenaries reported out. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French troops landed today on the Comoros Islands,
taking control of the country's security in what the Defense
Ministry called a military mission requested by the Comoros
government.
   Four hours later, French mercenary Bob Denard and about 25 other
European soldiers of fortune who trained and led the 600-member
Comoran Presidential Guard boarded a South African military plane
and left for South Africa, Agence France-Presse reported. No
violence was reported during the French operation.
   The French government said earlier that the mercenaries had
offered to relinquish control of the country, but it was unclear
whether an agreement was reached and if so, what terms were offered.
   A military spokesman said the soldiers came from the French
Indian Ocean island of Mayotte, 185 miles away, under a ``defense
cooperation agreement between France and the Comoros.'' France once
controlled the Comoros Islands.
   Both President Francois Mitterrand and Defense Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement had stressed earlier this week that there
would be no French military intervention in the Comoros.
   The islands off southeast African have been in turmoil since the
Nov. 26 assassination of President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane.
   AFP, the French news agency, said from Comoran capital, Moroni,
that 50 French paratroopers in helicopters landed to take over
control of the archipelago from the Presidential Guard. They were
followed by two transport planes full of troops.
   Denard and the Presidential Guard had been in control of the
islands since the president's assassination.
   At one end of the runway, 250 men of the Presidential Guard
stood at attention along with Denard dressed in civilian clothes,
awaiting the change of control, AFP reported.
   About 25 of the French troops, accompanied by the French
military attache in Moroni, approached Denard and his men and,
after a brief conversation, the chief mercenary left the area, AFP
said.
   On Thursday, AFP said Denard was willing to relinquish control
if the safety of his men was guaranteed and if he and his fellow
mercenaries were given an unspecified payment. It was unclear if
those demands were honored.
   The Johannesburg Star said South African officials planned to
issue Denard a temporary residence permit on condition he agreed to
leave within a month.
   Most Comorans believe Denard and his mercenaries, who first put
Abdallah into power in 1978, were responsible for his death. Denard
has denied killing the president, but he admitted during a news
conference that he was in the room when the shooting occurred.
   Denard, a veteran soldier of fortune in several Asian and
African conflicts, claimed that Abdallah was shot accidentally by a
bodyguard.
   Six French and Belgian mercenaries left Moroni on Thursday night
on the Air France flight for Paris, accompanied by wives and other
family members, AFP reported. They rest left today, the agency said.
   The intervention by the French, the former colonial power, ``a
matter of an express request by the Comoran authorities,'' said the
Defense Ministry in Paris. ``It is a takeover from the Presidential
Guard.''
   Both France and South Africa, the biggest aid suppliers to the
Comoros, had cut off assistance and were putting strong pressure on
Denard and his men to leave. Negotiations had been going on for the
past several days.
</TEXT>
