<HEAD>Judge's Phone Number Broadcast on 700 Club</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who was barraged with phone calls when
the Christian Broadcasting Network telecast her office phone number
nationwide said it will not help reduce the sentence she gave the
deputy director of Operation Rescue.
   Fulton County State Court Judge Thelma Wyatt Cummings had
sentenced Michael McMonagle to six months in jail after he refused
to pay a $1,000 fine after being convicted of obstructing a public
sidewalk during an abortion protest.
   ``If you believe that harassing telephone calls and harassing
letters with pictures of dead babies will cause me to modify your
sentence, you are mistaken,'' she told McMonagle Thursday.
   ``I believe that if you file a proper motion for modification, I
will consider it in proper fashion,'' the judge said. ``This is
having the opposite effect to what I believe you desire.''
   CBN reporter Ty Bragg presented a feature on the trials of
opponents of legalized abortion in Atlanta on Thursday morning's
``700 Club'' show. He supplied Cummings' number and encouraged
viewers to call and complain about the sentence given McMonagle.
   The judge said her secretary reported that calls were coming in
at the rate of one per minute.
   Cummings also was upset by a statement in Bragg's report that a
child pornographer had received a lighter sentence than McMonagle.
   ``I have not had a child pornography case in my 12 years on the
bench,'' Cummings said.
   Frankie Abourjilie, vice president of public relations for the
Virginia Beach, Va.-based CBN, said McMonagle had no control over
the show.
   McMonagle represented himself on a charge of obstructing a
public sidewalk or passageway during a November trial. The charge
stemmed from a demonstration in October 1988 at the Feminist
Women's Health Center. McMonagle was directing protesters with a
bullhorn when he was arrested.
