<FIRST>r w PM-Communists-Dissenters 1stLd-Writethru a0433 12-15 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Communists-Dissenters, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0433,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Keeping the Ideological Fires Burning</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Deletes superfluous words ``any of'' 13th graf, The Sandinistas.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crumbling of communist rule in Eastern
Europe is prompting some to proclaim that history, at least in
terms of ideological struggle, is over and the championship belt
goes to democratic capitalism.
   Not so fast, say dissenters on the left. History is not over by
a long shot. Don't count Marxism out just yet.
   In the United States, longtime U.S. Communist Party leader Gus
Hall yearns for the good old days when the Soviet Union was less
inclined toward revisionist thought.
   Hall was so incensed at the irreverent views of a leading Soviet
reform organ, Moscow News, that he urged his allies in the
birthplace of Lenin to have the editor removed.
   Otherwise, said Hall, they could ``burn down the god-damn
building. I mean get rid of it.'' As Hall sees it, the interests of
class struggle preclude capitalism's right to exist. Hall also had
no patience with pro-democracy demonstrators in China, finding them
entirely too pro-American.
   Hall's views may seem increasingly quaint in a world where
Marxists increasingly are on the defensive, but the far left does
not give up easily.
   In this hemisphere, Cuban President Fidel Castro still boasts a
devout following among some of his countrymen and the leftist cause
continues to persuade many in Nicaragua and El Salvador to take up
arms.
   Don't tell the Salvadoran rebels that democratic capitalists are
on the side of history. They see around them all the evils that
Karl Marx spoke of: exploitation, class stratification, disease,
unemployment and illiteracy.
   To these combatants, there is considerable allure to a
philosophy _ socialism _ which ``guarantees'' equality and the
right to health care, education and employment.
   The Salvadoran militants don't want to hear about the hundreds
of thousands who have been demonstrating in Prague for the past two
months demanding an end to 40 years of misrule.
   They want an end to more than a century and a half of misrule in
their own country. Obviously there are many in El Salvador who
believe that a rebel-led government would only make things worse.
   And don't tell the hard-liners within Nicaragua's leadership
about the wonders of democratic capitalism. Most of Latin America
has lived under elected civilian governments for the past decade, a
period marked by one of the steepest economic declines in the
region's history.
   The Sandinistas blame the armed uprising Washington has been
supporting for almost a decade for their inability to improve the
lot of their citizens.
   Perhaps the most irrepressible defender of the Marxist faith
these days is Castro, who believes someone must stand up for the
``thousands of millions of people in the world who live in inhuman
conditions.''
   Castro blames this state of affairs on the ``colossal looting''
of imperialist countries, led by the United States.
   Don't talk to Castro about the more than 200,000 East Germans
who have fled to West Germany this year. He'd rather talk about the
40,000 children who die each day around the world _ a Hiroshima and
a Nagasaki, as he puts it, every three days.
   Standing before a gathering of his countrymen last week, Castro
warned of the dangers of reverting to capitalist rule:
``prostitution, drugs, gambling, begging, unemployment, abysmal
inequality between citizens ... ''
   He believes communism is too young a philosophy to give up on,
especially when one considers the alternative. This notion, of
course, is being rejected by millions of East Europeans who believe
it is farfetched to suggest the flaws of Marxism can be corrected,
as Castro suggests, with mere fine tuning.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Gedda has covered foreign affairs for the
Associated Press since 1968.
</TEXT>
