<FIRST>r a PM-MissingGavel     12-15 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Missing Gavel,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gavel Disappears After Legislators Hammer Out Workers' Comp Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone has given Lt. Gov. Bill Hobby a
pounding headache by walking off with the wooden gavel he used
during a recent special session of the Texas Legislature.
   ``Who would have ever thought someone would take the gavel?''
Saralee Tiede, the lieutenant governor's executive assistant, said
Thursday. She said the gavel has been missing since legislators
left Austin earlier this week after wrapping up the session on
workers' compensation revisions.
   ``I mean, we operate on the honors system here,'' she said.
``It's kind of understood that you don't make off with the
paintings on the wall, you don't take the bronze busts and you
don't steal the gavel.''
   The oak gavel, made by Texas prison inmates, is nearly 2 feet
long and weighs about 4 pounds.
   ``It doesn't have much monetary value,'' Tiede said. ``However,
it has a lot of sentimental value at this point. We thought (Hobby)
might want to present it to someone.''
   Carleton Turner, Senate sergeant-at-arms, issued a memo to all
Senate offices Wednesday, asking staff members to look out for the
gavel.
   ``I'm not assuming any of the senators did it,'' Turner said.
``The Senate chamber is open at times when there is nobody in
there. It would have been easy for someone to slip in and take it.''
   State Sen. Carl Parker, who opposed the workers' compensation
legislation proposed by Hobby, suggested that it was ``was probably
stolen by a representative of the insurance industry who wants to
enshrine it as a holy object.''
</TEXT>
