<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-Vietnam, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0459,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees Protest Forced Repatriations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with protests in another camp.
Pickup 12th graf pvs, ``We haven't...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CINTY LI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 11,000 Vietnamese refugees who may be
forced to return to their homeland held protest marches for a third
day today and burned an effigy of British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher.
   Meanwhile, the Hong Kong's governor said no more boat people
will be sent home against their will before Christmas.
   Refugees in six camps around this British colony took part in
today's demonstrations, which have widened in scope daily since the
forced repatriation of 51 boat people on Tuesday.
   The protesters are among about 44,000 Vietnamese who have sailed
into Hong Kong since June 1988 and are considered illegal
``economic migrants'' unless they can prove they fled their
Communist homeland fearing persecution.
   Nearly 6,800 have been denied refugee status after being
screened by immigration officials and face repatriation, compared
with slightly more than 700 who have qualified for overseas
resettlement.
   Although the protests have been peaceful, about 100 Vietnamese
late Thursday attacked a prison officer with iron bars as he
investigated a crowd gathering inside the Chi Ma Wan camp. The
officer suffered minor injuries.
   Today, about 4,000 boat people marched inside the Whitehead
Detention Center in the New Territories. About 2,500 others chanted
slogans as they marched between huts in the High Island reception
center next to a rural park, the government said.
   About 550 boat people staged a sit-in at Sek Kong Detention
Center in the New Territories, 3,000 others participated in the
third day of protest marches at Hei Ling Chau camp on an outlying
island, and 1,000 Vietnamese demonstrated at Sham Shui Po Detention
Center in urban Kowloon. A few hundred protested at Chi Ma Wan.
   An effigy of Mrs. Thatcher, who has strongly defended the forced
repatriation program by this British colony, was burned at the Sham
Shui Po protest, a government spokesman said.
   Governor Sir David Wilson said today that more Vietnamese will
be sent back against their will but: ``We haven't got a flight plan
before Christmas.''
   Wilson acknowledged the program has led to widespread
international criticism, saying: ``We certainly face the fact there
has been a very emotional reaction against what we've done.''
   But he added that none of the critics has put forth a viable
alternative to solve the problem posed by the massive influx of
boat people.
   Journalists have not been allowed inside the detention centers
in recent weeks, but relief agencies say the atmosphere is tense.
   ``I think the feeling is that there is a great deal of tension
in the camps,'' said Jim Campion of Refugee Concern Hong Kong, an
advocacy group for the boat people. ``Whether that is going to
spill out or explode remains to be seen.''
   About 56,000 Vietnamese are housed in squalid camps in Hong
Kong, but only 4,500 refugees have been resettled so far this year.
Britain argues returning the refugees home is more humane than
keeping them indefinitely in crowded centers that are rife with
violence and disease.
   The United States has condemned the forced repatriation.
   The approximately 12,000 boat people in Hong Kong who arrived
before June 1988 are considered refugees eligible for resettlement.
</TEXT>
