<FIRST>r a PM-AgentsIndicted     12-15 0306</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Agents Indicted,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bail Set for Former DEA Agent Accused in Corruption-Drug Dealing
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. drug agent accused of
corruption, drug dealing and money laundering has been granted $1
million bail, but if he posts it he must stay under house arrest.
   U.S. District Judge Terry Hatter set bail Thursday over the
objections of prosecutors who maintained that former Drug
Enforcement Administration agent John Jackson was a risk to flee.
   Jackson, 40, of Claremont, could be released as soon as next
week from the downtown federal Metropolitan Detention Center. He
has been in custody since his Nov. 22, 1988 arrest.
   Jackson and two other former DEA agents, Darnell Garcia, 42, of
Rancho Palos Verdes, and Wayne Countryman, 46, of Walnut, were
charged in a 42-count indictment with trafficking cocaine and
heroin and laundering the proceeds through banks in Switzerland and
Luxembourg.
   Jackson's wife, Barbara, 41, and a former business partner,
Sherman Lair, 39, of Alta Loma, also were charged.
   Hatter ordered Jackson to be electronically monitored if he goes
free and to seek permission from parole officers to leave his home
for a doctor's visit or an emergency.
   Monitoring usually is done through a bracelet locked to the
wearer's ankle or wrist that emits a coded electronic signal.
   Jackson's lawyer, Terry Amdur, said his client was confined to
the special housing unit at the downtown Metropolitan Detention
Center, an area reserved for problem prisoners or arrested law
enforcement officers who cannot safely mix with inmates.
   Garcia, a fugitive for seven months, was arrested in Luxembourg
in July. He was sentenced to six months in jail by a Belgium court
for a passport violation, and U.S. authorities have requested his
extradition when his term ends in a few weeks.
   The trial for all the defendants has been scheduled for April.
</TEXT>
