<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1000EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Violence     12-15 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Violence,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Police, Informer Killed in Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three policemen and a police
informer were killed when a mine was detonated under their vehicle,
authorities said today.
   The incident occurred late Thursday outside Motherwell, a black
township near the Indian Ocean city of Port Elizabeth, police
headquarters in Johannesburg said. No further details were given.
   Police reported two bombings today on rail lines in the Cape
Town area, apparently related to the 6-week-old strike by 25,000
black employees of the state-owned transport company. The blasts
caused minor damage and no injuries, and one man was arrested,
police said.
   Officials of South African Transport Services said it had fired
2,400 more strikers, raising to more than 19,700 the number
dimissed during the walkout.
   Police said two children of a black spokesman for the transport
company were burned to death Thursday when their house near
Pretoria was set afire. Investigators were trying to determine if
the incident was related to the strike.
   In De Aar, in northern Cape Province, a black constable today
shot and killed a person who was part of a crowd throwing stones at
his home. In Soweto, Johannesburg's main black township, a black
man shot and wounded two policemen before he was arrested,
authorities said.
   No further details about these incidents were released.
</TEXT>
