<SECOND>PM-Toy Recall,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Orders Toy Recalled Over Choaking Hazard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today recalled more than
100,000 models of a children's playset because they contain small
parts that may present a choking hazard to young children.
   The Consumer Product Safety Commission said the manufacturer has
agreed to replace three components of the plastic ``Play to Learn''
furniture set, model 1411, made by JA-RU, Inc. of Jacksonville, Fla.
   The agency said two play figures _ a girl and a boy _ and a
plastic lounge chair included in the set are small parts which if
swallowed by young children may cause them to choke.
   Approximately 144,000 sets were sold nationwide since January
1987 but there have been no reports of injury, the commission said.
   Consumers should take the hazardous parts away from children and
request replacements by writing the manufacturer at 4030 Phillips
Highway, Jacksonville, Fla., 32217 or calling 904-733-9311.
</TEXT>
