<FIRST>r a PM-TridentLaunch     12-15 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trident Launch,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Sub Launches Third Trident 2 Missile in 11 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crew of a nuclear powered
submarine launched its third Trident 2 missile in less than two
weeks today, sending an unarmed warhead far down the Atlantic
tracking range, the Navy reported.
   The success was the fourth in six undersea firings of the
Trident 2. Three more such tests are planned, leading to
operational deployment of the weapon in March.
   Greenpeace anti-nuclear activists were not on the scene today as
the Tennessee unleashed the 44-foot, $26.5-million missile, the
Navy's newest weapon.
   On Dec. 4, a large Greenpeace vessel was rammed by a Navy ship
and two motorized rafts operated by protesters were rounded up and
escorted away when they entered the danger zone to try to stop the
launch.
   A launch was conducted on Wednesday after the Navy warned a
60-foot Greenpeace ketch out of a 5,000-yard safety zone
surrounding the submarine.
   Shannon Fagan, a Greenpeace spokesman, said Thursday the group
was leaving the area and would take its fight to Congress.
   The Navy reported the success of today's launch 10 minutes after
the 9:15 a.m. firing, which took place in the Atlantic about 50
miles offshore.
   The Tennessee will be the first of 24 Trident 2 subs to go to
sea with the missile. The submarine will carry 24 of the weapons,
each able to hurl as many as 12 nuclear warheads to individual
targets more than 4,600 miles away.
</TEXT>
