<FIRST>r w PM-Congressmen-Colombia     12-15 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congressmen-Colombia,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Returning From Secret Meeting with Colombian President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-member House delegation headed back to
the United States today after secret meetings in Colombia with
President Virgilio Barco and top aides to discuss support for
anti-drug efforts in the violence-torn nation.
   Aides said the lawmakers would brief President Bush before his
upcoming drug summit with leaders of the Andean nations in
Cartagena, Colombia, on Feb. 15.
   The two-day trip, kept secret because of concerns the
congressmen could become targets of cocaine traffickers, included
meetings with Barco as well as Colombia's defense and justice
ministers, national police director, the attorney general,
Colombian presidential candidates and U.S. Ambassador Thomas
McNamara.
   Barco met Sept. 28-29 with Bush and House leaders in Washington
to discuss American cooperation with the war on drug traffickers he
declared three months ago. The United States has asked the Colombia
government to extradite suspected traffickers indicted in this
country on drug charges.
   The delegation was led by Rep. Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y.,
chairman of the House Narcotics Abuse and Control Committee.
Members included Reps. Frank Guarini and William Hughes, both
D-N.J.; Lawrence Coughlin, R-Pa.; Benjamin A. Gilman, R-N.Y.; and
Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
   Bob Weiner, a spokesman for Rangel's committee, said the
congressmen traveled to show American support for Colombia's
anti-drug efforts as a wave of bombings and assassinations
continues. He said they also were demonstrating to Bush that they
could achieve safe passage to Colombia.
   Among those killed have been 50 judges, two newspaper
publishers, the chief of the narcotics police and a leading
presidential candidate. A bombing earlier this month wounded an
estimated 1,000 people in the capital city of Bogota.
   Hughes, who is chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee on
crime, is concerned about maintaining an ongoing dialogue with
Barco, spokesman Mark Brown said.
   ``They're taking some extraordinary actions and extraordinary
risks to handle this drug problem,'' Brown said of Colombian
officials.
   Hughes, author of a law to control diversion of drug refining
and processing chemicals, has said the flow of those chemicals and
assault weapons from the United States to Colombia has been
undermining local efforts to crack down on drug trafficking.
</TEXT>
