<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1110EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Sakharov     12-15 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Sakharov,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Obit-Sakharov</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Offers Condolences to Sahharov's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today offered his condolences
to Yelena Bonner, the wife of Soviet physicist and dissident Andrei
D.Sakharov, saying ``all of us are diminished by his utimely
death.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush sent a message
to the widow of the Nobel laureate early today.
   ``On behalf of all the American people, I would like to extend
to you and your family our deepest condolences on the death of your
husband, Dr. Sakharov,'' the message read.
   ``All of us who knew him will never forget his courage and
devotion to freedom. In the darkest hours of his struggle for human
rights in the Soviet Union, he embodied all that is good and decent
in the human spirit. He died as he lived, struggling in the Supreme
Soviet to codify in law the ideals for which he always stood.
   ``Just as he truly enriched all of us with his life, all of us
are diminished by his untimely death. Barbara joins me in sending
you our personal sympathy and prayers for this sad hour.''
   Fitzwater said the United States would send a delegation to
Sakharov's funeral, but that it had not been decided who would be
in it.
   Sakharov, who built the Soviet hydrogen bomb and became a beacon
for the world in the cause of human rights, died at age 68. The
1975 Nobel Peace Prize winner died alone in his study Thursday
night of an apparent heart attack, said his son-in-law, Yefrem
Yankelevich.
</TEXT>
