<SECOND>AM-BRF---Guard Dies,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guard Dies After Fitness Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERCURY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 58-year-old security guard at the Nevada
Test Site collapsed and died 30 minutes after a physical fitness
test.
   Authorities say Clair Robinson died after completing a half-mile
run and a 40-yard dash Thursday.
   Test site officials say Robinson had no history of medical
problems and had a physical examination in April. He was medically
certified Dec. 4 as qualified for the fitness test.
   Guards receive six chances to complete the half-mile in 4
minutes, 40 seconds, and the 40-yard dash in 8.5 seconds.
   The test site fitness test came under fire in 1985, two years
after a 59-year-old guard died of a heart attack after he ran a
mile in 88-degree heat. Two guards died after testing at Energy
Department facilities in Ohio and Washington.
   Robinson was a guard with Wackenhut Services, the private
security firm used at the test site.
   The cause of death will be determined by the Clark County
Coroner's Office.
</TEXT>
