<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina     12-15 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy Minister Resigns in Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Menem today
accepted the resignation of his economy minister, apparently in a
move to defuse political opposition to his economic program.
   Minister Nestor Rapanelli, 60, had been criticized for his
business background by the union-based governing Peronist Party.
   Menem replaced him with Erman Gonzalez, a former Central Bank
vice president and minister of social affairs. Gonzalez is a
longtime confidant of Menem and is held in esteem by rank-and-file
Peronists.
   Julio Mera Figueroa, Menem's former campaign chairman, was named
interior minister to replace Eduardo Bauza, who became the new
minister of health.
   Rapanelli's resignation had been anticipated after the economy
did not respond to a 34.5 percent devaluation of the austral this
week.
   Menem scheduled a news conference at which he was expected to
discuss the changes and to defend his 5-month-old government's
program of privatization and deregulation to stabilize Argentina's
economy.
   Gonzalez's appointment was expected to appeal to organized labor
and other factions of the Peronist Party that disagree with Menem's
plans to reduce state spending, sell public companies, lower tariff
barriers and increase taxes.
</TEXT>
