<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1220EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GlobalFlag     12-15 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Global Flag,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Global Flag Gets Start in St. Louis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LORI DODGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are flags for nations, states, cities,
clubs and teams, but until now there was no flag for the whole
world.
   ``Heck, McDonalds' even has a flag,'' said Ken Roffmann, one of
two St. Louis men who have designed a ``Global Flag.''
   Roffmann said Thursday that he hoped to have the flag flying
over every country of the world by the end of 1992 to remind people
that they are all ``citizens'' of the planet Earth.
   ``Seeing ourselves as one planet _ no divisions, no boundaries _
helps us envision the new levels of cooperation and interdependence
we need as we move into the most critical decade of human
history,'' Roffmann said.
   ``Our survival depends on our ability to think globally and act
locally,'' he said.
   The 3-by-5 Global Flag is midnight blue, and in the center is a
full-color reproduction of the ``full earth'' photograph taken by
Apollo 17 en route to the moon.
   Roffmann said he and his partner, David Fischer, already had
arranged to have the flag flying at the Global Forum on Environment
and Development for Survival and the Soviet-American Citizens'
Summit, both in Moscow next month.
   They also hope to have it incorporated into World Peace Day
activities around the world on Dec. 31, as well as the global Earth
Day 1990, on April 22.
   ``It would be marvelous if the next time we go to the moon,
instead of planting the American flag, we planted this global
flag,'' Roffmann said.
   In the first few weeks of their project, Roffmann said, about
100 Global Flags have been distributed to people and organizations.
   A portion of the proceeds from the sale of the flags, which run
about $50, will go to organizations involved in Campaign for the
Earth, a 10-year campaign to create a peaceful, sustainable world
that will kick off Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Editors: Roffmann may be reached at 1-800-PLANET1.
</TEXT>
