<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1218EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-OddballXmas Bjt   12-15 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oddball Xmas, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oddball Holiday Gifts Sustain Southern California's Wacky Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Velvet-wrapped chunks of the Berlin Wall,
pottery animals that sprout green coats and dolls to stick on car
windows just won't do as gifts for the well-heeled and adventurous
this holiday season.
   There is an abundance of offbeat gifts this Christmas,
particularly for the indulgent rich whose urgent needs are inspired
by Madison Avenue, Rodeo Drive window displays and chic catalogs.
   How about a gift with spirit? Jurgensen's offers Angels Share
fine Scotch whisky in an etched Baccarat crystal decanter for
$8,650 a bottle. One buyer was Dan Marcheano, owner of The Arches
Restaurant in Newport Beach.
   ``We aren't cracking that sucker open right now, I'll tell you
that. I'm not about to say, `Would you like a $750 shot of
whiskey?''' said Marcheano, who put the precious elixir in a
lighted display case.
   The car culture dictates the wish-list for fast-lane crazies,
and Beverly Hills Motoring Accessories provides drive-time
necessities for those on the fast track. There's a $1,200 car fax
machine, $2,100 Recaro leather seat, $100 monogrammed floor mats
and a $1,500, foot-long crystal Ferrari.
   For the kid who has almost everything, there's a half-scale
Ferrari Testarossa that reaches a maximum speed of 30 mph. It gohe difference
to
customers who buy Chrysler vehicles now.
   There was no immediate reaction to Chrysler's announcement from
General Motors Corp. or Ford Motor Co. In the past, when one of the
Big Three automakers significantly boosted incentive programs,
others followed suit.
   Incentives carry a big risk for the automakers: While cash
rebates or low-interest financing may boost sales, the cost of the
incentives come directly from manufacturer profits.
   In late March, when Ford kicked off incentive programs, GM and
Chrysler followed suit within four days. Those programs stimulated
sales, but dented profits.
   Today's announcement was an attempt to improve Chrysler's
slumping sales.
   Through Dec. 10, the company's car and truck sales were running
6.7 percent behind last year's pace. In recent months the decline
has been more significant.
   Chrysler reported sales declines of 8.6 percent and 9.2 percent
in October and November, respectively. Things have been worse at
GM, where sales fell 18.3 percent and 18.9 percent for the same
months, and at Ford, which reported declines of 11.1 percent for
October and 13.1 percent for November.
   The Big Three reported their earnings were down 8.3 percent
during that three-month period from the same period a year ago, the
most profitable second quarter in auto history.
   Chrysler, which said its incentive costs during the quarter were
20 percent higher than in the year-ago period, reported a 6.4
percent increase in its second-quarter profits.
   Since then, Chrysler's earnings have tumbled. In the third
quarter, the company reported a 77.1 percent decline in earnings,
without a one-time benefit from a sale of stock in Mitsubishi
Motors Corp. Some analysts are forecasting the company will barely
remain profitable in the final quarter of 1989.
   Ford's profits in the third quarter were down 44.3 percent and
GM's were off 39.8 percent.
</TEXT>
