<FIRST>r a PM-BullStatue     12-15 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bull Statue,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist Leaves 3-Ton Bull Statue on Wall Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An artist took a bronze bull by the horns _
well, he used a truck and forklift, actually _ and deposited it in
front of the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``This is my Christmas present for America. For the bullish
country of America,'' sculptor Arturo Di Modica told the New York
Post after he plunked down his three-ton work, ``The Charging
Bull,'' on Wall Street late Thursday.
   Di Modica, who worked on the 11-foot-high bronze statue for two
years in his SoHo studio and said he spent $300,000 on the project,
did not seek a permit to show the work, which he brought in under
cover of darkness.
   ``They wouldn't give me one if I asked,'' he said.
   Di Modica said he chose the location because ``for the stock
market, the bull is strength, and the power of the country is the
stock market.''
   The Sicilian-born sculptor said he began the statue after the
1987 stock market crash. He wanted to create ``a monumental work
attesting to the vitality, energy and life of the American people
in adversity.''
   Despite calling the statue a Christmas present, the artist told
the paper he would like to sell the work. He hopes authorities will
let it stay until New Year's Day.
   Sharon Gamsin, a spokeswoman for the New York Stock Exchange,
declined to comment on the matter this morning.
   Police want to talk to the person responsible for the statue
before deciding what to do, said Officer Janice Swinney, a
department spokeswoman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
