<HEAD>Dangerous Wind Chills Slap Central U.S.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-13 bgng `Even more...' with 14 grafs to UPDATE
with snow conditions today in Wyoming, Colorado, Michigan, Wisconsin and
elsewhere. Picks up 14th graf, `A winter....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wicked northwest winds whipped snow and arctic air into the
north-central states today, spawning subzero temperatures across
most of the northern Plains and Upper Mississippi Valley and wind
chill indexes of 50 degrees below zero.
   Frigid temperatures were expected to continue this weekend as
massive arctic high pressure settled into the northern and central
Plains.
   At 11 p.m. Thursday, North Dakota wind chill indexes included 55
below in Fargo, 49 below in Jamestown and 43 below in Grand Forks.
   Wind chill factors are the combined effect of winds and chilling
temperatures on exposed skin. Advisories for dangerous wind chills
as cold as 60 below have been posted for much of Nebraska, Kansas
and Iowa today.
   In north-central Wyoming, it was snowing so hard in the Big Horn
Mountains that the Antelope Butte ski resort couldn't opened this
weekend as planned. Roads to the resort were blocked, preventing an
engineer from reaching the area for an annual inspection required
by the U.S. Forest Service, its owners said. Some 30 inches of snow
has fallen in the area.
   A winter storm warning was in effect for much of northern,
central and southeastern Wyoming today.
   A snow and blowing snow advisory was issued for the north and
central mountains in Colorado today after 18 inches of snow fell
near Vail Pass.
   Even more snow was expected in the already blanketed Great Lakes
region. A heavy snow warning was in effect for Lake Superior's
shoreline today.
   Six inches of new snow fell overnight in Wisconsin's Door
County, bringing the amount of accumulation since Wednesday to 30
inches.
   Heavy snow warnings were posted today for Michigan's western and
central Upper Peninsula, with up to 12 inches expected in isolated
areas. The 3 below recorded in Flint this morning broke a
26-year-old record low of minus 1.
   Advisories for snow and blowing snow have also been issued for
central Montana.
   Snow in the middle Mississippi Valley was expected to spread
into the Ohio Valley. In Missouri, the heaviest snow _ about 6
inches _ hit the St. Louis area, but Kansas City and Kirksville
were the coldest spots in the state with readings of 15 below and
14 below respectively.
   Lake snow advisories were issued for parts of western New York
state.
   A winter storm warning was in effect today for northern
Kentucky, the southern half of Indiana and southwest Ohio. A snow
advisory was issued for southeast Ohio and a winter storm watch was
posted for the northeastern part of the state.
   A winter storm warning was in effect today and tonight in West
Virginia's northern mountains.
   Peoria, Ill. broke an 88-year-old record for the date's coldest
temperature with 7 degrees. Other cities with record lows for the
date included Bismarck, N.D., 26; Buffalo, N.Y., 2; Rochester,
N.Y., 3; Rockford, Ill., 4, and Pensacola, Fla., 27.
   Temperatures Thursday warmed into the 70s across parts of
California and in extreme southern Texas.
   The nation's high was 79 at Spring Valley, Calif., and San Juan
Capistrano, Calif.
   Other reports at 4 a.m. EST today:
