<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1321EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Sakharov-Gorbachev     12-15 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov-Gorbachev,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharov-Gorbachev Relationship Defined Era of Reform</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Sakharov, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Andrei D. Sakharov shared
little personally except a mutual respect and a commitment to
change.
   As they went before the nation in a parliamentary session this
week, they could not have appeared more different: Gorbachev, at
the pinnacle of his power, was robust and self-confident; Sakharov
was stooped and stammering.
   And yet, the times dictated that they work together, and it was
Sakharov's relationship to the Soviet president that defined his
role in an era of reform.
   It was a sign of the program of change that Sakharov long had
urged and Gorbachev instituted that Soviets could watch the two men
struggle with each other at the Congress of People's Deputies
parliament.
   Sakharov died Thursday evening in his study, preparing to
challenge Gorbachev once more on the political supremacy of the
Communist Party that Gorbachev leads.
   ``It's a great loss,'' Gorbachev said Friday during a break in
the Congress of People's Deputies, where Sakharov had served as a
parliamentarian. ``During this time of perestroika, Academician
Sakharov had his mission, his role, and that we all understood. He
was a man of conviction and sincerity. He was not some sort of
political intriguer.''
   The Soviet public liked and respected Sakharov at least as much
as Gorbachev. An unscientific poll conducted by the weekly
Arguments and Facts in October found Sakharov the country's most
popular politician, more popular than Gorbachev.
   Gorbachev freed Sakharov from the exile in the industrial city
of Gorky imposed by Leonid I. Brezhnev, and withdrew Soviet
soldiers from Afghanistan. It was Sakharov's criticism of the
intervention into Afghanistan 10 years ago that led to his exile in
Gorky.
   Even though Sakharov owed his return to Moscow from the living
hell of isolation, force-feedings and surveillance in Gorky,
Gorbachev never dominated Sakharov.
   Sakharov spoke out in favor of the reforms Gorbachev instituted
because they matched his own ideals, but in the past several months
had become increasingly critical of the pace of the reform and
Gorbachev's accumulation of power.
   He said the country had no alternative to Gorbachev's leadership
but prodded the Soviet president to push harder. The day he died,
he told a group of like-minded deputies that the Soviet
leadership's hesitancy to press more radical reform was leading the
country to catastrophe.
   Sakharov told the first Congress in June:``I personally respect
Mikhail Sergeyevich Gorbachev very much, but it is dangerous to
give so much power even to the initiator of perestroika.''
   Sakharov continually challenged Gorbachev at the Congress, but
was no match as a public speaker to the vigorous and self-confident
president. Sakharov stammered, rambled and spoke in a high-pitched
voice, often losing his audience even when it supported him.
   He often pressed issues that a smarter politician would have
left alone. Deputies hounded him in June for allegations that the
Soviet military had hunted down and killed its own soldiers in
Afghanistan rather than risk their captured by rebels.
   In recently released excerpts of a book to be published next
year, Sakharov said that Gorbachev usually greeted him with a smile
that was ``half-kindly, half-condescending.''
   Even when Gorbachev tried to silence him, Sakharov insisted on
being heard.
   Their last exchange was shown to millions of Soviets on live TV
on Tuesday, the opening day of the Congress' winter session.
   Gorbachev granted Sakharov the right to speak after having
denied it to a previous deputy, but cut him off abruptly when he
began challenging the Communist Party's grip on power.
   Sakharov handed Gorbachev a stack of telegrams in support of his
position, and the Soviet leader retorted: ``You come to me, I will
give you three files of telegrams.''
   Even though Gorbachev called Sakharov in exile in December 1986
to tell him he could return to Moscow, the two did not meet until
more than a year later, Jan. 15, 1988.
   Typically, Sakharov handed Gorbachev a list of 200 prisoners
still held for their political beliefs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
