<FIRST>u i PM-Panama 2ndLd-Writethru   12-15 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0598,0696</SECOND>
<HEAD>Noriega-controlled Assembly Gives Him No. 1 Political Post, Sweeping
Powers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with details on powers given, pickup
6th graf `Asked about...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers controlled by Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega today named him head of the government and granted
him sweeping powers, saying they took the action to confront a
``state of war'' because of U.S. sanctions.
   The unanimous resolution by the 510-member People's Assembly,
which the Defense Forces chief picked, said Noreiga was being
designated ``maximum leader for national liberation.''
   The move formally gives Noriega greater powers than provisional
President Francisco Rodriguez, a situation that already existed de
facto.
   Several thousand Noriega supporters surrounded the assembly as
it met and cheered as the resolution passed.
   ``The Republic of Panama is declared to be in a state of war
while the aggression lasts,'' said the resolution. ``To confront
this aggression, the job of chief of government of Panama is hereby
created, and Manuel Antonio Noriega is designated to carry out
these responsibilities as maximum leader for national liberation.''
   The resolution gave Noriega the power to appoint public
officials, control foreign relations, convoke the assembly, and
``make decisions on whatever other matter or unforeseen
circumstance that affect the national life and the interests of the
country.''
   Asked about the move, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger told reporters in Washington, ``This ia charade and
nonsense. As far as we are concerned, at least, there is no
government in Panama anyway.
   Isaac Chandeck, a delegate from the Panama City suburb of Ancon,
predicted Thursday that the assembly would give Noriega the post.
   Rodriguez, a Noriega friend since high school, was picked as
president after Noriega halted vote-counting in a popular election
in May, backed the general for the new post Thursday.
   Noriega annulled returns from the May 7 vote when they showed
the opposition winning by a landslide. The move also blocked the
election of a new National Assembly, so Noriega picked a new
legislative body.
   Noriega is wanted in the United States on federal
drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges. The United States
has been trying to oust him with economic sanctions and diplomatic
pressure.
   Rodriguez told the assembly Thursday that the United States had
``declared war on all Panamanians'' with its economic sanctions.
   ``It is not Noriega they want to do away with,'' Rodriguez said.
``They want to do away with our national capacity to be
independent.''
   Noriega has weathered more than a year of the sanctions,
opposition demonstrations and two attempted coups from inside the
Defense Forces.
   As chief executive, Noriega would hold the same title as that of
dictator Omar Torrijos, who negotiated treaties with the United
States to transfer the Panama Canal to Panamanian control at the
end of the century and close down U.S. military installations.
   Noriega says the United States is trying to force his ouster
because it wants to renege on the treaties.
   In another move against the United States, Chandeck said he will
be distributing ``wanted'' posters for two U.S. generals.
   Chandeck has filed charges of destroying Panamanian property
against Gen. Marc Cisneros, commander of U.S. Army South; and Gen.
Maxwell Thurman, head of the U.S. Southern Command that includes
all U.S. military forces in Latin America.
   The generals were charged in Ancon, Chandeck's constituency.
They were accused of destroying public property by driving armored
personnel carriers on public roads and by other actions.
   The U.S. military twice rejected court summons for Cisneros and
Thurman. U.S. officials offered in one letter the ``courtesy'' of
facilitating ``the transfer of custody of selected fugitives
pending drug-trafficking charges in the United States.'' That was a
reference to Noriega and the charges against him.
   Borough officials did not respond to the tongue-in-cheek offer.
Instead, they issued an arrest warrant for Cisneros and Thurman.
Chandeck said he now plans to distribute ``wanted'' posters of
Cisneros and Thurman all over the country.
   ``We will have their pictures and a big `wanted' sign on top,''
he said.
</TEXT>
