<FIRST>r a AM-FareHikes     12-15 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fare Hikes,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>NY Subway Fares Going Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ignoring demonstrators chanting ``Shame! Shame!
Shame!'' the Metropolitan Transportation Authority voted Friday to
raise its bus and subway fares 15 cents to $1.15.
   In addition to the first subway fare hike in four years, the MTA
board approved increases averaging 15 percent for the commuter
trains and express buses that serve the city's outer boroughs and
suburbs.
   ``No one likes a fare increase, but it does cost money to get
things done,'' explained MTA Chairman Robert Kiley. ``Service is
getting better.''
   The average fare increase of 15 percent compared favorably with
a 22 percent increase in the cost of living since the last hike, he
said.
   Dozens of protesters, including a contingent of Guardian Angels,
circled outside the MTA offices in Manhattan. Inside, the board's
session was punctuated by shouts of ``You'r stealing food out of
people's mouths!'' and ``Let the people vote on the fare!''
   When board member Herbert J. Libert asked Kiley if the
demonstrators could be quieted, Kiley replied: ``This will be a
test of your attention span, Herb.''
   Guards threw one sign-carrying demonstrator out of the room
after he approached the table where board members were sitting.
   The new fares take effect Jan. 1.
   The TA had proposed boosting bus and subway fares to $1.25 with
discount packages of 18 tokens for $20, but that was hooted down at
public hearings.
   Connecticut officials said this week they would veto the fare
increase for Metro-North trains running from that state into New
York.
   ``If Connecticut fails to make us whole, we would put on a level
of service (for Connecticut) that would reflect that,'' Kiley said.
   He said about $7.7 million in cuts for Connecticut service would
be necessary if state officials persist in their veto and refuse to
increase the state's direct subsidy to Metro-North Commuter
Railroad.
   The new fares include increasing Long Island Rail Road and
Metro-North fares 15 percent to 20 percent. An off-peak, 10-trip
ticket will be sold at 10 percent off the regular fare, and there
will be off-peak ``family fares'' under which children riding with
a parent pay 50 cents a ride. The $1 penalty for buying tickets on
the train will be increased to $2.
</TEXT>
