<FIRST>r a PM-DecoderTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0572 12-15 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Decoder Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0572,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendants to Appeal Verdicts in TV Satellite Descrambler Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, bgng `Beck said' with 1 graf to clarify that
attorney said this was first prosecution of descrambling using federal
wiretap law.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOTHAN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A county commissioner and three others were
convicted of illegally making and selling equipment used to
descramble pay-TV channels, a case a defense attorney said was the
first of its type in the nation.
   Dale County Commissioner Billy Clyde Herring and his brother,
Bennie Dean Herring, were convicted Thursday of three counts each
of conspiracy to manufacture, assemble, possess and sell video
deciphers modified to receive scrambled television signals on
premium pay channels without authorization.
   The Herring brothers and two others were convicted under a 1968
federal wiretap law that was amended by Congress in 1986 to include
electronic communications.
   Defense Attorneys George Beck and Jim Parkman said their clients
sold the devices openly and did not know the amended wiretap law
applied to descrambling. The defense contended the law was intended
to apply to bugging devices, not satellite transmission receivers.
   A new federal law, which went on the books in January,
specifically covers descrambling. The four were charged with
selling descrambling equipment in December 1987 and June 1988,
before the new anti-descrambling law was passed.
   Beck said the prosecution was the first against descrambling of
pay-TV channels using the federal wiretap law. U.S. Attorney Jim
Wilson could not confirm that, but said it is one of the first.
   ``We're naturally disappointed with the verdict,'' Beck said.
``We don't think the defendants had sufficient notice that what
they are accused of was a violation of the wiretap statute.''
   In addition to the Herrings' convictions, Ron Mills, 39, of
Goshen was convicted of two counts of conspiracy and Dee Dee Bell,
35, of Ariton was convicted of one count. Bennie Herring owns
Tri-State Satellite in Brundidge, and the other three worked for
him.
   U.S. District Judge Truman Hobbs did not set a sentencing date.
The four remain free on $5,000 bond apiece. Each defendant could
get up to five years in prison and fined $250,000 on each count.
   Dale County Commission Chairman Curt Head said state law
requires that Billy Herring step down from his post. Gov. Guy Hunt
will appoint a successor to finish the term, he said.
</TEXT>
