<FIRST>r a AM-Anti-GrowthProposal     12-15 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-Growth Proposal,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>County Proposal Would Halt Growth In Nation's Hottest Housing Market</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King County officials are considering a proposal
that could bring growth in the nation's hottest housing market to a
grinding halt.
   The proposal, unveiled Thursday by County Councilman Ron Sims,
would block housing construction in unincorporated King County
until after adequate roads, schools and other services are built.
   Sims and co-sponsor Councilwoman Cynthia Sullivan said the
proposal aims to shift the power to make land use decisions to the
public, essentially giving them veto rights over developments if
their neighborhoods are being overwhelmed by growth.
   In May, Seattle voters adopted limits on downtown growth in one
of the city's first demonstrations of discontent with the fast pace
of development.
   If the county council approves the measure, it would put an
amendment of the council's charter on the Nov. 6, 1990, general
election ballot.
   The proposed amendment reads: ``No county officials shall have
the authority to approve private development where facilities will
not be adequate, unless an emergency is found to exist.''
   That would eliminate the discretion county officials have to
approve development plans when services are not in place.
   Sims listed roads, sewers, water, schools, open space and
surface water drainage as key services that would have to be in
place before ground is broken for a project.
   ``We're taking away the permissiveness that has allowed growth
to occur before we have the infrastructure to support it,'' Sims
said. He said he would formally introduce the ordinance at Monday's
council meeting.
   A simple majority on the nine-member council is needed for
approval.
   ``What it does is require communities to `pay as they grow' and
that's something we've been promoting for over a year,'' said newly
elected council member Brian Derdowski, a slow-growth activist.
   Developers criticized the measure as a ``poorly drafted''
ordinance that fails to define what is adequate service.
   ``If this ordinance passes, (housing) prices will skyrocket,''
said Bill Sherman, president of the Seattle Master Builders
Association.
   Sims said a later ordinance would define which services would be
included and what would be considered adequate.
   The measure comes as the median cost of a single-family home in
the Seattle area is rising at 23.7 percent a year, up from $88,900
to $110,000 in the past year, the fastest pace in the nation,
according to the National Association of Realtors.
   The population is also swelling, with an estimated 650,000 more
people expected by 2020.
   The 2,128-square-mile county has about 1.4 million residents,
about 31 percent of Washington state's population. Incorporated
areas include Seattle and its suburbs, with a total of about 1
million people. Much of the eastern part of the county is
unincorporated.
   The county has grown by about 190,000 people during the past
decade, with newcomers accounting for about half the increase.
   Seattle was named the nation's most liveable city this year by
the Places Rated Almanac, in part because of its affordable real
estate.
</TEXT>
