<DOCNO> AP891215-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-Analysis     12-15 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Analysis,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition's Big Victory Should Help Subdue Pinochet</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A decisive election victory gives the new
civilian government vital leverage on Gen. Augusto Pinochet, who
will keep command of the army after leaving the presidency, but the
road ahead is not smooth.
   President-elect Patricio Aylwin acknowledges he must build
careful alliances with conservatives to achieve democratic reforms
sought by his center-left alliance.
   Also, Pinochet appears at least indirectly strengthened in his
claim to leadership of the politial right.
   Aylwin won 55.2 percent of the vote for president Thursday,
nearly twice the 29.4 percent of pro-government candidate Hernan
Buchi. A third candidate, entrepreneur Francisco Errazuriz, got
only 15.4 percent, according to virtually complete returns released
Friday.
   The 17-party coalition Aylwin represents won a majority in the
120-member House of Deputies and 22 of the 38 elected Senate seats.
The consitution Pinochet's government wrote in 1980, however,
allows it to appoint up to 10 more senators.
   His own impressive victory, and the especially good showing of
his Christian Demcratic Party give Aylwin ``a strong mandate,''
said Arturo Valenzuela, Latin American studies director at
Georgetown University in Washington.
   Thursday's vote demonstrates that ``Aylwin has broad-based
support, which Pinochet does not,'' Valenzuela said in an interview
in Santiago, where he witnessed the election. ``He can say: `Look,
I got 55 percent. You only got 43 percent.'''
   Pinochet won 43 percent of the vote in October 1988 on a
referendum proposal to extend his presidency to 1997.
   He lost the referendum and was forced to call the elections, but
Pinochet's showing was much stronger than Buchi's in the
presidential race.
   ``For the right, Pinochet is the most powerful figure,
potentially,'' Valenzuela said.
   The fiercely anti-communist general, 74, seized power in 1973,
overthrowing elected President Salvador Allende, an avowed Marxist
who died in the coup. He is to relinquish the presidency March 11,
but has said he will remain as commander of the 60,000-man army.
   A special clause in the constitution allows him to keep the job
until 1998. From the army command, directly across Santiago's main
boulevard from the presidential palace, he plans to lead the
military in its role as watchdog of his 1980 constitution.
   Pinochet also has hinted occasionally that he may return to
politics _ because, the general says, Chileans will come to miss
his authoritarian leadership.
   Aylwin's platform includes several democratic changes in the
constitution and in special laws, but majorities of up to
two-thirds are needed to pass them.
   That his coalition failed to achieve such dominance is due
largely to complicated electoral laws written by the junta that
caused many leftist candidates to lose even when they got more
votes than rightist opponents.
   Parties of the left have considerable influence in powerful
labor groups, and Aylwin will need to make sure they do not feel
disenfranchized as he tries to reach accommodation with
conservatives.
   At a news conference Friday, the president-elect seemed well
aware of his delicate position. He denied any intention of setting
his Christian Democrats apart from the alliance as a means of
wooing moderate rightists known to dislike Pinochet.
   The alliance will continue to work ``as a team,'' Aylwin said,
and he will follow a ``path of broad consensus'' between now and
March 11.
   He spoke of the peaceful manner in which Chileans are returning
to civilian government, and declared: ``In this country, the
commitment toward moderation prevails.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Kevin Noblet is AP bureau chief in Santiago and
has covered South America for The Associated Press since 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
