<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Sakhalin     12-15 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Sakhalin,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Korean Wartime Survivors on Sakhalin Return Home in Tears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty-three Koreans on Friday were
tearfully reunited with their relatives after arriving from the
Soviet island of Sakhalin, where Japan sent them to work during
World War II.
   The Koreans, ranging in age from 57 to 83, hugged relatives and
shed tears when they arrived at Seoul's Kimpo International Airport
for their first visit. They are among thousands sent to labor on
Sakhalin when the island was under Japanese control. The Soviets
took it over in the closing days of the war in 1945, when Korea was
liberated from Japan's colonial rule.
   This was the first batch of Koreans on Sakhalin who have visited
South Korea under a program initiated in July by South Korean and
Japanese Red Cross officials.
   The 23 Koreans will return to the Soviet territory after winding
up an officially-sponsored two-week stay in South Korea.
   About 4,000 Korean wartime survivors live on the island, in
addition to more than 30,000 Sakhalin Koreans of the second or
third generation.
   South Korea had urged the Soviet Union to establish official
channels to help the Koreans on Sakhalin visit their homeland since
the communist superpower permitted limited home visits by the
Sakhalin Koreans in 1986.
   Although South Korea has no diplomatic relations with the Soviet
Union, the two countries have sharply improved trade and other
relations in recent years.
   Sakhalin, a narrow 580-mile-long island, lies about 40 miles
north of Japan's northernmost island of Hokkaido and straddles the
Soviet mainland.
</TEXT>
