<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviet     12-15 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Critical of Soviet Economic Planning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House suggested Friday that
continued Soviet adherence to ``a centralized planning course''
could jeopardize some economic incentives President Bush offered
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater cited recent criticism
in the Soviet Congress of People's Deputies of Gorbachev's
perestroika _ or restructuring _ and moves toward keeping multiyear
planning methods.
   ``We're disappointed that they appear to be on a centralized
planning course,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush outlined ``a number of economic opportunities for the
Soviet Union'' when he met earlier this month with Gorbachev at
Malta, including a promise to support Moscow's bid for observer
status in the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an
international organization that establishes trading rules,
Fitzwater said.
   ``A good deal of the progress under those initiatives requires
that they move toward market pricing ... toward market economics,
'' Fitzwater said. ``This is not particularly encouraging for their
participation in world economic bodies. And, so, we are
disappointed.''
