<FIRST>u a PM-High-RiseFire 1stLd-Writethru a0579 12-15 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-High-Rise Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0579,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire At High-Rise for Elderly Kills Three</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with number of dead and injured
confirmed, authorities saying arson is cause and that safety violation
helped fire spread; picks up 8th graf, `There's not....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WATERTOWN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An arson blaze this morning on the first
floor of a high-rise for the elderly pumped smoke into upper
floors, killing three people out of reach of firefighters' aerial
ladders, authorities said.
   After rescuers evacuated the 15-story Midtown Towers in
below-zero cold, 77 residents and two firefighters were taken to
Watertown's two hospitals, most for treatment of smoke inhalation.
Six residents were listed in critical condition.
   ``A lot of people were hanging out the upstairs windows
screaming,'' said Bruce Wright of Guilfoyle Ambulance Service Inc.
``There was a tremendous amount of flames coming out the front and
back end of the building.''
   Fire Chief Joseph H. Gravelle said a door at the base of the
building's stairwell jammed, trapping some residents until it was
pried open. Most of the dead and injured were reportedly found in
stairwells, he said.
   State fire investigators classified the fire as ``probable
arson,'' Police Chief Michael J. Hennegan said. He said if this
preliminary determination stands, the deaths will be investigated
as homicides.
   Investigators said the fire started shortly after midnight in a
first-floor recreation area of the 20-year-old building, which has
150 apartments.
   More than 100 firefighters from nine departments arrived within
minutes and controlled the blaze within an hour.
   Gravelle said the fire was contained to the first floor, but
that smoke quickly spread throughout the building. He said a safety
violations helped the fire spread on the first floor _ the
recreation room's double doors were left open overnight.
   One of the dead was found in a hallway and two were found in
stairwells on the 12th and 13th floors, beyond the reach of the
city's aerial ladders.
   ``There's not a truck in the world that could reach the top of
the building,'' said former Watertown Fire Chief Ronald D. Damon,
adding that the fire truck ladders reach about eight stories.
   Firefighters led about 200 elderly residents down
fire-protective staircases out of the building or through apartment
windows to a suspended aerial platform.
   A shelter was set up nearby for those residents not requiring
medical treatment.
   ``I was asleep with my TV on, and all of a sudden the smoke
alarm went on and I got right up,'' said 78-year-old Edna Gardner.
   Police Sgt. Ray Montrois identified the dead as Pansy Kiernan
88, Eunice Roberts, 88 and Frank Pepe, 69, all residents.
</TEXT>
