<DOCNO> AP891215-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1457EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IndustrialProduction     12-15 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Industrial Production,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Output Little Changed As Sluggishness Spreads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial production was little changed in
November despite rebounding from a major strike and a devestating
earthquake, the government said Friday in a report that showed
spreading economic sluggishness.
   Many economists said the weak 0.1 percent gain in output _ the
first in three months _ accompanied by moderating inflation
suggests the Federal Reserve Board should permit another drop in
short-term interest rates to stimulate the economy.
   ``Manufacturing production continues to slow _ it's not
collapsing, but it is slowing _ and I think the Fed is sensing that
it has some type of leeway to ease'' rates, said John Silvia, an
economist with Kemper Financial Services in Chicago.
   In its report Friday on industrial production, the Fed
attributed the gain to a rebound from the Boeing Co. strike, which
ended in late November, and from the lingering effects in the
computer and related industries from the San Francisco Bay-area
earthquake in October, when output had slumped 0.6 percent.
   ``Excluding the impact of these events, the total index would
have been little changed in both October and November.'' the Fed
reported.
   The manufacturing sector has been among the hardest hit by the
Fed's tight-money policies as the central bank tries to contain
inflation by slowing the economy without tipping it into a
recession.
   But in the latest report on inflation, the Commerce Department
said Friday that wholesale prices dipped 0.1 percent in November,
the third decline in five months.
   Industrial output had not risen since a 0.4 percent gain last
August and that followed a 0.1 percent drop in July. It was down
0.3 percent in September.
   ``Clearly, the manufacturing sector is sluggish,'' contended
Lawrence Chimerine, senior economic adviser for the WEFA Group in
Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
   ``It started in the auto industry earlier this year and spread
to other consumer durables,'' he said. ``We're seeing softness in
appliances and furniture and, in the last month or so, seeing it
show up in the capital goods industry.''
   Output at manufacturing plants making both durable and
nondurable goods rose 0.2 percent in November after falling 0.8
percent in October and 0.4 percent in September.
   Production of durable goods _ items expected to last more than
three years _ rose 0.5 percent last month after falling 1.8 percent
in October and 0.7 percent in September. Nondurable manufacturing
fell 0.2 percent after rising 0.5 percent in October and 0.1
percent in September.
   In another report reflecting sluggishness, the Fed said the
operating rate of the nation's factories, mines and utilities edged
down 0.1 percentage point to 82.7 percent in November to its lowest
rate since April 1988.
   ``That's one of the reasons you're seeing producer prices
falling,'' said Donald Ratajczak, economic forecasting director at
Georgia State University. ``When you have excess capacity, that's
when you see price concessions.''
   The closer U.S. industry gets to full operating capacity, the
greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading
to shortages and subsequent price increases.
   Analysts generally consider an operating rate of 85 percent or
above as an indication of inflationary pressures.
   Factory use had dipped in October to 82.8 percent from 83.4
percent in September. The rate posted 10-year highs of 84.3 percent
last December and January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
