<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS newsman Charles Osgood, whose trademarks
include his bow tie and rhyming radio reports, says poetry does not
come easy under deadline pressure.
   One device for making a news story written in New York remain
fresh when it is aired three hours later on the West Coast is
``anticipatory verse,'' Osgood told a luncheon for affiliate KIRO
Thursday.
   He gave this example:
   ``There once was a pretty young lass
   Who hailed from the Bay State of Mass.
   And on a fine and sunny day
   She stepped into the bay
   In water right up to her knees.''
   Osgood explained: ``It doesn't rhyme now, but it will when the
tide comes in.''
