<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-OrkinSuit     12-15 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Orkin Suit,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cat Owner Sues Exterminator over Pet's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cat fancier sued Orkin Exterminating Co.,
accusing the pest control company of poisoning and burying her cat
when she had her house fumigated.
   ``The point of the whole suit is that they need to recognize the
value of animals and what animals mean to a lot of people,'' said
Lisa Hogan, a nurse who filed suit Thursday in Hillsborough Circuit
Court.
   The lawsuit did not specify the amount of damages sought.
   An Orkin crew had put a tarpaulin over Ms. Hogan's house to
prepare for termite fumigation June 29, according to the lawsuit.
While Ms. Hogan and a roommate were moving pets out, Dewey, a big
gray cat, jumped from her roommate's arms and scrambled beneath the
house.
   She said she tried to lure Dewey out with cat food but failed.
   Ms. Hogan told an Orkin employee not to begin fumigating ``if
there was any chance of her cat being under the house,'' according
to the lawsuit.
   The cat's body was found nearly a week later, half-covered with
soil a few feet from the back porch, she said.
   Ms. Hogan said an Orkin employee she talked with, identified
only as Mike in the complaint, acknowledged burying the cat.
   Chip Girkins, general manager for Orkin in Tampa, said Ms. Hogan
told workers to fumigate the house even though she knew the cat
might be underneath it. He acknowledged a worker buried the cat
without telling the owner.
   ``They were trying to make it easier on her,'' Girkins said.
</TEXT>
