<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov-NATO     12-15 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov-NATO,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Ministers Hail Sakharov</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Sakharov, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NATO foreign ministers on Friday
hailed Andrei D. Sakharov as a pioneer who played a key role in
changing Soviet society.
   NATO Secretary General Manfred Woerner said the ministers
expressed a ``deeply felt sense of loss at the passing of Andrei
Sakharov.''
   He said the allies underscored that Sakharov ``played an
exceptional role personally and who was a symbol for universal
democratic values.''
   Officials said U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III and
his NATO counterparts discussed Sakharov at the start of the second
and last day of their year-end strategy talks at the alliance
headquarters.
   Dutch Foreign Minister Hans van den Broek said in view of the
Soviet human rights leader's stature it was only ``natural that we
reflected for a minute'' on Sakharov's death.
   ``Sakharov is a man we must remember with much respect for the
untiring way he strove for freedom,'' Van den Broek said after the
meeting.
   He called his death ``a loss for the Soviet Union and especially
... for the forces of reform there. For many in the Communist
world, this man was a beacon.''
   British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd said after the meeting,
``We all feel a very deep sense of loss at the death of Mr.
Sakharov.''
   ``We should remember today, the great courage which it took in
very difficult and dangerous times for him to act and go on acting
as the focus, symbol, the spokesman of freedom in the Soviet
Union,'' he said.
   Hurd said he was glad Sakharov lived long enough ``to see
substantial progress in the direction which he was pointing his
country toward.''
   ``And I think in remembering that today we must also express the
hope that the torch will be handed on and that work which is not
yet completed will be carried forward by people who will rembmer
him,'' Hurd added.
   Baker called Sakharov ``a tremendous force for peace and
freedom.''
   ``He was as well a courageous pioneer who led the way in the
face of great adversity and we are very sad by his passing,'' Baker
said.
   ``I think Sakharov would be pleased if our reflection on his
work extended as well to all of those brave men and women, many of
them whose names we'll never know, who sacrificed their liberty,
indeed their lives, for the freedom of others.''
   Baker said until the very end, Sakharov pursued ``the causes
that meant the very most to him, standing up in parliament for
beliefs that may not be fully accepted today, but which will have
their day.''
</TEXT>
