<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1607EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran     12-15 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranians Vote For Nine Parliamentarians, Seen As Test Of Pragmatism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iranians braved rain and cold in Tehran
and five other cities Friday to choose nine Parliament members in
elections considered a crucial test for President Hashemi
Rafsanjani's pragmatic policies.
   Hard-liners fear Rafsanjani's efforts to liberalize the economy
and Iranian society will undermine revolutionary fervor and the
ideological purity of the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Tehran radio, monitored in Nicosia, said turnout in five of the
six constituencies, including Tehran, was so great that the 5
o'clock closing time of the polls was extended by two hours.
   But observers in Tehran reported low voter turnout.
   An Asian diplomat based in Tehran said the 5 p.m. closing time
of the polls was extended to attract last-minute voters in an
effort to increase the count.
   The radio did not provide a figure for voter turnout. But the
Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored in Nicosia, said all
constituents over 15 were eligible to vote.
   Candidates chosen by the electorate will represent Tehran,
Kashan, Karaj, Kerman, Bandar-Turkman-Kordkui and Kuhdasht-Chegini
in Parliament. Some of the constituencies are multi-member.
   Four seats in Tehran were being contested by 38 candidates, many
of them hard-line opponents of Rafsanjani and his so-called
pragmatic policies.
   Rafsanjani's former seat in Tehran, which he won with a record
1.2 million votes in the last general election in April-May 1988,
is one of those vacant.
   He gave up that seat following his victory in the presidential
elections in June.
   Most of the other vacant seats in the 270-member Majlis, or
parliament, were left empty when Rafsanjani appointed legislators
to posts in his new administration.
   Rafsanjani's ambitious policies to revive the economy by
improving ties with the West to attract badly needed investment and
technology are under attack by a hard-line faction led by former
Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi.
   Mohtashemi, who is contesting one of the Tehran seats, was
dumped in August when Rafsanjani formed his new government.
   He is closely linked with Shiite Moslem extremists believed to
hold most of the 18 Western hostages _ including eight Americans _
in Lebanon.
   He was also involved with militants who carried out suicide
bombings against the U.S. Embassy and the U.S. Marine base in
Beirut in 1983, killing hundreds of people.
   Friday's elections are Montashemi's first major effort to make a
comeback.
   The Majlis is already dominated by radicals of various stripes
and further gains by hard-liners in the elections will intensify
pressure on Rafsanjani.
   Rafsanjani has been very low-key about the elections.
   He said Friday after casting his vote that ``these are not the
general elections, therefore they lack enthusiasm. But in any case,
they are effective.'' His remarks were broadcast on Tehran TV,
monitored in Cyprus.
   Khomeini, who died June 3, spent much of his time after the 1979
revolution mediating squabbles between hard-liners and pragmatists,
and keeping their power in check. The power struggle has
intensified since Rafsanjani became president and began sidelining
his opponents.
   Apart from Mohtashemi, a number of other ex-ministers dumped by
Rafsanjani are standing in the election.
   This includes former Labor Minister Abulqasem Sarhadizadeh,
former Education Minister Reza Akrani, former Heavy Industries
Minister Behzad Nabavi, former Commerce Minister Habibollah Asgar
Owladi, and former Posts and Telegraph Minister Morteza Nabavi.
</TEXT>
