grave doubts about the intentions of the Nicaraguan government.''
   He said the Nicaraguan government is at a crossroads: ``It can
hold free and fair elections and thereby advance the process of
national reconciliation in Nicaragua and peace in Central America.
   ``Or it can endanger the peace process and the sanctity of the
electoral process by intimidation and violence against the
opposition,'' he said.
   On Thursday, members of a bipartisan panel gave President Bush a
firsthand account of bloodletting last weekend that they said was
caused by Sandinista supporters wielding machetes.
   Cecilia Lopez, a spokeswoman for the Nicaraguan Embassy in
Washington, called the violence ``an isolated incident'' and said
the opposition has held more than 50 peaceful rallies since
campaigning began.
   National elections are set for Feb. 25.
