<FIRST>r w AM-Flue-Cured     12-15 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flue-Cured,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Department Announces Tobacco Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department on Friday announced
some major provisions of the 1990 program for flue-cured tobacco.
   The federal marketing quota will be 877.7 million pounds, down
from this year's 890.5 million, said Undersecretary Richard T.
Crowder. The 1990 average yield goal will remain at 2,088 pounds
per acre.
   Next year's national acreage allotment will be 420,354 acres,
down from 426,485 in 1989.
   For each farm, the 1990 basic quota and allotment will decrease
about 1.5 percent from 1989.
   Crowder said the effective quota for 1990, which takes into
consideration previous undermarketings and overmarketings, will be
about 939 million pounds, up 35 million pounds from the 1989
effective quota.
   The price support level for 1990 flue-cured tobacco will be
$1.488 per pound, up 2 cents from this year, he said.
   Further details, including next year's ``no-net-cost
assessment'' and the amount of reduction under the Gramm-Rudman
budget reduction law will be announced later.
   Flue-cured tobacco farmers approved acreage-poundage quotas last
January for crops in 1989 through 1991.
</TEXT>
