<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran Arms,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>33-Month Sentence for Illegal Export</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Silicon Valley exporter was sentenced to
33 months in prison and fined $150,000 Friday for conspiring to
ship guided missile parts to Iran.
   Ken Park of Los Altos Hills, owner of Ellin International Co. in
Sunnyvale, pleaded guilty in August to the felony charge, and the
government dropped six charges of export violations. He was
sentenced by U.S. Distict Judge John Vukasin, who could have given
him five years in prison.
   The United States forbids arms sales to Iran.
   Prosecutors said Park shipped wing assemblies, illumination
devices and other parts for the Hawk, Sidewinder and Sparrow
missile systems, and falsely labeled them as truck and tractor
equipment destined for South Korea. He pleaded guilty to conspiring
to ship missile parts without a State Department license.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Joel Levin said no one else has been
charged in the case.
