<FIRST>r a AM-LawFirm-ElSalvador     12-15 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Law Firm-El Salvador,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minneapolis City Council Drops Law Firm With Ties to El Salvador</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The City Council voted Friday to fire a law
firm because it lobbies for Salvadoran President Alfredo
Christiani, a day after four partners and one associate lawyer
resigned from the firm for the same reason.
   ``After individual and collective soul-searching, we decided
that this was the best thing to do,'' said Douglas Franzen, one of
the partners who resigned from O'Connor &amp; Hannan on Thursday.
   The council voted 10-2 to drop the law firm effective Jan. 15,
ending a $500,000 a year legal contract.
   After the slaying of six Jesuits last month in El Salvador, a
group of protesters organized under the banner of the O'Connor &amp;
Hannan Campaign persuaded a majority of the council to support a
resolution co-sponsored by Council Members Carol Johnson and Brian
Coyle.
   Johnson, a primary author of the resolution to end the city's
contract with O'Connor &amp; Hannan, called the lawyers' resignation
``a courageous decision.''
   The other partners who quit are William McGrann, whose office in
Washington, D.C., represents the Salvadoran leader, Douglas
Carnival and Andrew Shea and associate lawyer Kathleen Lamb.
   The five, who make up the Minneapolis office's lobbying
division, are among the best-known legislative lobbyists in the
state. O'Connor &amp; Hannan represents many public bodies, including a
Minneapolis city agency.
   O'Connor &amp; Hannan has said it did not do legal work for
Cristiani and provided only public relations and congressional
lobbying, arranging meetings for Salvadoran officials with key
federal lawmakers and journalists.
   A spokesman for the law firm did not immediately return a phone
call Friday.
   McGrann and Franzen said in an interview Thursday the decision
to resign came after some clients had voiced their uneasiness with
the firm's link to Cristiani, and the lawyers' own personal and
professional convictions compelled them to quit.
   ``The clients said, `We keep reading about your law firm every
day and we don't like what we're seeing. We're uncomfortable about
that,''' McGrann said. ``The whole thing led to making it very
difficult for us to do the kind of work we do, generally in the
public sector, without it impacting our clients. Or at least our
clients felt they were being impacted.''
   Franzen said the group plans to establish a law firm ``and
continue serving our clients as best we can.''
   ``We want to state our belief ... that Mr. Cristiani has a right
to counsel and that right extends to lobbying the U.S. Congress.''
   But, the lawyers said, they did not want to be involved in that
effort and were unable to convince the firm to drop Cristiani.
</TEXT>
