<HEAD>Artist Leaves Bull Statue on Wall Street</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY46</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-ton bull took up a stand in front of the
New York Stock Exchange for part of Friday, but the exchange
couldn't bear the bronze statue and had it hauled away.
   The statue arrived by truck and forklift late Thursday under
cover of darkness.
   ``This is my Christmas present for America. For the bullish
country of America,'' sculptor Arturo Di Modica told the New York
Post, after he deposited te ``The Charging Bull'' on Wall Street.
   He said he chose the location because ``for the stock market,
the bull is strength, and the power of the country is the stock
market.''
   The Sicilian-born sculptor said he started work on the statue in
his SoHo studio after the 1987 stock market crash. He wanted to
create ``a monumental work attesting to the vitality, energy and
life of the American people in adversity.''
   Di Modica, who said he spent $300,000 of his own money on the
project, did not seek a permit to show the work. ``They wouldn't
give me one if I asked.''
   But during the day Friday, the statue was hauled away by a
private company, said police spokesman Sgt. Nick Vreeland.
   ``We did arrange for the bull to be taken away,'' said Sharon
Gamsin, a spokeswoman for the stock exchange.
   ``The city told the artist that he had to take it away, but he
told them he donated it to the city, so we assisted the city in
arranging to have it removed,'' Gamsin said.
