<FIRST>r a AM-Buchwald-Paramount     12-15 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Buchwald-Paramount,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Coming to America' Case Opens With Buchwald Alleging Plagiarism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art Buchwald wants $5 million to teach
Paramount Pictures a lesson, his lawyer said Friday. The columnist
claims the studio stole his script idea and turned it into the
movie hit ``Coming to America.''
   Paramount took Buchwald's idea titled ``King For A Day'' and
transformed it into the 1988 Eddie Murphy comedy, which grossed
more than $150 million, the lawyer said in opening arguments of the
trial, being conducted without a jury.
   ``We seek substantial punitive damages to teach Paramount and
others like it a lesson not to treat creative people like this ever
again,'' said attorney Pierce O'Donnell.
   Murphy, the attorney said, already has netted $22 million from
the film and Paramount collected more than $50 million in
distribution fees. But, he said, the studio refused to pay Buchwald
and producer Alain Bernheim $250,000 plus a small share of profits
under their original contract.
   ``Sadly, the evidence shows that even a towering literary figure
like Art Buchwald is prey to an unscrupulous major movie studio,''
the attorney said to Superior Court Judge Harvey Schneider.
   An attorney for Paramount, Robert Draper, ridiculed the idea
that Buchwald's script idea was plaigarized.
   He said it was different and that it never occurred to Ned
Tanen, the head of the studio, that there was any similarity
between the two ideas, both of which dealt with an African prince
coming to the United States.
   Draper acknowledged that during the year in which the case was
pending, Murphy _ who is not a party in the lawsuit _ admitted that
he had seen Buchwald's proposal. But Murphy said he couldn't tell
whether it influenced him subconsciously in writing his own script
for ``Coming to America.''
   ``What they're claiming, I think, is that Eddie didn't
intentionally rip them off. But in his subconscious, he ripped them
off,'' Draper said in his opening statement.
   A Memphis, Tenn., man, Laurence Armour, filed a $40 million
lawsuit in January against Murphy, claiming the movie's plot was
stolen from him and writer Shelby Gregory also has claimed the
story as his.
</TEXT>
