<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2018EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-15 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Party Draft Calls for Multiparty System, Membership in the EC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party proposed a
multiparty system, free elections and full membership in Western
economic institutions, including the European Community, according
to a declaration drafted Friday.
   ``The end to the authoritiarian socialism has come,'' said the
declaration, which also called for constitutional guarantees to
bring market-oriented economic reform, establish an independent
judiciary and protect human rights.
   The document, prepared for adoption at next month's national
party congress and published by the Borba daily, appears to be
Yugoslavia's reply to the wave of democratic reforms currently
sweeping Eastern Europe.
   ``The communist party of Yugoslavia supports freedom of
assembly, speech and all other civil liberties, regardless of
political convictions of individuals,'' said the document released
by a preparatory committee.
   Political ``associations, movements or parties will depend on
the will of the citizens, whose freedom of choice must be
guaranteed by the constitution,'' the declaration stated.
   It said that the communist party will no longer retain its
monopoly on power and will participate along with other parties in
``free, direct and secret elections.''
   ``We are changing all of this now in order that tomorrow will
not be too late for socialism in Yugoslavia,'' the document stated,
adding that the reforms should be implemented within six months
after the congress.
   Until now, the Communist leadership of Yugoslavia's largest
republic of Serbia was the staunchest opponent of Western-style
democracy in Yugoslavia. But at its congress on Friday Serbia's
Communist Party appeared to have softened its hard-line stance.
   Communists and Serbian authorities ``have no reason or wish to
administratively impede the establishment of (independent)
political parties'' in the republic, said Bogdan Trifunovic, the
region's party chief, in his keynote address.
   Serbia's rejection of Western-style democracy has been shared to
date by Yugoslavia's military, which contended that opposition
parties would be formed along ethnic lines, thus fueling ethnic
tensions.
   However, Gen. Ivo Tominc on Friday was quoted by the official
Tanjug news agency as saying that ``the army would not stand in the
way of the country's democratic development'' and that it would
``adjust itself to the changes in the society.''
   The second-largest republic of Croatia and liberal northern
Slovenia have already endorsed parliamentary democracy and are both
scheduled to hold free legeslative elections next spring.
   Independent movements and parties have been formed in Croatia
and Slovenia in the past year. Despite resistance from authorities
several opposition groups have also sprung up in Serbia, Bosnia,
Macedonia and Montenegro, where Communists have in the past tried
to sidestep democratic reforms.
   The draft congress declaration also said Yugoslavia will seek
``full participation in integration processes in Europe and
membership in the European Community, the Council of Europe, the
European Free Trade Association and other similar organizations and
institutions.''
   Yugoslavia has for years been a socialist showcase despite its
one-party system.
   But political, economic, social and ethnic problems have
mushroomed since the death in 1980 of President Josip Broz Tito,
whose charisma was seen as a major force in bounding together the
divergent ethnic groups in the country.
   In an unprecedented move, Serbia last month severed all business
and political ties with Slovenia after authorities there banned an
anti-Slovenian rally planned by thousands of Serbs.
   The Serbian move was generally seen as an attempt to isolate
Slovenia and prevent its liberal ideas from spreading all over the
rest of the country.
   ``The economic blockade of Slovenia ... is contrary to the
implementation of economic and political reforms and the reform of
the party in Yugoslavia,'' said Gen. Tominc in the first open army
criticism of the Serbian move, according to Tanjug.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2025EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-WetlandsMemorandum     12-15 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wetlands Memorandum,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Decides To Put Hold On EPA-Corps Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement between the Environmental
Protection Agency and the Army Corps of Engineers that would have
begun to carry out President Bush's campaign pledge to preserve
wetlands will be held up for 30 days, the administration announced
Friday.
   The two agencies ``will use the extension to allow for
explanations and discussion with federal agencies that have raised
concerns about the agreement,'' and to ``clear up any
misunderstandings about the purpose of the memorandum,'' EPA said
in a statement.
   The memorandum of agreement, which was reached in early November
and scheduled to take effect Friday, has caused a split within the
administration. The departments of Energy and Transportation oppose
the agreement and the Council on Environmental Quality and the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration are in favor.
   The Interior Department denied reports that the agreement had
sparked a fight in the department between the Fish and Wildlife
Service and the Minerals Management Service. Spokesman Steven
Goldstein said ``The only concerns we have are procedural.''
   Bush had promised during the campaign to strive for a goal of
``no net loss'' of wetlands.
   In a letter to Bush on Thursday, the president of the National
Wildlife Federation said the way in which the White House handles
the EPA-Corps agreement ``will demonstrate whether or not you are
truly commited to a national wetland policy of no net loss.''
   ``There is no middle ground on this one. It's either up or
down,'' wrote Jay Hair.
   The agreement has faced stiff criticism from the oil industry in
Alaska and the Alaska congressional delegation, who fear it could
disrupt oil and gas production on the North Slope and cripple that
state's economy. Gov. Steve Cowper has threatened to sue if the
agreement isn't changed.
   Many conservationists have grown increasingly concerned about
the disappearance of wetlands such as swamps, bogs, marshes,
potholes on the Great Plains and tidal estuaries.
   According to some estimates, up to 400,000 acres of wetlands per
year have been lost in recent decades to housing devlopments,
farms, shopping centers, highways and other encroachments of a
modern economy.
   But wetlands buffer floods, purify streams and provide wildlife
habitat for many species that can't life elsewhere.
   Federal law requires that the Corps grant a permit before
developers may put fill in most wetlands. EPA may challenge the
decision and has certain veto powers over it, and the two agencies
frequently had been at odds.
   The Corps agreed in the memorandum to ``strive to avoid adverse
impacts and offset unavoidable adverse impacts to existing aquatic
resources, and for wetlands, will strive to acheive a goal of no
overall net loss of values and functions.''
   The EPA, in its statement, said the memorandum ``does not define
a `no net loss' policy, but rather establishes a clear sequence of
actions to be considered in the (existing) permit-review process.''
   Under the agreement, permit applicants would first have to seek
alternatives to disturbing wetlands and if none were available
would have to work to minimize damege to wetlands.
   If the project would still cause significant harm, the applicant
would have to compensate for the loss, perhaps by building new
wetlands or restoring, old, already damaged areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
