<FIRST>r i AM-India     12-15 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslem Separatists Celebrating Hostage Swap Battle Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASKARI ZAIDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem separatists celebrating the
release of five radicals in exchange for a government minister's
kidnapped daughter hurled gasoline bombs at police Friday in
clashes that killed five people.
   Curfews were imposed in five towns of the northern state of
Jammu-Kashmir after widespread violence and to stop Moslem
separatists from demonstrating after Wednesday's swap. Security
forces were told to shoot violators.
   Officials said two people were killed and 30 others were injured
in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu-Kashmir with a population
of 700,000. The Moslem-majority state lies on the Pakistan border.
   Officers opened fired in the town of Anantnag when mobs hurled
stones and gasoline bombs on police barricades, said Shoaib S. Ali,
deputy inspector general of the state police.
   In Shupiyan, crowds burned a forest office building and attacked
police contingents. Police fatally shot three men and wounded 30
others, said Divisional Commissioner Mohammad Shafi Pandit, a
senior government official.
   Curfews were imposed in Sopore and Baramullah on Thursday after
separatist violence left two teen-agers dead and 50 others injured.
   Security forces were ordered to shoot curfew violators Friday,
Ali said. Soldiers have been posted in all five towns, he said.
   Five militants of the Kashmir Liberation Front were released
Wednesday in exchange for the Rubaiya Sayeed, held hostage since
her abduction by the separatist group Dec. 8.
   Ms. Sayeed, 22, is a medical intern at a Srinagar hospital and
the youngest daughter of Home Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, a
Kashmiri and the first Moslem to be named to the sensitive post
that oversees police and internal security.
   Prime Minister V.P. Singh said the release of the militants was
not ``bowing to terrorists,'' but a decision that took into account
``the overall situation.''
   He said the new government, formed Dec. 2, will assess the
situation in the state but was not in favor of precipitate action
becuase ``it is a delicate situation.''
   The Kashmir Liberation Front, formed in 1965, wants
Jammu-Kashmir to secede from India and become either independent or
merge with Islamic Pakistan.
   Moslems make up 64 percent of Jammu-Kashmir's 5 million people
but only about 12 percent of the country's 880 million people.
Hindus account for about 80 percent of the population.
   Kashmir, the northwestern region of the state, is claimed by
both India and Pakistan, and the two countries have fought three
wars over the territory since gaining independence from Britain in
1947.
   A cease-fire line monitored by the United Nations separates the
state into Indian and Pakistani territory.
</TEXT>
