<FIRST>r i AM-Hugo-Troops     12-15 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hugo-Troops,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last of Federal Troops Return Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHRISTIANSTED, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last U.S. troops
sent to restore order on St. Croix after Hurricane Hugo began
pulling out Friday, an official said.
   All 170 members of the 276th and 471st Washington, D.C.,
National Guard military police units will leave the island by
Saturday, said National Guard spokeswoman Maj. Phyllis
Phipps-Barnes.
   The National Guardsmen arrived a month ago to take over from
1,100 federal troops sent by President Bush three days after the
Sept. 17 storm to restore order and stop looting.
   The storm destroyed most buildings and homes here and caused $1
billion in damages. Due to a near complete absence of local
authority, for three days following the hurricane looters cleaned
out most businesses and food stores.
   A senior officer of the Virgin Islands National Guard, who asked
not to be identified, said local police and Guardsmen could handle
security on the island now. ``There is no need for outside troops
to be on St. Croix,'' he said.
   The stateside units helped local officials in joint patrols and
maintaining an 11 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew, in effect since the storm.
   The withdrawal of the 1,100 troops ordered by Gov. Alexander
Farrelly in November outraged business leaders and the Chamber of
Commerce, who asked the White House to keep the troops there until
power and telephones were restored.
   Power is still out to 60 percent of the island's 55,000
residents, while 400 local and stateside linesmen are working to
restore downed power lines.
</TEXT>
