<FIRST>r a AM-LoiteringOrdinance     12-15 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Loitering Ordinance,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Drug Measure Ruled Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MELBOURNE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A circuit judge has ruled that the city's
year-old loitering ordinance, aimed at street drug dealers, is
unconstitutional.
   The law is vague and overbroad, and violates the Fourth and 14th
Amendments of the U.S. Constitution, Brevard Circuit Judge John
Antoon decided this week. The Fourth Amendment gives citizens
rights against unreasonable search and seizure and the 14th
Amendment guarantees the right to due process for any U.S. citizen.
   The ordinance, adopted in December 1988, made it unlawful to
loiter in or near Melbourne's streets or public places in a manner
for engaging in drug-related activities.
   Melbourne city officials stand by the law, which was closely
modeled after a long-standing ordinance adopted in Tacoma, Wash.,
that had withstood scrutiny.
   ``We wouldn't have adopted the ordinance if we had not felt it
would meet that test,'' City Manager Samuel Halter said Thursday.
   City Attorney Jim Reinman plans to meet with Brevard-Seminole
State Attorney Norm Wolfinger within the next week to discuss an
appeal, Halter said.
   Only one person had been charged under the ordinance, and the
case against him was dropped when the officer who arrested the man
left the Police Department and failed to appear in court, Halter
said.
   Antoon wrote in his order: ``While the city has passed this
legislation with the noble goal of reducing drug-related crime, it
has also given law enforcement and the state `carte blanche'
authority to prosecute innocent people exercising fundamental,
personal liberties.''
</TEXT>
