<FIRST>r a AM-Bishops-Celebrezze     12-15 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bishops-Celebrezze,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ohio Bishops Give Abortion Message to Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Catholic gubernatorial candidate's switch to
a pro-abortion stance prompted Ohio's Catholic bishops Friday to
criticize politicians who personally oppose abortion while
tolerating it publicly.
   ``We cannot judge the state of anyone's conscience before God.
We control no votes except the ones we cast personally,'' said a
statement read by Cincinnati Archbishop Daniel Pilarczyk at a news
conference at St. Peter in Chains Cathedral.
   ``But it is clear to us that, objectively speaking, the
tolerance of abortion in our society and the refusal to allow
religious and moral principles to influence public life are
positions which are both morally and socially wrong,'' the
statement said.
   Pilarczyk, who is president of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops, said the Ohio group's statement was prompted by
gubernatorial candidate Attorney General Anthony J. Celebrezze
Jr.'s change from an anti-abortion to pro-choice public position.
   Celebrezze, a Democrat and Catholic, announced his position
switch Dec. 2, then announced his candidacy for governor Monday. He
said he still personally opposes abortion.
   Many politicians have grown fearful of jeopardizing their
candidacies with anti-abortion stands. In California last month, an
underdog Catholic candidate for the state Assembly won a narrow
victory after a bishop barred her from taking communion because of
her support for abortion rights.
   Celebrezze was followed by anti-abortion pickets this week as he
opened his campaign for the 1990 Democratic nomination with
appearances in 14 cities. Concluding his tour Friday in
Springfield, he said he values the bishops' opinion but sees
abortion as an issue of individual vs. government choice.
   ``I respect the bishops tremendously,'' Celebrezze said. ``The
question here is what makes good public policy. I think we need to
do a lot more to prevent unwanted pregnancies.
   ``I strongly oppose abortion. The issue that people are reacting
to ... is who makes that decision. I believe it's an intensely
personal decision to be made by the woman with the advice of a
doctor, family, friends, whomever. But the government should not
make that decision.''
   Pilarczyk is chairman of the Ohio Catholic Conference, which
includes bishops from all of Ohio's six dioceses. He said the
statement, which did not refer to Celebrezze by name, was intended
for all holding or seeking public office.
   ``This is not just addressed to Mr. Celebrezze. ... One might
say that Mr. Celebrezze was the occasion of it, but he was not the
cause of it,'' Pilarczyk said in an interview.
   ``It's intended for all those to whom it applies. It's intended
to teach what the church teaches, and it's intended to teach those
in public life that they should not attempt to divorce moral
principle from public policy.''
   Signing the statement with Pilarczyk were the other diocesan
bishops in Ohio: James A. Griffin, Columbus; James R. Hoffman,
Toledo; James W. Malone, Youngstown; Albert H. Ottenweller,
Steubenville; and Anthony M. Pilla, Cleveland.
   The statement was also signed by Andrew Pataki, bishop of the
Eastern Rite church in Parma, and Louis Puscas, head of the
Romanian Rite church in Akron.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
