<FIRST>u w AM-Congressmen-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0631 12-15 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressmen-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0631,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Report on Secret Meeting with Colombian President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New material thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A six-member House delegation returned Friday
from secret meetings with Colombian President Virgilio Barco and
said they had seen a nation trying to resist intimidation by a
handful of cocaine traffickers.
   The congressmen praised Barco for his courage as a rash of
bombings and assassinations masterminded by drug lords and chips
away at the Colombian judicial system.
   ``You have to be there to understand the kind of fear that we
saw,'' Rep. William Hughes, D-N.J., told reporters.
   ``Colombia is indeed a battlefield,'' said Rep. Frank Guarini,
D-N.J., who noted Barco's desire for American help in attacking
money laundering, reducing the demand for cocaine and keeping
assault weapons from entering the country.
   All agreed that despite death threats against top Colombian
officials, President Bush should go ahead with plans to attend a
Feb. 15 drug summit in Colombia to demonstrate U.S. support for
Barco's battle.
   ``We will collect our forces in the Congress to provide the type
of resources that will be necessary to make this war victorious,''
said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., who led the visit, which was
requested by Barco and supported by the State Department.
   ``We will take our struggle to the United Nations, to the
Organization of American States, to our allies in Europe and
Japan,'' Rangel said.
   The lawmakers, all members of the House Narcotics Abuse and
Control Committee, also met with Colombia's defense and justice
ministers, the national police director, the attorney general,
Colombian presidential candidates and U.S. Ambassador Thomas
McNamara.
   ``In our meetings with them, it was apparent their determination
and the determination of the courts was there'' to apprehend drug
traffickers and clamp down on the production of cocaine and crack,
said Rep. Lawrence Coughlin, R-Pa., the ranking Republican on the
committee.
   Rangel, the panel's chairman, was joined by Reps. Benjamin A.
Gilman, R-N.Y., and Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
   Aides kept the two-day trip secret out of concerns that the
congressmen could become the targets of cocaine traffickers, who
have been blamed for a rash of violence that has wracked Bogota,
the capital.
   Among those killed have been 50 judges, two newspaper
publishers, the chief of the narcotics police and a leading
presidential candidate. A bombing earlier this month wounded an
estimated 1,000 people.
   Barco traveled to Washington Sept. 28-29 for discussions with
Bush and House leaders about American cooperation with the war on
drug traffickers he declared three months ago. The United States
has asked the Colombian government to extradite suspected
traffickers indicted in this country on drug charges.
</TEXT>
