<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     12-15 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Havel Calls for Justice, Not Revenge Against Communists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition activist Vaclav Havel
said Friday that if he is elected Czechoslovakia's first
non-Communist president in four decades he will try to prevent a
Communist witch hunt.
   ``There must be justice, but not revenge,'' said Havel, the
playwright and leader of the opposition Civic Forum, in an
interview with the state news agency CTK. ``I would try my best to
avoid a witch hunt in this country. Including Communists.''
   His comments followed word of a deepening split inside the
ruling party between hard-line and reform-minded members that could
lead to the establishment of a new democratic party.
   ``The Communist Party has 1.7 million members, all of them are
our compatriots and there are countless people among them who are
among the same as we are and who want this country to live in
democracy,'' said Havel.
   Rudolf Prevratil, spokesman for the recently founded reform
Communist group Democratic Forum, told CTK that next week's party
congress ``will show whether this movement can live inside the
Communist Party.''
   Reform members of the party are anxious to distance themselves
from the discredited regime of ex-party chief Milos Jakes and
former hard-line President Gustav Husak, who resigned last Sunday
after swearing in Czechoslovakia's first government not dominated
by Communists in 41 years.
   Since then, a dispute has developed over how to elect the
president. Under the constitution, the president is to be chosen by
the parliament within two weeks.
   But the Communist-dominated Parliament is reluctant to vote for
Havel, and is considering a proposal to throw the election open to
popular vote. Negotiations are under way to resolve the dispute
between the opposition and leaders of the Communist and other
smaller parties.
   A final resolution is not expected until after Parliament
reconvenes Dec. 19 and an extraordinary party congress is held next
Wednesday and Thursday.
   The interview with Havel is the first in a series to be
conducted by the state news agency, which is moving toward greater
independence from the Communist Party.
   ``The real presidential campaign has begun,'' the agency said,
adding that interviews would be conducted with all those considered
leading contenders.
   These include Alexander Dubcek, architect of the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms who was ousted in 1969 after the Soviet invasion;
Cestmir Cisar, the student candidate for president in 1968, later
expelled from the Communist Party; and Ladislav Adamec,
Czechoslovakia's prime minister until Nov. 7.
   Havel said he did not want the race to ``drive a wedge'' between
himself and Dubcek or between Czechs and Slovaks.
   He said his priority, if elected, would be to ``guard the quiet,
peaceful and dignified nature of the social movement, which some
call a revolution'' and not let it be sullied by ``intrigue,
politicking and all kinds of dirt.''
</TEXT>
