<FIRST>r w AM-FDA-SkinProducts     12-15 0196</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FDA-Skin Products,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Wants To Ban Use Of Word `Hormone' On Skin Product Labels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration wants to
prohibit manufacturers from using the word ``hormone'' on the
labels of nonprescription skin products.
   Labeling such as ``hormone cream'' implies that the product has
a therapeutic effect by altering the structure or function of the
body, the FDA said.
   However, the agency said that while nonprescription skin creams
can contain hormones, they are at low levels that have not been
shown to have any therapeutic effect.
   Under the FDA's proposed ban, manufacturers could not refer to
their products as ``hormone creams'' or say they contain
``hormones.'' But they would be allowed to include in their regular
listing of ingredients the names of hormones in the product, as
long as they are not listed prominently.
   The FDA has published the proposal in the Federal Register but a
final rule is not expected to be issued for a year, a spokeswoman
said.
   The ban would take effect six months after the final rule is
published, but the FDA is asking manufacturers to comply
voluntarily with the proposal before the rule becomes final.
</TEXT>
