<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessShelter     12-15 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Shelter,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Shelter Opens Across Street From Governor's Mansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SARAH OKESON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Gov. James R. Thompson glanced out a
bay window of the 40-room Governor's Mansion on Friday, he could a
homeless shelter opening across the street.
   What does the governor, who only spends about a third of his
time in the Greek Revival mansion, think about the shelter?
   ``It's in a good location,'' Thompson said earlier this week.
   He said he plans to volunteer soon at the shelter, a two-room
building.
   ``If we're neighbors ... I think it would be a great thing to
do,'' Thompson said.
   The shelter came to the neighborhood after downtown businesses
were reluctant to rent space for it, said Dick Lofgren in Mayor
Ossie Langfelder's office, which is enthusiastic about the facility
being run by Helping Hands of Springfield, a volunteer group.
   The Young Women's Christian Association offered use of its
vacant building, which had been used for storage, and the state
provided $46,000, Lofgren said.
   On Friday afternoon, volunteers were painting the walls and
sweeping floors. Homeless people were expected later in the day at
the shelter, which will offer soup, donuts and coffee.
   ``They've been constantly asking me, ever since they heard about
it, when it's going to open up,'' said volunteer Duane McShane.
   On Friday, the wait might have seemed particularly long. The
noon temperature was 4 degrees below zero _ 37 below with wind
chill factor, according to the National Weather Service.
   On any night, an estimated 30 to 50 homeless people are on the
streets of Springfield, Lofgren said.
   The shelter, which has a $50,000 annual budget, will be open 24
hours a day. It is intended to serve as an emergency shelter and
doesn't have beds.
</TEXT>
