<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--KlanMarch     12-15 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Klan March,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>KKK Cancels Weekend March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ku Klux Klan on Friday canceled a march
Saturday in support of two high school students who wore Klan-like
robes to school in a Halloween stunt, police said.
   Ron Lee of Morrow, who has identified himself as a Klan member,
told police the march was canceled because of a snowstorm, acting
Police Chief Richard McVey said. Lee said the Klan might try to
reschedule the march in the spring, McVey said.
   The Klan spokesmen said their rally was to have been in protest
of the suspension of two students who wore robes to class on
Halloween and shouted racial slurs. White and black residents
staged a march Nov. 3 to protest the youths' behavior and to
promote racial harmony.
   Community leaders in Oxford, a southwestern Ohio college town of
about 20,000 people, had predicted that residents would largely
ignore the march. About 95 percent of the town's residents are
white.
</TEXT>
