<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FreewayOpening     12-15 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freeway Opening,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Says Development Should Accompany New Freeway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL OAK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The last link of a $675 million freeway
has opened, more than 30 years after its proposal set off years of
bickering and court fights.
   The final link of the Walter P. Reuther Freeway opened to a
flood of cars Thursday evening. Reuther's daughter, Elizabeth
Dickmeyer, and the man who originally proposed Interstate 696,
former highway director John Mackie, attended the ceremony.
Reuther, a former president of the United Auto Workers union, died
in a 1970 plane crash.
   The final 9.1-mile section was finished this month and was the
last link of the 28.2-mile, $675 million freeway. The road is
expected to carry more than 100,000 vehicles daily at first with
that number growing to 170,000 daily, cutting east-west travel time
north of Detroit by as much as 30 minutes, state officials said.
   Interstate 696, which borders 16 cities, was first proposed in
1957.
   But the section between Interstate 75 and Lahser Road had to go
through seven communities, and it was up to them to decide which
routes to choose among five or six alternatives. They couldn't
agree, according to Paul Garceau, deputy district engineer for the
Michigan Department of Transportation.
   In 1966, then-Gov. George Romney held a marathon meeting with
the seven communities, but they still couldn't agree. Binding
arbitration upheld court challenges from the disgruntled
communities and eventually settled the route in 1968.
   But then the federal Environmental Protection Act of 1969, which
required environmental impact statements, further delayed
bid-letting on the last part of the freeway just completed.
   Land acquisition alone cost $81 million.
</TEXT>
