<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSAutopsies     12-15 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Autopsies,0386</SECOND>
<UNK>City Will Test Bodies For Disease And Warn Contacts</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An AIDS test will be routinely performed as part
of all autopsies in New York City, and the information will be used
to warn contacts of the deceased who may be at risk, health
officials said Friday.
   They emphasized that the identity of any body that tests
positive for HIV, the AIDS virus, would be kept confidential, as
required by the state's AIDS Confidentiality Law.
   Thus the medical examiner's office will not report names of
AIDS-positive corpses to the city Health Department. But it will
pass on such information as sex, race, age and neighborhood to help
studies of how and where the incurable disease is spreading, said
Dr. Charles S. Hirsch, the chief medical examiner.
   The only people to know names will be counselors who follow up
to warn sex or drug-abusing partners of the AIDS-positive dead that
they may have been exposed. The counselors will be trained and made
available to Hirsch by the Health Department, but will be under
Hirsch's command, said Dr. Stephen Joseph, city health commissioner.
   Hirsch's office estimated that at least 1,000 of the
approximately 8,000 post mortems performed annually will turn up
HIV infection. About 75,000 people die each year in New York, but
the medical examiner takes jurisdiction only in cases when deaths
are violent, suspicious, unexplained or occur without a doctor in
attendance.
   The AIDS testing will be put into effect at the medical
examiner's offices soon, after meetings with various AIDS advocacy
groups, said Ellen Borakove, speaking for Hirsch.
   The groups, representing racial, ethnic and social populations
hardest hit by AIDS, have generally resisted, on privacy grounds,
any forms of involuntary testing or disclosure.
   ``We're going to reserve comment until we find out just how it
is going to work,'' said Geoffrey Knox, spokesman for the Gay Men's
Health Crisis.
   Joseph developed the plan with Hirsch and said he could see no
sane reason to oppose it.
   ``What argument can anyone make to not warn the unsuspecting
partner of someone who is dead?'' said Joseph.
   He and Hirsch both have said that because of recent gains in
treating the disease, infected people reached early enough may
expect longer and better lives.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     12-15 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Threatens to Cut off Money to Rebellious Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Elias Hrawi's government
threatened Friday to stop paying soldiers loyal to Gen. Michel
Aoun, who refuses to recognize the new administration and give up
control of the Christian heartland.
   Prime Minister Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, appeled on televised
to Christians in east Beirut and the Christian-dominated coastal
zone to the north to renounce Aoun and help reunify Lebanon. He
said a new round of the 14-year civil war could begin at any time.
   ``My brother in the eastern area: I can guarantee that I am not
going to declare war on you, but I cannot guarantee that the war is
not going to explode again,'' Hoss said.
   Hrawi, 64, was elected president by Parliament on Nov. 24 with a
mandate to carry out a peace plan negotiated in October. Aoun, a
Maronite Catholic like Hrawi, has rejected the election and the
accord, demanding a specific timetable for withdrawal of the 40,000
Syrian troops in Lebanon.
   A government statement said future army payrolls would be
handled by Gen. Emile Lahoud, who was appointed army commander last
month after Hrawi dismissed Aoun.
   It said the Central Bank would not pay army salaries unless the
five brigade commanders in the Christian enclave submitted monthly
payrolls to Lahoud within five days.
   Hrawi controls the Central Bank, in Moslem west Beirut.
   Officials loyal to Aoun urged all institutions and employees to
``reject directives and instructions, which are null and void, from
those who deal with the occupiers,'' meaning the Syrians.
   The reference was to Hrawi's government, which is Syria and most
other governments support.
   Aoun became head of a Christian government after President Amin
Gemayel's term ended in September 1988 with Parliament unable to
agree on a successor. Hoss led a competing Moslem Cabinet until the
peace plan was worked out.
   In defiance of Hrawi, Aoun remains in his bunker beneath the
shell-battered presidential palace at Baabda, a Christian suburb
east of Beirut, and commands about 20,000 Christian troopers.
   In his televised appeal, Hoss told Christians he could not
guarantee peace ``as long as the secessionist movement led by
General Aoun exists. We have learned from past experience that wars
simply explode without anyone declaring them.''
   He called Aoun, 54, a ``mutineer who is leading the nation
toward final partition merely because he is hungry for power.''
   Most of Lebanon is controlled by Syria, whose soldiers are in
the country under a 1976 Arab League peacekeeping mandate. Aoun and
the Syrians fought a six-month artillery war that was ended in
September by an Arab League cease-fire.
   Hrawi and Lahoud, who commands 22,000 Moslem soldiers, have
established temporary headquarters at Ablah in the
Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley of eastern Lebanon.
</TEXT>
