<DOCNO> AP891215-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ReportCritic     12-15 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Report Critic,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Researcher Criticizes Pesticide Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A widely circulated report by the National
Research Council on pesticides used by farmers included information
that was deficient, out-of-date and in some respects one-sided, a
private researcher said Friday.
   However, Leonard P. Gianessi of the Washington-based non-profit
Resources for the Future said that despite what he perceived as
shortcomings, the NRC report issued Sept. 7 ``makes an important
contribution to the debate'' over the use of chemical pesticides.
   ``Perhaps my expectation was that it would provide answers to
most of these questions as well. It doesn't,'' he said. ``It
probably should be viewed as an important first try to get on top
of this issue and not as the final word.''
   The 450-page NRC report cited case studies of farmers using
alternative methods of production without the indiscriminate use of
chemicals. Among its many proposals was one for Congress to revise
federal farm policies so that environmentally sound production
methods would be encouraged.
   Environmentalists and many others applauded the report, based on
a three-year $625,000 study by a 17-member committee. The Kellogg
Foundation put up $410,000 for the study, and other financing
included $80,000 from the Agriculture Department.
   Gianessi presented his paper at a briefing on the NRC report
held by Resources for the Future, an independent group founded in
1952. Its specialty is research in development, conservation and
use of natural resources.
   In his critique, Gianessi said the NRC _ a branch of the
National Academy of Sciences _ used case studies that were ``data
deficient'' in making its case for alternative ways of producing
farm crops and livestock.
   ``Information is often not presented for such key factors as:
How often do these alternative farmers simply abandon fields
because they are too weedy? How much pesticide use is there on
these farms? The report hints at these questions but doesn't
provide any real quantified answers,'' he said.
   Also, Gianessi said, the case studies were for the 1986 crop
year _ and the report came out in 1989.
   ``The farms are referred to as if they are currently sustaining
their successes for 1986,'' he said.
   ``One of these farms has gone out of business. At least two
others have had to abandon key parts of their successful program
because of the emergence of a new pest in Florida and the
withdrawal of a key pesticide in California.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
