<FIRST>u i AM-Bulgaria     12-15 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition and Communists Meet, Demonstrations Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-NATO, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders and opposition
activists met Friday for the first time and agreed to hold more
talks while thousands of people again rallied demanding political
reforms.
   Constantin Trenchev of the independent trade union Podkrepa told
reporters that Andrei Lukanov, the No. 2 man in the Communist
leadership, and Premier Georgi Atanassov met with a Podkrepa leader
and three members of the Club for Glasnost and Perestroka.
   Trenchev did not attend the meeting. He said it was agreed that
a round of talks would begin next week, with the agenda still to be
decided.
   Parliament took these actions Friday: It agreed to have a
parliamentary commission headed by Lukanov investigate corruption
under former party leader Todor Zhivkov. The commission includes
representatives of independent groups who are not members of
Parliament.
   A commission was estalished to examine possible environmental
damage because of two power projects.
   Eliminated clauses in the penal code dealing with crimes against
the state and granted amnesty to all those punished under those
sections. It could not be immediately determined how many people
were affected by the amnesty.
   Several thousand people, many holding candles, gathered near the
Alexander Nevski cathedral, chanting ``Freedom!'' and ``Resign,
Resign!'' as they did during Thursday's mass demonstration in front
of Parliament when they called on Communist Party chief Petar
Mladenov and house speaker Stanko Todorov to quit.
   Many of the people first went to a rally outside Parliament but
marched to the cathedral when the reform Union of Democratic Forces
appealed to them to go to the church to honor Soviet human rights
champion Andrei Sakharov who died Thursday.
   About 2,000 people later left the cathedral and walked a
half-mile to the state television headquarters where they booed and
demanded an apology for television coverage of Thursday's
demonstration. They said the report had represented them as
extremists.
   Filip Bokov, recently appointed to head the television and radio
system, was drowned out by jeers as he tried to address the crowd.
   He insisted the television commentator had not used the word
``extremists'' but also apologized and TV later showed portions of
Thursday's demonstration.
   Thursday's angry protests be tens of thousands of people
developed after Parliament postponed action on demands that Article
1 of the Constitution, which guarantees the Communist Party the
dominant role, be scrapped.
   On Friday, Parliament unanimously approved a statement saying
the clause would be removed at its next session in January.
   The statement said Parliament considered dropping the article
``an important step on the way to solidifying political pluralism
and the development of a democratic state of law.''
   Proposals to set up free elections, which are scheduled to be
held by May, and to redistribute state-owned land also be will te
considered at the January session.
   The independent representatives at Friday's meeting were Zheliu
Zhelev and Petko Simeonov of the Club for Glasnost and Perestroika
and Georgi Spassov of Podkrepa.
</TEXT>
