<FIRST>u i AM-Comoros 1stLd-Writethru a0670 12-15 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comoros, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Troops Take Control of Comoros, Mercenaries Leave</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with more French, South African
comment; picks up 7th pvs `Most Comorans'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French mercenary and 21 of
his men arrived in South Africa on Friday after French troops
landed in the Comoros Islands and peacefully ended the mercenaries'
rule.
   Foreign Minister R.F. Botha told reporters most of the
mercenaries, who were in uniform, would be put on flights to France
within 48 hours and the future of their leader, Bob Denard, was
being discussed by France and South Africa.
   ``The idea is to get them out of here as soon as possible,''
said Dries Venter of the Foreign Ministry. He said the mercenaries
had been carrying sidearms, which were confiscated.
   Earlier Friday, French troops landed at the airport in Moroni,
capital of the Indian Ocean islands, and took control of security.
The French Defense Ministry said in Paris the Comoros government
had requested the ``military assistance mission.''
   ``France has not intervened in the Comoros,'' Premier Michel
Rocard of France said in Lome, Togo. ``We have lent a hand to a
process of returning to a more normal situation toward democracy.''
   Denard and the other European mercenaries boarded a South
African military plane four hours after the French landing and left
for South Africa.
   They trained and led the 600-man Presidential Guard, and had
controlled the Comoros since President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane
was assassinated Nov. 26.
   Most Comorans believe Denard and his mercenaries, who first put
Abdallah in power in 1978, were responsible for his death. Denard
has said a bodyguard accidentally shot Abdallah.
   South Africa and France had been the two largest aid donors to
the Comoros, a former French colony. South Africa, which has
extensive economic interests in the nation, had financed the
presidential guard.
   South Africa and France had cut off assistance, however, and
were pressuring Denard and his men to leave. Negotiations had been
going on for the past several days.
   Denard told a news conferece in Moroni on Thursday that he was
willing to relinquish control of the Comoros if the safety of his
men was guaranteed and if they were given an unspecified payment.
It was unclear Friday if those demands were met.
   French President Francois Mitterrand and Defense Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement said earlier this week that the French
military would not intervene in the Comoros.
   A French military spokesman said Friday that his nation's troops
were dispatched under the French-Comoran defense cooperation
agreement and came from the French Indian Ocean island of Mayotte,
185 miles away.
   The news agency Agence France-Presse reported from Moroni that
50 French paratroopers in helicopters landed Friday morning and
were followed by two transport planes full of troops.
   AFP said that as the first aircraft landed at Hahaya Airport,
about 250 Presidential Guardsmen stood at attention at one end of
the runway. Denard also was present, dressed in civilian clothes.
   Five other mercenaries arrived in Paris on Friday after an
overnight flight from Moroni.
   One of them, identified only as Lt. Didier, told reporters that
Denard ``didn't want to be king'' of the Comoros.
   ``He became it in spite of himself,'' Didier said.
</TEXT>
