<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     12-15 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Responds Coolly To Noriega Promotion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration dismissed on Friday as
a ``charade'' the promotion of Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
as head of government.
   As the United States has not recognized the Noriega-led
government since February 1988, the action by the People's Assembly
changes nothing, a State Department official said.
   American officials are under orders to have no dealings with the
Panamanian government on grounds that such actions would be
illegitimate.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger, asked about the
action by Panama's People's Assembly, told reporters:
   ``This is a charade and nonsense. As far as we're concerned at
least, there is no government in Panama anyway.
   ``For Noriega to be named head of a non-existent government, at
least in the view of the United States government, is putting him
in charge of nothing,'' Eagleburger said.
   The U.S. view is that the term of the last constitutionally
elected national assembly in Panama expired on Aug. 31 and that the
body that promoted Noriega has no legal or popular standing, the
State Department official said.
   He added that the 510 members of the assembly, none of whom
opposed Noriega's appointment, all were selected on the basis of
their loyalty to him.
   Noriega has been wanted by U.S. authorities for almost two years
on drug trafficking charges.
</TEXT>
