<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Icy Snowstorm Spreads from Plains to East Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Temperatures dropped to record lows in cities across the Midwest
and Great Plains on Friday as a storm dropped up to 30 inches of
snow before moving east later in the day.
   About 3 to 6 inches fell through Friday from Kansas to West
Virginia, with storm watches posted into Saturday in the Northeast.
Sheridan, Wyo., got 25 inches in two days, with lesser amounts
elsewhere in the state and up to 18 inches in the Colorado Rockies.
   At midday, snow was falling from southwestern New York state to
North Carolina and Tennessee and as far west as Wyoming and
Montana. Winter storm watches for Saturday were posted over much of
New England, New York and northern New Jersey.
   Up to 30 inches of snow fell in northeastern Wisconsin's Door
County in two days.
   Record lows included 26 below zero at Dickinson, N.D.; 19 below
at Dubuque, Iowa; 16 below at Burlington and Carroll, Iowa and
Concordia, Kan; and 15 below at Salina, Kan. Record low
temperatures were expected to be broken again Friday night.
   The low temperature for the nation Friday morning was 30 degrees
below zero at Chadron, Neb. Temperatures around the nation at 3
p.m. EST ranged from 11 degrees below zero at Lemmon, S.D., to 79
degrees at Kingsville, Texas.
   Snowfall during the 6 hours ending at noon included 3 inches at
Columbus, Ohio, Lexington, Ky., and Zanesville, Ohio; 2 inches at
Akron and Cincinnati, Ohio, Lewistown, Mont., and Pittsburgh, as
well as 1 inch at Indianapolis.
</TEXT>
