<FIRST>r w AM-GenericDrugs     12-15 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Generic Drugs,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Downgrading Rating of Products by Four Generic Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration is
downgrading the therapeutic rating of products made by four generic
drug companies because they submitted false or incorrect
information in their applications for FDA approval, the agency said
Friday.
   Many of the products already have been recalled by the
companies, or their distribution has been suspended.
   The lower rating tells physicians and pharmacists that the FDA
does not consider the drugs to be interchangable with the
brand-name drug.
   One of the companies, Quantum Pharmics of Amityville, N.Y., has
agreed to give up FDA approvals for nearly all its drugs, said
Carole Emerling, a spokeswoman for Quantum's parent company,
American Home Products.
   Quantum had stopped production on the 25 products in September.
The company has one drug left on the market, but Emerling said no
decision had been made on whether the other products will be
reintroduced.
   The FDA said it had downgraded the ratings of 29 products made
by Vitarine Pharmaceuticals of Springfield Gardens, N.Y., and that
the company has agreed to voluntarily relinquish approvals for the
products.
   The FDA has said it was initiating procedures to withdraw the
approvals.
   However, Vitarine president Roger Jordan said the company had
not agreed to give up the approvals. He said distribution of the
products was suspended in April and the company has resubmitted
data to the FDA in supplements to the drug approvals.
   The FDA also lowered the rating for a generic form of Dyazide, a
popular high blood pressure drug made by Bolar Pharmaceutical Co.
of Copiague, N.Y. The agency has said it wants to withdraw Bolar's
approval for that drug, which would leave no generic version of
Dyazide on the market.
   The FDA also said it has downgraded the ratings of three tablet
strengths of diazepam made by Superpharm Corp. of Bayshore, N.Y.
The company voluntarily recalled the products Dec. 7.
   The FDA is lowering the rating for orphengesic tablets,
orphengesic forte tablets and triamterene-hydrocholorothiazide
tablets made by Par Pharmaceuticals of Spring Valley, N.Y.
   The agency is moving to withdraw Superpharm's and Par's
approvals for those drugs.
</TEXT>
