<FIRST>u a AM-EmergencyLanding     12-15 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emergency Landing,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Makes Emergency Landing; Ash Suspected in Engine Trouble</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boeing 747 passenger jet made a safe
emergency landing here Friday after it flew through volcanic ash
and temporarily lost power to all four engines, the Federal
Aviation Administration said. There were no reports of injuries.
   The engine problems were reported immediately after KLM Royal
Dutch Airlines Flight 867 passed through ash from Redoubt Volcano,
which erupted Thursday and Friday. The volcano is 115 miles
southwest of Anchorage.
   The jet carrying 231 passengers and a crew of 14 landed at
Anchorage International Airport at 12:25 p.m. and taxied to a gate
under its own power, airport and FAA officials said.
   The plane was traveling to Anchorage from Amsterdam when the
crew reported smoke in the cockpit and loss of engine power at
11:50 a.m., FAA spokeswoman Mary Lou Wojtalik said. About eight
minutes later, the crew reported two of the engines had been
restarted, Wojtalik said. She said the other two were restarted
shortly afterward.
   The jet fell 13,000 feet during the engine trouble, Wojtalik
said.
   She said the volcanic ash was so fine that it went undetected by
radar, and the pilot was unaware of the ash until it appeared on
the plane's windshield.
   Flight restrictions had been imposed because of the volcanic
ash. Wojtalik said the KLM plane was flying where it was supposed
to be when the engine problems occurred.
</TEXT>
