<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Nolting     12-15 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Nolting,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ex-Ambassador to Vietnam Dies at 78</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frederick E. Nolting Jr., a career
diplomat and former U.S. ambassador to South Vietnam, has died. He
was 78.
   Nolting died of an aneurysm Thursday at the University of
Virginia Hospital, a family member said.
   Nolting joined the U.S. Department of State in 1946 and then
entered the foreign service. Before being sent to Saigon, he was a
political officer at the U.S. Embassy in Paris, deputy U.S.
representative to the North Atlantic Treaty Organization and
alternate U.S. representative to the Atlantic Council.
   President Kennedy named him ambassador to South Vietnam in April
1961. He served in Saigon until he was replaced by Henry Cabot
Lodge in August 1963.
   Three months after Nolting left the country, South Vietnamese
President Ngo Dinh Diem and his brother were assassinated in an
American-backed coup. Nolting was an ardent defender of Diem and
called U.S. involvement in the overthrow ``stupid'' and
``dishonorable.''
   Nolting retired from the foreign service in 1964 as a career
minister and returned with his family to Paris as vice president of
the international division of Morgan Guaranty Trust Co.
   In 1971, Nolting became a diplomat in residence at the
University of Virginia and then Olsson Professor of business
administration in the Colgate W. Darden Graduate School of Business
Administration.
   When the White Burkett Miller Center for Public Affairs opened
at the University of Virginia in 1975, he was named first director.
He became professor emeritus in 1982.
   Nolting is survived by his wife, Lindsay Crumpler Nolting, four
daughters and seven grandchildren.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
