<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0688 12-15 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Throws Out Convictions in Treason Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf `The Appeal' to insert name of fifth prisoner
freed, Muzi Malindi. Pickup 6th pvs, `Hundreds of ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The high court on Friday threw
out convictions imposed in the country's longest treason trial and
freed five black activists, including three prominent
anti-apartheid leaders jailed since 1985.
   Scores of jubilant supporters, including Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu, welcomed the men as they passed through Cape Town's
airport en route from Robben Island prison to their homes near
Johannesburg.
   ``It's a sign we are winning the struggle,'' said Tutu. ``We
knew that justice would prevail one day.''
   The three leaders of the United Democratic Front and one of
their co-defendants, a church worker, were convicted of treason in
November 1988 after a three-year trial. They received sentences
ranging from six to 12 years from a judge who contended the front
sought to incite anti-government violence.
   The Appeal Court in Bloemfontein overturned the verdicts against
those four and seven co-defendants convicted of terrorism. Six of
the seven received suspended sentences, but one, Muzi Malindi, was
given a five-year term and sent to the Robben Island penitentiary.
Malindi was a member of the Vaal Civic Association, an affiliate of
the United Democratic Front.
   Hundreds of chanting well-wishers greeted the five at
Johannesburg's airport. Police used guard dogs to control the
crowd, confiscated banners, and seized film from at least two news
photographers.
   The independent South African Press Association reported that a
woman in the welcoming crowd was bitten by a police dog and that
the Rev. Allan Boesak, an anti-apartheid leader, was arrested when
he tried to aid her. Police had no immediate comment.
   A five-judge appellate panel unanimously upheld defense lawyers'
arguments that the trial judge, Kees van Dijkhorst, improperly
dismissed one of the two legal experts assisting him in the trial.
   Van Dijkhorst asserted that law professor W.A. Joubert was too
sympathetic to the United Democratic Front because he had signed a
front-supported petition opposing a new constitution that
entrenched racially segregated politics.
   During the trial, most of the defendants were granted bail. But
van Dijkhorst repeatedly denied bail for the three leaders of the
front, a huge multiracial coalition formed in 1983 to campaign for
black political rights.
   ``We have not sacrificed more than so many others. We do not
feel bitter,'' said Patrick Lekota, one of the front leaders, after
being carried shoulder-high through the Cape Town airport. ``For
us, it does not stop here. It's the beginning of another chapter.''
   Van Dijkhorst ruled that the front was a ``revolutionary
organization'' that conspired with the African National Congress
guerrilla movement to provoke violence in black townships in 1984
in a bid to render South Africa ungovernable. The front was banned
in February 1988, but most of its leaders have circumvented or
defied the ban.
   Lekota, 41, the front's publicity secretary, was sentenced to 12
years in prison; Pope Molefe, 37, the front's national secretary,
and Moses Chikane, 41, secretary of the Transvaal Province branch,
were sentenced to 10 years. The Rev. Tom Manthata, 49, a church
field for the South African Council of Churches, was sentenced to
six years.
   ``We always believed in their innocence,'' said the Rev. Frank
Chikane, general secretary of the church council. ``Their
conviction and sentencing were examples of the grave miscarriage of
justice which the apartheid courts of South Africa hand down.''
   Lawyers for Human Rights, an association of civil rights
lawyers, hailed the Appeal Court ruling as ``an excellent victory''
that would help restore the credibility of the South African
judiciary.
   The group urged the government to disclose the cost of ``this
abortive prosecution which took years of blundering incompetence to
achieve nothing but red faces.''
   The trial began in 1985 in the farming town of Delams and was
shifted to Pretoria. Eleven of the original 22 defendants were
acquitted at various stages.
   One of the activists' lawyers, David Dyson, said the Appeal
Court ruling appeared to be based solely on legal questions and
doubted it was related to the changing political climate created by
President F.W. de Klerk's easing of curbs on opposition activity.
   The trial entailed 439 days of court proceedings spread over
more than three years. The 368-page indictment named more than 900
alleged co-conspirators, ranging from Tutu to African National
Congress leader Oliver Tambo. There were more than 220 witnesses
and the official court record contained about 30,000 pages.
</TEXT>
