<FIRST>r a AM-EversSlaying 1stLd-Writethru a0689 12-15 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Evers Slaying, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0689,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Find No Jury Tampering Evidence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `DeLaughter, who ..., to CORRECT date of trial
to 1964, sted 1963.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators have found no evidence of
jury tampering in the murder trial 26 years ago of a fertilizer
salesman charged in the slaying of civil rights activist Medgar
Evers.
   Charges against Byron De La Beckwith, a white supremacist who at
the time was a salesman in Greenwood, were dropped after two
all-white Hinds Circuit Court juries were unable to reach verdicts.
Allegations of possible jury tampering by a state agency recently
were raised.
   ``So far, there is absolutely no evidence to indicate jury
tampering,'' Assistant District Attorney Bobby DeLaughter said
Thursday. ``None were contacted. None were even aware that any
contact had been made with their employers until after the fact.''
   DeLaughter, who led the jury-tampering investigation into the
second, April 1964 trial, said he told a Hinds County grand jury
his findings Thursday in a closed-door meeting at the courthouse.
   Prosecutors now will turn their attention to Beckwith's first
trial earlier in 1964, although no allegations of jury tampering
have been raised about that trial.
   Evers, field director of the state NAACP, was shot to death June
12, 1963, outside his home in northwest Jackson.
   Beckwith's rifle, bearing one of his fingerprints, was found
near the Evers home. Beckwith contended the rifle had been stolen
from him.
   DeLaughter said Thursday that prosecutors are still trying to
decide if the murder case itself can be reopened and new charges
sought.
   ``My opinion is unless we can have the benefit of the evidence
available in 1964 and newly discovered evidence, it would be
extremely hard to get around the speedy trial question,''
DeLaughter said.
   Beckwith, 68, now lives in Signal Mountain, Tenn.
   The district attorney's office investigated Beckwith's April
1964 trial after a Jackson newspaper reported Oct. 1 that the state
Sovereignty Commission, the state's segregation spy agency,
screened potential jurors.
   ``What was done was the (Sovereignty Commission) investigator
would call up employers and say, `What can you tell me about this
person?''' DeLaughter said.
   ``While I consider it extremely unethical for one state agency
to be working against state prosecutors, it still is not a crime,''
DeLaughter said.
   The commission, formed by the 1956 Legislature, died after its
funding was cut off in 1973.
   DeLaughter said he and others in the district attorney's office
contacted 11 of the 12 jurors in the second Beckwith trial and are
seeking the other juror.
   DeLaughter said he and investigators talked earlier with former
Sovereignty Commission Director Erle Johnston of Forest and
reviewed records Johnston kept. The commission's own records are
sealed in a vault on orders of the 1977 Legislature.
   The rifle and all other evidence from the two trials are missing
from the Hinds County circuit clerk's office.
   But DeLaughter said there's no indication the evidence was
stolen. If cases are inactive for many years, the law allows the
evidence to be destroyed.
</TEXT>
