<FIRST>u i AM-SovietTroops 1stLd-Writethru a0696 12-15 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Troops, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0696,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Disclose Troop Strength Abroad</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to ADD more Fitzwater comment; pickup
4th pvs, `Petrovsky did...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union announced Friday that it
has 627,500 troops abroad, its first such disclosure of its foreign
forces, and said it would like to bring them home by the year 2000.
   However, Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky, who
made the announcement, said the pullouts would not be unilateral
and would depend on negotiations with other nations.
   White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said the statement
was ``encouraging.'' He said the U.S. position is that all such
matters are to be worked out at the conventional forces talks under
way in Vienna.
   Petrovsky did not give a breakdown of troop deployment and said
it was well known that the troops were stationed in Warsaw Pact
countries and in Mongolia. He did not elaborate.
   Next week, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze is to
meet leaders of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization. Diplomats
said they believed the troop strength announcement was intended to
help pave the way for that visit.
   Under a U.N.-negotiated agreement, the Soviet Union withdrew
more than 100,000 troops from Afghanistan and has said that all
nations should agree not to station their soldiers abroad.
   Petrovsky declined to discuss possible troops withdrawals from
Eastern Europe, saying those were subject to negotiations in Vienna.
   A year ago, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced his
nation would make massive, unilateral cuts in soldiers and military
equipment overseas.
   Petrovsky said that next year it is possible to conclude a
practical agreement on withdrawal of conventional forces in Europe.
``But in order to achieve the aim of withdrawing troops to national
boundaries, it is necessary to use different bilateral and
multilateral arrangements and talks,'' he said.
</TEXT>
