<FIRST>u i AM-Flight103 2ndLd-Writethru a0713 12-15 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0713,0893</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Year Later, Some Clues in Crash, But No Prosecutions Near</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON9,10,13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 7 `It would' with one graf to CLARIFY reference to
Esson; pickup 8th pvs `Asked whether...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly one year after the bombing of
Pan Am Flight 103, investigators said Friday they have assembled
some clues to the international terrorist plot but are not close to
prosecuting anyone.
   ``What we are doing in effect is trying to piece together an
international terrorist jigsaw,'' said George Esson, a police
official. ``We have some of the pieces, some we are trying to
place, and some we have yet to find.''
   Esson spoke as Scottish officials announced the first public
inquiry to be held into the explosion of Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, on Dec. 21, 1988, that killed all 259 people on board and
11 people on the ground.
   The inquiry, to be held next year before an independent judge,
will be the first in which members of the public will have the
chance to attend the proceedings. A criminal police investigation
and a Transport Department investigation alreday are under way in
Britain.
   Speaking at a news conference, officials said one focus of the
investigation is the Popular Front For the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command, a radical Palestinian faction headed by
Ahmed Jibril.
   But they said other groups also were under investigation.
   ``It would be right to say that we have focused our attention on
one group but it would be unwise for us to exclude others,'' Esson
said.
   Asked whether that one group was the PFLP-GC, he said,
``certainly.''
   Jibril, a former Syrian army officer, has denied involvement
though he has said his faction has used devices like the one that
brought down Flight 103.
   Lord Fraser, Scotland's senior law officer, and Esson, chief
constable of the Dumfries and Galloway Constabulary, told reporters
they also are interested in Mohammad Abu Talb, a member of another
radical Palestinian group who is charged in Sweden with four
bombings in northern Europe.
   Also Friday in Washington, attorneys for families of 13 members
of the flight crew filed a lawsuit alleging that two companies
failed to provide adequate security. The lawsuit says Alert
Management Systems Inc. and Pan Am World Services Inc., which
provided security at Frankfurt and Heathrow airports, failed to
comply with minimum security procedures.
   In New York, Pan Am spokesman Alan Loflin said the airline
hadn't heard of the lawsuit.
   Esson said the police investigation has encompassed 52 countries
and Fraser said West Germany, Malta and Sweden have been ``the
focus of important areas of investigation.''
   Investigators have said the bomb was made of a plastic explosive
packed in a radio-cassette player in a suitcase loaded into a
forward cargo hold of the Boeing 747.
   They released photos Friday showing the reconstruction of the
forward hold, with a gaping hole, and the reconstructed metal
container which held the suitcase bomb.
   Fraser said significant progress had been made in identifying
other contents of the suitcase, including clothing.
   He said he ordered the Scottish public inquiry now because the
police investigation had reached a stage where he thought it would
be ``appropriate.'' He did not elaborate, but said the inquiry
could be postponed or canceled if criminal proceedings appeared
likely.
   The public inquiry, formally known as a fatal accident inquiry,
will be held next year although a date and a presiding judge have
not yet been selected, Fraser said.
   He confirmed he had requested Swedish permission for Scottish
police to remove clothing from Abu Talb's Swedish home, reportedly
to compare it with the recovered shreds.
   ``I have at present no intention to seek the extradition of Abu
Talb,'' Fraser said.
   Esson would not say how many individuals were under
investigation nor whether all were Arabs. Some are in a position
where they could be extradited, he said.
   Scottish police still believe the bomb ``either started or
passed through Frankfurt airport'' where the flight originated, he
said. West German police maintain that has not been proven.
   Unconfirmed news reports have said the suitcase arrived in
Frankfurt on an Air Malta flight from the Mediterranean island and
was transferred onto the Pan Am flight without an accompanying
passenger.
   Esson said he believed police will obtain enough evidence to
prosecute the bombers, but said ``there are more investigations to
be conducted.''
   The photographs released Friday were of sections of the plane,
painstakingly reconstructed from wreckage scattered over 845 square
miles to determine precisely how it was destroyed.
   The reconstruction was done by the Department of Transport's Air
Accidents Investigation Branch based at Farnborough, southwest of
London, which will publish a report on its findings in the first
half of 1990.
   One photograph shows the fuselage, including the forward cargo
hold area where the suitcase bomb exploded. The section 55 feet
long, 27 feet high and 25 feet wide shows a gaping hole. The metal
is peeled back, illustrating what investigators called the
``petaled out'' effect produced by the explosion.
   Another photo shows the reconstructed metal cargo container,
with the Pan Am insignia on the side, in which the suitcase had
been loaded onto the plane.
</TEXT>
