<SECOND>AM-Czech Border,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Supports Dismantling Border Barriers with Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Iron Curtain'' of barbed
wire and other barricades along Czechoslovakia's border with West
Germany also should be dismantled, Defense Minister Miroslav Vacek
said Friday.
   Czechoslovakia started removing parts of its barriers along the
Austrian border on Monday but left untouched the fenches and
obstacles on the frontier with West Germany.
   Vacek told a news conference the ``army leadership ... proposes
the Czechoslovak government evaluate the possibility of eliminating
engineering and technical obstacles along the entire Austrian and
West German border.''
   He announced that Communist Party cells within the armed forces
would be disbanded next month and said there were plans to shorten
the term of compulsory military service from 24 months to 18 months.
   ``The Czechoslovak army is going to be built on principles of
openness and democracy for all citizens, but without political
parties,'' Vacek said in reporting the planned elimination of
Communist party cells in the military, ending more than four
decades of political activity including indoctrination.
   It was recently announced that party cells in the police force
would be eliminated.
   Vacek, a member of the Communist Party, was sworn in Dec. 10 as
a minister in Czechoslovakia's first government not dominated by
Communists since 1948.
