<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1948EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-GrandJury     12-15 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grand Jury,0842</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans District Attorney Indicted on Charge of Aiding Bookie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District Attorney Harry Connick was indicted
by a federal grand jury Friday for allegedly aiding a New Orleans
bookie by returning seized gambling records.
   Eight others were also named in the indictment for running or
aiding the $2,000 a day sports gambling operation. They included
convicted bookmaker Walton K. Aucoin, 49, of New Orleans and former
assistant U.S. attorney Patrick Fanning, who is now Aucoin's
attorney.
   Also indicted were actor Paul Burke, 63; Wilson P. Abraham, 70,
a New Orleans real estate developer; William G. Condon, 34, no
address; Steven Bertolino, 57, no address; Iris Ethridge, 30, no
address; and Darleen Aucoin Toca, 27, no address.
   Condon, Bertolino, Aucoin, Ms. Ethridge and Ms. Toca were
charged with owning and conducting an illegal gambling operation.
Fanning, Abraham and Burke were accused of aiding the operation by
helping Connick devise the excuse for returning the records to
Aucoin.
   The excuse was that Aucoin needed the records to pay his federal
taxes, specifically, to file his December federal gambling stamp
tax returns.
   U.S. Attorney John Volz said that since the indictment included
Fanning, who worked with him in the federal prosecutor's office in
New Orleans, the case was being handled by the Justice Department's
Public Integrity division from Washington.
   Burke, a New Orleans native who was in the movie ``Valley of the
Dolls,'' and Ms. Ethridge also were charged with perjury for
allegedly lying to the grand jury investigating the case.
   Connick, district attorney in New Orleans since 1974, denied any
wrongdoing. At a news conference attended by about 150 of his staff
members and supporters, he accused Volz of carrying out a personal
vendetta, complete with ``Brown Shirt'' tactics.
   ``The U.S. attorney's office is using the Justice Department in
Washington, D.C., to do his dirty work for him,'' Connick said.
   Connick said he would not resign and would run for re-election
to a fourth term next year, even if the case is still pending. He
said he did not expect the indictment to affect his handling of his
office.
   ``I'm not going to roll over and play dead for John Volz or
anybody else,'' Connick said, sparking enthusiastic applause from
the crowd of supporters.
   When the grand jury investigation surfaced in January, Connick
said the probe centered on the way the bookmaker, Aucoin, got
copies of the betting sheets seized in a Dec. 4, 1988, raid on his
apartment.
   At the time Connick said he received telephone calls on behalf
of Aucoin from Fanning, Abraham and Burke, and he acknowledged that
he got copies of the gambling records for Aucoin.
   ``There is nothing unusual, nothing illegal, about a prosecutor
returning to the accused his property or copies of his property,''
Connick told the news conference.
   He denied having been advised by his staff or police that
returning the property would help a gambling operation.
   ``Despite being advised by the New Orleans police and his own
staff that defendant Aucoin needed the bookmaking records solely to
pay and collect the illegal bookmaking debts and to continue the
illegal gambling business without disruption, defendant Connick,
without examining records and before the case had been referred to
or accepted by his office for prosecution, ordered the return of
copies of the bookmaking records to defendant Aucoin, who he had
been informed was one of the largest bookmakers in Louisiana,'' the
indictment said.
   Connick also told Fanning he would attempt to get Aucoin's
Jaguar returned to the bookmaker, despite being advised by police
that Aucoin used the car in paying and collecting gambling debts,
the indictment said.
   All the defendants face a maximum 25 years in prison and a
$500,000 fine if convicted. The perjury counts could net Burke and
Ms. Ethridge an extra five years and $250,000 fines each.
   Volz has denied any personal grudge. He refused to elaborate on
the indictment at a Friday news conference.
   Aucoin was released the same day of his 1988 arrest without
having to post bond. He was described by police as a three-time
convicted bookmaker who catered to high rollers.
   Connick acknowledged that the day after the arrest he asked
police for copies of gambling records, at Fanning's request.
   Connick contended he acted in accordance with state criminal
procedures, which he said allow defendants to see evidence against
them so their attorneys can prepare a defense.
   Aucoin had not been charged at the time. Connick did not
formally charge him until after the U.S. attorney wrote in a Jan.
24 letter that the grand jury had made Connick a target in their
investigation.
   Frank DiSalvo, attorney for Fanning, said Friday his client has
done nothing wrong. Abraham did not immediately return a telephone
call to his home. There are no telephone listings for the other
defendants in the New Orleans directory.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
