<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina     12-15 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Shakeup Follows Economic Nosedive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Menem, under
attack for his handling of the nation's economic crisis, on Friday
accepted the resignation of his economy minister and shuffled two
other Cabinet posts.
   In another development, the Central Bank declared a bank holiday
Monday to let shaky financial markets settle. By Tuesday, banks and
exchange houses will have been closed for three of the past six
working days.
   Antonio Erman Gonzalez, an accountant and former provincial
treasury secretary, was named to replace Economy Minister Nestor
Rapanelli. Gonzalez served briefly in the Central Bank as a vice
president and has been in the Cabinet as minister of health since
Menem's May 14 election.
   Menem's former campaign manager, Julio Mera Figueroa, was
appointed interior minister to replace Eduardo Bauza, who was named
minister of health. Figueroa is a longtime strategist in Menem's
Peronist Party.
   ``I have resigned, and if you are looking for scandalous
statements, then you haven't gotten to know me very well in five
months,'' Rapanelli told reporters.
   Asked as he walked out of the Treasury Building after noon what
he intended to do in the future, Rapanelli replied, ``I'm going to
have lunch.''
   Menem canceled a news conference Friday evening. Presidential
spokesman Humberto Toledo told reporters no other Cabinet changes
would be made and the new ministers will be sworn in Monday.
   ``The government will continue along the same general lines,''
declared Foreign Minister Domingo Cavallo, a Harvard-educated
economist.
   The Cabinet shakeup followed a 6-week plunge of the austral on
foreign exchange markets, soaring interest rates, strikes by
teachers, doctors, court clerks and other public employees for
higher wages and rekindled inflation.
   Menem's tax reform and 1990 budget proposal have stalled in
Congress, and organized labor stepped up its criticism that two
stabilization plans imposed since he took office in July were aimed
at curtailing inflation by forcing workers to accept cuts in real
wages.
   Last week, Menem officially devalued the austral and raised
public service rates again. He angered businessmen by increasing
taxes on exports and suspending for two years the repayment of
principal on internal bonds.
   Labor leaders, politicians and businessmen were cautious in
their assessment of the political shakeup.
   ``It was unavoidable,'' said Guerino Andreoni, co-director of
the 3 million-member General Confederation of Labor.
   Osvaldo Cornide, director of the Argentine Chamber of Merchants,
said Rapanelli had concentrated on curtailing inflation to the
exclusion of other important goals, such as controlling interest
rates and wage levels.
   Gonzalez, a member of the small Christian Democrat Party, is the
third economy minister in Menem's government. The first, Miguel
Roig, died of a heart attack six days after he was sworn in.
   Gonzalez' appointment was expected to appeal to organized labor
and factions of the Peronist Party that disagree with Menem's plans
to reduce state expenditures, sell public companies, lower tariff
barriers and increase taxes.
   Aldo Ducler, a Rapanelli aide who also resigned, called the
departing economic team ``a dike against the demands of those who
resisted the modernization of the economy.''
   Rapanelli, 60, is a former executive of the Bunge and Born grain
trading multinational synonomous with ``big business'' in this
South American country. It is viewed with distaste by unions and
leftist elements within Menem's party.
   His resignation has been expected since the free market austral
plunged to 1,560 per dollar on Thursday from 1,020 the week before.
   Meanwhile, supermarkets and other stores began to mark up prices
drastically in anticipation of inflation projected to top 30
percent in December. The November rate was 6.5 percent; the October
rate, 5.6 percent.
   Mera Figueroa is a former national deputy with long ties to the
Peronists. During the 1970s, he was aligned with its leftist
factions and imprisoned for three years following a 1976 military
coup.
   After the restoration of democracy in 1983, Mera Figueroa worked
within the party and was an early backer of Menem, then a
provincial governor.
</TEXT>
