<FIRST>r a AM-MrDinkins     12-15 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mr Dinkins,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Press Secretary Wants Dinkins Addressed as `Mister'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The raucous news conferences of the Ed Koch era
will have a touch more class under his more sedate successor, his
press secretary said. To begin with, call him ``Mr. Dinkins.'' But
first, raise your hand!
   That was the word Friday from Albert Scardino, the press
secretary for Mayor-elect David Dinkins, as he laid down some
``rules of conduct'' for the City Hall press corps.
   Scardino, a former New York Times reporter who won a Pulitzer
Prize for editorial writing, told reporters that Dinkins ``places a
high value on courtesy and mutual respect'' and would like to be
addressed as ``Mr. Dinkins'' at press conferences.
   Scardino said reporters also should raise their hands when they
want to ask questions and be recognized before doing so, rather
than blurt them out in competition with other journalists.
   ``I would be grateful to you if you would please respectfully
pose your questions, `Mr. Dinkins'. He'll respond to you,''
Scardino said at the third in a series of press briefings he has
set up during the transition of government from the Koch
administration.
   ``I would appreciate it if you would please try to restrain
yourself and not ask out of turn,'' he said.
   Asked if Dinkins had complained to him about the way the press
asked its questions, Scardino said, ``No. He has not.''
   Dinkins said later he did not mind how reporters addressed him.
He said he did not know Scardino was going to make such a request
and had not asked him to do so.
   However, he said, ``I do think it would be useful if reporters
were not discourteous to each other.''
   At Mayor Edward I. Koch's news conferences, reporters tend to
call him ``Mr. Mayor,'' ``Mayor'' or ``Your Honor.'' Koch seemed
amused by the whole thing when he learned about the request.
   ``I wonder what it would have been like if they called me Mr.
Ed, like a horse?'' Koch said.
</TEXT>
