<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-PLO     12-15 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-PLO,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Official Confirms Attack, Despite Disavowal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commander of Yasser Arafat's PLO faction
insisted Friday that his forces had raided a Syrian army base in
south Lebanon, though PLO headquarters condemned the attack.
   Thursday's attack, which Lebanese police also blamed on Arafat's
mainstream Fatah group, threatened to undermine efforts to end a
six-year rift between Arafat and Syrian President Hafez Assad.
   Police reported 15 people were killed and 43 wounded when
Palestinian guerrillas from Fatah, the biggest faction in the
Palestine Liberation Organization, attacked Syria's military
intelligence headquarters in south Lebanon at the village of Rmaile.
   ``The operation was carried out by Palestinians. No Lebanese
took part in the attack,'' said the Fatah commander, who identified
himself only by his nom-de-guerre of Abu-Maher.
   He said Fatah commanders in south Lebanon prepared the attack
without consulting Arafat.
   ``No one knew about it at PLO headquarters in Tunis,'' he said
in an interview in Sidon's Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp 25 miles
south of Beirut. It is the main PLO base in Lebanon.
   A statement issued Thursday by PLO headquarters in Tunis,
Tunisia, denounced the attack without explicitly denying that Fatah
members were involved.
   The statement said the PLO had ordered an investigation in
collaboration with the other factions in Sidon to identify the
``authors and commanders'' of the attack.
   As chief of the PLO umbrella group, Arafat presides over several
factions of guerrilla fighters who sometimes launch independent
attacks or war among themselves.
   Syrian officials in Damascus made no comment on Thursday's
fighting, which undermined efforts by Arafat and Assad to achieve
long-elusive Arab unity before convening an international Middle
East peace conference.
   About 150 of Abu-Maher's fighters reportedly stormed and
ransacked the Syrian base three miles north of Sidon to free
comrades held there.
   Police said the dead included four Syrians and five Palestinians.
   They said a Communist Party guerrilla, two leftists and three
members of the Nasserite militia that has ruled Sidon since
Lebanon's civil war broke out in April 1975 were also killed at a
checkpoint north of Sidon when they clashed with the returning
Fatah fighters.
   The guerrillas, led by Maj. Abdel-Raouf Zaarour, freed 15
prisoners held by the Syrians, including Lebanese and Fatah
members, in the two-hour clash at Rmaile.
   About 2,000 Palestinians are held in Syrian prisons. Most were
rounded up in 1983 during a Syrian-backed mutiny by radical groups
that drove Arafat's forces out of the north Lebanon port of Tripoli.
   ``We have the right to strike at the Syrians and defend our
rights. We're not under Syrian trusteeship,'' said Abu-Maher.
Syrian forces, who came to Lebanan under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate, police most of country.
</TEXT>
