<FIRST>r a AM-DrugAgency     12-15 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agency,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>State's Embattled Drug-Treatment Czar Resigns, So Cuomo Gives Him
New Spot</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo's drug treatment czar,
under fire for alleged shoddy management of his agency and helping
friends obtain lucrative state contracts, resigned Friday.
   The embattled bureaucrat, former heroin addict Julio Martinez,
was quickly given a new state job by Cuomo at a ``comparable''
salary.
   Martinez, 45, one of the Cuomo administration's highest ranking
Hispanics, received $87,338 as director of the state Division of
Substance Abuse Services. He will become head of the state prison
system's drug treatment programs, said Cuomo spokesman Gary Fryer.
   Only a few hours earlier, but before Martinez had a lengthy
meeting with several top Cuomo aides, a spokesman said Martinez had
no plans to quit.
   Martinez came under fire Thursday when the state Commission on
Government Integrity, after a year-long probe, outlined a string of
alleged abuses and called for an overhaul of the Martinez-led state
substance abuse division.
   In his resignation, Martinez said the commission's report failed
to present ``a complete and balanced view'' of his division's work,
but the charges ``have effectively precluded my ability to provide
strong and continuing leadership within the agency.''
   Cuomo, in a letter to Martinez, said the job he had held was
``undoubtedly one of the most difficult positions in public service
anywhere in the United States.''
   The Martinez-headed agency also had come under fire from the
state comptroller's office and Cuomo's own management advisers. The
division announced a restructuring after that earlier criticism.
   Fryer said Martinez got a new job ``because the governor has a
very high regard for Julio and always has. Julio's ability to
motivate and inspire people to seek and participate fully in
treatment is a great asset to the state.''
   Fryer also noted that in his new job, Martinez ``would not have
the administrative burden'' he had in the old job.
   Martinez, a native of Puerto Rico and a drug treatment activist
in New York City, was picked to head the state's drug treatment
efforts by then-Gov. Hugh Carey in 1979. Hispanic leaders recently
had pressed Cuomo to keep Martinez in that post despite the
critical reports about his agency.
   Traditionally, Cuomo doesn't fire cabinet members he's unhappy
with, they simply resign, as Martinez did.
   The governor, who is facing an expected re-election race next
year, has recently been trumpeting a major new state effort to
battle drug abuse.
   On Thursday, the Cuomo-appointed anti-corruption commission said
Martinez's agency suffered from an intricate web of favoritism and
infighting. The commission said friends of Martinez won
million-dollar, drug-treatment contracts that never led to any
treatment.
   Three of four residential drug treatment programs investigated
over the last year failed to open a single bed, despite millions of
dollars in state funding, said the commission, headed by Fordham
Law School Dean John Feerick.
   The Ferrick Commission said Martinez, over the objection of
other top division officials, frequently had intervened on behalf
of friends and long-time associates to arrange funding for their
proposed drug-treatment programs.
   ``The evidence concerning all four programs under investigation
indicates that a personal connection to Director Martinez or other
executive staff members smoothed the way for DSAS funding,'' the
commission said.
   The commission report didn't call for Martinez to be replaced.
Spokeswoman Linda Sachs said Friday that the commission has not yet
decided whether to recommend a criminal investigation.
</TEXT>
