<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Military     12-15 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Military,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Soviet Military Cutbacks on Schedule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet military budget for next year is 8.2
percent lower than for 1989 and unilateral cutbacks have reduced
Soviet armed forces by 256,000 personnel, a senior army officer
said Friday.
   Col. Gen. Nikolai Chervov told a news conference that under
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform program ``the image of the
armed forces is changing.''
   He said military staffs were going ahead with the plan to cut
troop strength by 500,000 by 1991.
   Plans for the cutbacks and reduced military spending were
announced by Gorbachev in a speech to the United Nations on Dec. 7,
1988.
   ``As of today, we have carried out 50 percent of our goal, we
have reduced our troops by 256,000 people,'' said Chervov, director
of the General Staff. He said there has been an additional
reduction of 173,000 military cadets.
   ``We have substantially reduced major military maneuvers and we
are reducing the plans for military materiel and weapons,'' he said.
   As of Jan. 1, 1990, Soviet troop strength will consist of
3,993,000 soldiers, sailors and airmen, compared to America's 2.2
million military personnel, according to Chervov.
   He did not specify where the cuts were made, but said the
reductions were not limited to Eastern Europe and applied to all
branches of the armed forces.
   Chervov said the 1990 military budget is 70.9 billion rubles
($114.8 billion), compared to 77.3 billion rubles for this year.
   Some of the money slashed from the military budget will be used
to convert military production plants into civilian operations to
produce more consumer goods, he said, but he gave no figures.
   Gorbachev's economic reforms include increasing consumer goods
to alleviate the country's chronic shortages.
</TEXT>
