<FIRST>r a AM-GiftsReturned     12-15 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gifts Returned,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thief Returns Gifts, Leaves Money to Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON FOURNIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A thief who ransacked a house, raided
the refrigerator, unwrapped about 40 Christmas presents and made
off with some of the gifts apparently had a change of heart.
   The thief returned the packages the next day with about $5 in
change and this note:
   ``Please forgive me. Here are your belongings and some money to
fix the window. It may not be enough, but I'll keep bringing some
til I pay you back fully. I'm very sorry. Please accept my apology
and please don't send me away.''
   Pam Shigley, 31, said the presents were found Thursday on her
porch by her 10-year-old daughter, Kim, with about $5 in nickels
and dimes. Mrs. Shigley said the money probably came from a change
jar that the thief spilled in the house the day before.
   The presents were in their original boxes. ``I was amazed. My
heart was broke when they all got stolen,'' she said. ``When they
came back, I thought, `Jesus, people really do have a conscience.'''
   Mrs. Shigley said she may return the favor. ``I thought of
leaving a note out there to wish him a merry Christmas and thank
him for having a conscience, and I've even thought of leaving a
small gift out there for him.''
   Her other daughter, Stephanie, 12, arrived home from school
Wednesday to find the back door window broken.
   ``Apparently, they came in and made themselves at home. There
was cereal and chocolate cookies and cherry pie filling laying
out,'' Mrs. Shigley said. She later said she believes only one
thief was involved.
   The presents under the family Christmas tree were unwrapped, and
about seven were missing. ``The rest were open for everybody to
see,'' she said. ``All my kids know all their surprises.''
   Springdale, a city of about 23,000 people in the northwestern
corner of Arkansas, is about 100 miles east of Tulsa, Okla.
</TEXT>
