<DOCNO> AP891215-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Brandley 1stLd-Writethru a0761 12-15 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brandley, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0761,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Attorney Says Brandley Won't Be Released Any Time Soon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of DeGeurin, sted DeGuerin, throuhout; no
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals on Friday
stalled defense attorneys' efforts to have death row inmate
Clarence Brandley released on bail, ending his hopes of freedom by
Christmas.
   The court, which overturned Brandley's capital murder conviction
earlier this week, ruled Friday that a Galveston judge would have
to prove he had jurisdiction in the case before a bond hearing set
for Monday could take place.
   Defense attorney Mike DeGeurin said the ruling essentially puts
an end to efforts to free Brandley before Christmas _ or even
before a third trial could take place.
   ``The announcement of the (prosecutor's) filing of a new trial
effectively denies any hope of Clarence Brandley being freed or
even coming off death row,'' DeGeurin said.
   Montgomery County District Attorney Peter Speers said Thursday
he would ask the appellate court to reverse its decision and,
failing that, would retry Brandley for the capital murder.
   Speers filed a motion with the Court of Criminal Appeals asking
the court to prevent the Galveston judge from conducting the bond
hearing in the meantime.
   The appeals court said the Galveston judge would have until Jan.
2 to prove why he has jurisdiction to decide bail for Brandley.
   DeGeurin, however, said he had decided to withdraw his motion
for bail from the Galveston court. He said Brandley's release would
be stalled until the Court of Criminal Appeals issues a decision on
the prosecutor's request that it reverse its decision.
   ``I'm disappointed that the prosecution hasn't gone ahead and
dismissed the indictment and instead is seeking to keep Clarence on
death row while they're asking for a reversal,'' DeGeurin said.
   Brandley, 38, was convicted in the rape-strangulation of
16-year-old Cheryl Dee Fergeson of Bellville, who was killed in
1980 while attending a volleyball tournament at Conroe High School.
   The appeals court Wednesday set aside the verdict, saying
Brandley did not receive a fair trial.
   Brandley, who is black, was a janitor at the school when Miss
Fergeson was attacked. Miss Fergeson was white. Brandley supporters
contend the former janitor's conviction was racially motivated.
   Brandley's first trial ended with a hung jury. In the second
trial, an all-white jury convicted him of capital murder and
sentenced him to death. He has come within six days of execution.
</TEXT>
