<FIRST>r a AM-Dancer'sMom     12-15 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dancer's Mom,0311</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeal Rejected of Woman Convicted in Daughter's Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court has upheld the
convictions of a woman who forced her daughter to work as a
strip-tease dancer and was prosecuted for child abuse after the
girl committed suicide.
   Theresa Jackson's appeal seeking to overturn her 1987
convictions on charges of child abuse, forgery and procuring a
sexual performance by a child was rejected Wednesday by the Fourth
District Court of Appeals.
   Jackson, 42, of Coral Springs, altered her daughter's
identification before forcing her to get the job dancing nude at an
adult club, court testimony showed.
   Her daughter, 17-year-old Tina Mancini, shot herself to death in
March 1986. Testimony at the subsequent trial showed Jackson
ordered her underage daughter to perform at nude bars, then
collected most of the girl's earnings.
   No date of surrender has been set yet for Jackson, who has been
free on $4,500 bail, working as a cab driver. She was sentenced in
1987 to 364 days in prison, followed by two years of house arrest
and two more years of probation.
   ``They shoot horses, don't they?'' Jackson said after learning
of the appeals court opinion. ``Why don't they do that with me and
get it over with? I wish they would have done it a long time ago.''
   The trial was believed to be the first use of a psychological
autopsy in a criminal case involving suicide. In rejecting the
appeal, the justices approved the use of the evidence in Jackson's
trial.
   ``We are satisfied,'' the justices wrote in their opinion,
``that ... the psychological autopsy is accepted in the field of
psychiatry as a method of evaluation for use in cases involving
suicide, and that the trial judge acted within his discretion in
admitting this evidence at trial.''
</TEXT>
