<FIRST>r a AM-Sagansky     12-15 0495</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sagansky,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Finally Signs New Programs Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS, facing a third season as No. 3 in prime
time ratings, reached agreement Friday with movie executive Jeff
Sagansky to be its new programs chief, sources close to the
negotiations said.
   The move comes two weeks after the resignation of his
predecessor, Kim LeMasters, who resigned as CBS Entertainment
president after only two years in the job.
   Although CBS officials declined to comment and a spokesman for
Sagansky said ``there is no announcement yet,'' one executive who
asked not to be named said Sagansky's hiring would be announced
Monday by CBS and Columbia Studios.
   The delay, the executive explained, was to allow for ``an
orderly transition'' at both companies. Columbia, based in Burbank,
Calif., owns Tri-Star Pictures, of which Sagansky has been
president since March this year.
   CBS' agreement with Sagansky had been expected. But it was
delayed by extended negotiations between CBS and Columbia Studios
for the release of Sagansky from his Tri-Star contract, CBS
officials have said.
   Ironically, CBS previously considered him for the job before
deciding on LeMasters in 1987. Sagansky was wooed again before and
after CBS' unsuccessfully bid last week to lure to its vacant job a
top TV production team, Marcy Carsey and Tom Werner. Their company
makes NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and ABC's ``Roseanne,'' the nation's
two highest-rated series.
   Sagansky, who will be responsible for CBS' entire program
schedule, faces a large task of restoration in coming months at the
once-dominant network that last month suffered its worst-ever
November ratings.
   Although its daytime schedule emerged first in the November
ratings ``sweeps,'' CBS' prime time programs, late-night ``The Pat
Sajak Show'' and ``CBS This Morning'' all were third in network
ratings.
   However, the morning program, usually third in ratings even when
CBS enjoyed prime time success, showed slight improvement when its
ratings were compared with those of November last year.
   In prime time, though, CBS slipped two-tenths of a ratings point
in November. It averaged a 12.0 rating, a full ratings point behind
ABC and 3.1 points behind first-place NBC.
   A ratings point represents 921,000 homes, and in prime time can
be worth between $120 million and $140 million annuallly to a
network.
   The results of the quarterly sweeps periods are most important
to affiliates, which use them to set their own advertising rates
for the next three months.
   Although some CBS programs like ``Murphy Brown'' and the
recently returned ``Beauty and the Beast'' have gotten critical
praise, CBS hasn't had a hit series since the debut of ``Murder,
She Wrote'' in 1984.
   In news, Dan Rather's ``CBS Evening News'' broadcast, once
usually first in ratings, also is showing signs of slipping.
   ABC's ``World News Tonight'' has won in ratings for the last two
weeks. In the last ten weeks, that broadcast, anchored by Peter
Jennings, has won eight times and tied twice with Rather's program
in the Nielsens.
</TEXT>
