<FIRST>r a AM-FarmPrize     12-15 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Prize,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kraft Cuts Funding for Award Recognizing Third-World Food Research</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft General Foods has withdrawn
financial support for its coveted $200,000 World Food Prize, given
yearly to a scientist for agricultural research in Third World
countries, company officials said Friday.
   ``Funding for the prize was always decided on a year-to-year
basis,'' said Kraft spokesman Michael Mudd in a telephone
interview. ``We believe the award should succeed in establishing
broad-based support from other corporations.''
   The 3-year-old prize has been awarded to scientists for
achievements in developing new crops and livestock systems to help
feed underdeveloped regions of the world.
   The announcement of the funding cut-off came nine months after
General Foods and Kraft merged to form Glenview-based Kraft General
Foods. Both are subsidiaries of New York-based Philip Morris
Companies, the giant food and tobacco concern.
   ``It's a shame,'' said David L. Call, dean of the College of
Agriculture and Life Sciences at Cornell University in Ithaca, N.Y.
   ``Hunger has become sort of old hat to people, but there still
are an awful lot of people out there who go without,'' said Call,
who is on a seven-member council of advisers for the prize.
   Dr. Robert Chandler, who won the award in 1988 for his work as
director of the International Rice Institute in the Philippines,
said losing the annual prize could mean fewer important discoveries.
   ``It's a stimulation and something to be hoped and aimed for,''
Chandler, 82, said in a telephone interview from his Clermont,
Fla., home.
   This year's prize was awarded to Dr. Verghesi Kurien of India
for pioneering work in establishing a dairy cooperative system. Dr.
M. Swamanathan, also of India, won in 1987 for his work in
improving production of rice and wheat in that country.
</TEXT>
