<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Zionism     12-15 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Zionism,0203</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Reject U.S. Call To Help Repeal U.N. Declaration on Zionism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet envoy on Friday rejected a U.S.
appeal for a joint effort to repeal a 1975 U.N. resolution that
equates Zionism with racism.
   ``We consider that there is no need for this kind of action,''
Deputy Foreign Minister Vladimir Petrovsky told a news conference.
   Responding to a question, he said his government would not join
the United States on behalf of Israel to repeal the measure
``because if this question will be raised, there no doubt will be
confrontation in the United Nations and that will go far beyond the
discussion of Middle East questions and have a negative effect on
the whole state of affairs in the United Nations.''
   Vice President Dan Quayle told U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar Monday that the United States is seeking repeal of
the Arab and Soviet-backed resolution.
   The United States and Soviet Union have frequently worked
together this year to achieve consensus instead of calling for
divisive votes.
   Washington recently lauded the Soviet Union for urging Arab
nations to back away from demanding national observer status for
the Palestine Liberation Organization.
