<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2331EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-StatenIsland     12-15 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Staten Island,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Signs Bill Allowing Staten Island Secession Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staten Island residents won the chance to
secede from New York City under a bill signed Friday by Gov. Mario
Cuomo.
   ``There are no dispositive, substantive arguments offered
against the bill,'' Cuomo said.
   The bill gives Staten Island residents the chance to vote next
year on whether to establish a commission to draw up a new
government. After at least three years, the actual question of
secession and the form of a new government would go to the voters
again.
   Secession has long been sought by some residents of New York
City's smallest borough, who complain they have little voice in
city affairs compared to residents of more populous Manhattan, the
Bronx, Brooklyn and Queens.
   Staten Island, nearly 14 miles long and 7 miles wide, is 2{
times the size of Manhattan. Yet the 400,000 mostly middle-class
residents of the island are only a fraction of the city's 7 million
residents.
   ``I want to congratulate the governor on his prudent decision,''
said state Sen. John Marchi, a Staten Island Republican and chief
sponsor of the bill. ``It comes as an early Christmas present for
me and, I believe, for the people of Staten Island.''
   The secession movement gained steam last spring with a U.S.
Supreme Court ruling that New York City's form of government was
unconstitutional.
   Staten Islanders feared that a new government drawn up by a
charter revision commission would give them even less power.
   The secession bill was passed by the Legislature on the final
night of its 1989 session, yet was held back from the governor's
desk for several months by Marchi.
   The measure was opposed by New York City officials worried about
the loss of tax revenue from Staten Island residents. Mayor Edward
I. Koch argued that voters in the entire city, not just Staten
Island, should vote on secession.
   Cuomo said that there's ``more than enough time'' to deal with
the opponents' objections.
   He did, however, attach one condition to his signature. Cuomo
said he wants new legislation requiring that any new charter that
is adopted by Staten Island voters also be subsequently approved by
the state Legislature. Marchi has agreed to sponsor such
legislation next year, said his spokesman Charles Dumas.
   New York City Mayor-elect David Dinkins said Staten Island has
been an integral part of the city since it joined in 1898.
   ``The law allows the residents of the borough to reconsider this
historic relationship,'' Dinkins said. ``It is my hope that after
they complete their evaluation, they will choose to remain part of
America's greatest city.''
   U.S. Rep. Guy Molinari, who becomes Staten Island borough
president on January 1, said the chances of Staten Island
eventually seceding are ``very, very slim'' because if secession
benefits the island financially, legislators from other parts of
the state won't approve it.
   If it doesn't benefit Staten Islanders, voters there would turn
it down, he said. ``So it may be nothing more than a cruel hoax,''
Molinari said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
