<DOCNO> AP891215-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a i AM-Britain-PigeonRacing Adv22   12-15 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Pigeon Racing, Adv 22,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pigeon Racing Is Popular Sport in Britain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHELTENHAM, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From the blue-collar housing projects
of cockney east London to the gardens of the gentry, grown men scan
the skies for hours most weekends, waiting for their pigeons to
race home.
   They rhapsodize about pigeon racing, the sport known as ``the
fancy'' and now one of Britain's more popular pastimes.
   ``All you see is a pinprick in the sky,'' said Maj. Edward
Camilleri. ``They fly toward you and you hope its yours. Then they
fold their wings, they drop out of the sky, they literally do. They
come straight down like bullets.''
   Says Bernie Bennett, who has 60 pigeons: ``Unless you're a
pigeon fancier, you just find it very hard to understand, to see a
person out in the garden, like me yesterday, bucketing down with
rain, looking for pigeons to come from 100 miles.
   ``With pigeons I find one thing and one thing only: You're the
jury, you're the prosecution, you are the judge. All that happens
down in your backyard is down to you.''
   Camelleri, a retired soldier who runs the Royal Pigeon Racing
Association, estimates Britain has more than 200,000 pigeon
breeders and racers among its 56 million people.
   Nearly 2 million pigeons, many with meticulously documented
pedigrees dating back several avian generations, are registered
with Camilleri's association alone.
   The sport has an honorable history: The ancient Egyptians kept
pigeons; Hannibal took them over the Alps; they served in both
world wars, carrying messages for the Allied intelligence forces in
Europe. Thirty-one pigeons were awarded the Dickens Medal, the
``Animal Victoria Cross,'' in World War II.
   In Britain, pigeons were traditionally associated with
beer-drinking, cloth-capped men, but it has moved upmarket in
recent years, attracting lawyers, actors and titans of industry. At
the top end of the scale, Queen Elizabeth II maintains a pigeon
loft.
   Britain's largest pigeon breeder, Louella Pigeon World, is a
high-tech enterprise that paid a world record 77,000 pounds
($120,120) in 1988 for the racing pigeon Emerald II.
   ``That, pound for pound, makes it more valuable than the Derby
winner,'' Camilleri said, referring to Britain's most prestigious
horse race.
   Emerald II is moved from one secret location to another, because
with the large sums sometimes at stake in bets and prize money,
sabotage and pigeon-napping are not unheard of.
   However, high prices don't always guarantee success, Camilleri
said, and a good racing pigeon can start as low as 20 pounds ($32).
   ``Stockmanship comes into it, knowing and understanding
pigeons,'' he explained. ``They all have their individual
characters and what you've got to do is understand their character
well enough and encourage them to come home quicker than the next
pigeon.''
   No one knows exactly how pigeons they find their way home after
being released, sometimes hundreds of miles away.
   ``The sun is definitely one (factor) and magnetic field is
definitely a second,'' Camilleri said. Research in Europe indicates
the sense of smell also may help.
   There's also a very basic urge.
   Most pigeons in Britain are kept on the ``widowhood system.'' As
soon as a hen and cock produce a pair of young, or squeakers,
they're separated. Only the males are raced, and the only time they
get to see their hens is when they return to the loft at the end of
a race.
   Each fancier's loft is registered and the distance between it
and any of the 200 official British ``liberation sites'' measured
to the nearest yard.
   Pigeons are bundled into baskets, sometimes the night before a
race, and taken to the liberation site in air-conditioned trucks.
Each wears a rubber band about the size of a wedding ring on its
leg with the details of where it came from.
   The pigeons are all released at the same time. They ascend
rapidly, quickly become oriented and head for home.
   When they land, the fancier removes the rubber band and puts it
in a timeclock that is sealed and taken to the local racing club.
The flight distance is divided by the time it took to determine who
won the race.
   What is it about pigeons that engenders such passion and loyalty?
   ``The fascination about it: you get a few pigeons, you start
winning races, and from then on it's a lot like horse racing, only
cheaper,'' Camilleri said.
   ``You can pit your wits against nature.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, Dec. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1314EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:TwoDirectors Adv22   12-15 1126</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Two Directors, Adv 22,1156</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 22</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs, Dec. 22, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Memories of the Holocaust</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``The Music Box'' opens in New York and Los Angeles on Dec.
22; ``Enemies, A Love Story'' opened in New York on Dec. 13 and will be
released elsewhere early next year.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years ago, a friend talked to Constantin
Costa-Gavras about a project concerning Nazis permitted to emigrate
to the United States after World War II.
   The director, who makes films about issues _ Greek political
assassination in ``Z,'' Chilean government brutality and American
compliance in ``Missing,'' white extremists in ``Betrayed'' _ was
immediately interested. He read books on the subject and developed
the idea for his new film, ``Music Box,'' in which a lawyer
(Jessica Lange) defends her Hungarian father against accusations of
atrocities committed during the war.
   ``Essentially, I like to do something which has never been made
or said before,'' the Greek director explained in a recent
interview. ``It's the best way for me to do a movie, to deal with a
very original subject.
   ``We in Europe used to think most of the war criminals went to
Latin America. When I was in Chile they showed me places, `Here,'
`Here,' `There,' where Nazis lived. Paraguay also. In America, it
was quite secret for the general population.''
   Memories of the Holocaust also haunt ``Enemies: A Love Story,''
Paul Mazursky's new film. The director started with Isaac Beshavis
Singer's novel and filled in his own memories of growing up in the
Brownsville section of Brooklyn during the 1940s.
   Ron Silver stars as Herman Broder, a Polish Jew who hid from the
Nazis during the war and now lives in Brooklyn.
   He is torn among his current wife, Yadwiga (Margaret Sophie
Stein), a Polish peasant who took care of him while he hid from the
Nazis; Masha (Lena Olin), a fellow survivor with whom he's having a
passionate affair; and his first wife, Tamara (Angelica Huston),
who has returned after supposedly being murdered by the Nazis.
   Mazursky, like Singer _ and Costa-Gavras _ was never in the
Holocaust. But ``Enemies'' is simply a story, based on second-hand
knowledge and a first-rate imagination, the director insisted.
   ``Isaac spoke to many survivors, I'm sure, who must have flooded
the streets of New York,'' said Mazursky, who also has directed
``Harry and Tonto,'' ``An Unmarried Woman'' and ``Down and Out in
Beverly Hills.''
   ``He probably got the story from talking to more than one
survivor, so that people like Masha and her mother and Herman and
the person who hid him in the barn _ those are stories he probably
heard and made this tale up.
   ``I met many survivors, had dinner, conversations, whatever. All
that I had gotten I gave to the actors while we rehearsed. I had
them meet with some of these people, in Los Angeles and in New
York.''
   For ``Music Box,'' Costa-Gavras began with non-fiction and built
a story around it.
   In both films, the Holocaust is always present but never on
screen, unlike the recently released ``Triumph of the Spirit.'' For
Mazursky and Costa-Gavras, the subject seemed too large for even
the most learned observer.
   Singer himself wrote: ``From his (Herman's) own experience with
Masha and other survivors of the German camps, he knew that the
whole truth would never be learned from those who had survived the
concentration camps or the wandering through Russia _ not because
they lied but because it was impossible for them to tell it all.''
   So Mazursky deferred to documentaries such as ``Shoah'' and
``Hotel Terminus'' as more appropriate ways to learn directly about
that tragedy. Once research was completed, he concentrated on the
actual film.
   Costa-Gavras agreed, saying he deliberately confined ``Music
Box'' to the present.
   ``You run the risk of being eaten by the story. In `Music Box,'
there's no particular action, no landscape. It's a very empty
movie. It takes place in the present, but with people speaking
about the past. How you deal with the past, that's the challenge.''
   With such explosive material, it is important to have actors
with whom the audience will be comfortable. But balance is
necessary; the story always comes first. As Costa-Gavras noted,
``Music Box'' is not a ``Jessica Lange'' film, any more than
``Missing'' is a ``Sissy Spacek'' film or ``Betrayed'' a ``Debra
Winger'' film.
   ``It's not only being known, it's being a good actor,'' he said.
``You're a good actor and you get known. That's the case with Sissy
or Debra or Jack Lemmon and now Jessica Lange. You can spoil the
story with a big actor.
   ``We're far away from the actors of the '40s and the '50s. Gary
Cooper, Errol Flynn. This is over, those kind of mythical stars.
Now we go to see an actor playing a character, a real character.
Jessica made her character real.''
   Mazursky praised Silver, acclaimed for his performance on stage
in ``Speed-the-Plow,'' and said the actor was ideal for playing ``a
Herman.''
   ``A Herman is somebody who comes from Europe, whose father was a
rabbi, who's a scholar, an intellectual, who loves women, who's
very bright, ironic, and who's sad,'' the director explained.
   ``Ron can play that. Certain other actors, a lot of them don't
have all those qualities. They'd have to find them. I'm better off
finding someone who already has them.''
   ``Music Box'' ends with Lange, shattered by what she has learned
about her father, embracing her son in back of their lakefront
house. With her own innocence gone forever, she can only pass on
her knowledge and help her son adjust.
   ``The theme is about memory,'' Costa-Gavras said. ``Of course,
the memory goes with the future. She does what she does to save her
son, to have her son thinking differently and acting differently.
To learn how to live with this.''
   Mazursky adds his own touch at the end of the film, dissolving
from a closeup of Yadwiga's baby to a shot of the Coney Island
``Wonder Wheel,'' which can be viewed from Herman's window. The
message is bittersweet: Wounds eventually heal, a new generation is
born. But also, the lessons of the Holocaust may be forgotten.
   ``Out of the baby comes this image of the wheel,'' Mazursky
said, ``and all through the movie Herman has focused on the wheel
in his most contemplative and meditative moments, when he's
thinking about God knows what.
   ``The wheel keeps turning, life goes on. The baby is life and
life is mysterious. There's man and there's woman, it never ends.
Even the Holocaust is absorbed into that circle and the life will
go on.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Friday AMs, Dec. 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
