<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By saying they may have to take refuge in
bankruptcy court, the retailers owned by deeply indebted Campeau
Corp. intensified concerns among suppliers and increased the
chances that shipments could be halted.
   One of the major factoring companies, which act as middlemen
between manufacturers and retailers, said Thursday it no longer
would extend credit on merchandise bound for Campeau's department
stores.
   Several apparel and accessory manufacturers said they were
keeping in close touch with executives in charge of Campeau's U.S.
retailing operations. Bills have been paid on time so far, they
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Express Co. announced a plan to raise
about $900 million in new capital for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
and reduce its stake in the struggling brokerage to under 50
percent.
   After Thursday's announcement, Moody's Investors Service
confirmed Shearson's senior debt ratings, removing a major threat
to the reputation and financial stability of the nation's
second-largest Wall Street firm.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pinnacle West Capital Corp. ended weeks of
speculation by announcing it had turned down an ``opportunistic
attempt'' by an Oregon-based holding company to buy Arizona's
largest corporation.
   PacifiCorp on Dec. 1 proposed swapping stock to acquire Pinnacle
West in a deal valued at about $1.87 billion.
   But Pinnacle West's board ``unanimously determined'' Thursday
that the proposal was inadequate.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Low natural gas prices have forced Mesa Limited
Partnership to scrap cash distributions and sell assets to reduce
debt, the energy company run by takeover strategist T. Boone
Pickens announced.
   Besides cutting out its 37.5-cent per unit quarterly
distribution, Mesa said Thursday it will package its holdings in
the Hugoton natural gas field into a separate royalty trust and
sell shares to raise $300 million to pay down its $1.5 billion in
long-term debt.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and French securities regulators signed a
mutual assistance agreement to help stamp out insider trading and
other market abuses, the Securities and Exchange Commission said.
   Under the agreement, the SEC and its French equivalent _ the
Commission des Operations de Bourse (COB) _ will assist each other
by providing information in their respective files, interviewing
individuals and obtaining documents.
   The agreement was signed Thursday in Paris by SEC Chairman
Richard C. Breeden and COB President Jean Saint-Geours.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 10,000 floppy disks on AIDS programmed
with a virus that destroyed information in some computers have
turned up in Europe, Africa and California, officials and news
reports said.
   Scotland Yard, which is investigating, said Thursday it was
treating the case as criminal damage and blackmail.
   The magazine PC Business World said it believed the saboteur,
whose identity and whereabouts were not known, used its mailing
list to target victims.
