<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0099</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Fall on T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on 52-week Treasury bills fell
in Thursday's action to the lowest level since June 1988.
   The Treasury Department sold $9.75 billion of the bills at an
average discount rate of 7.14 percent, down from 7.17 percent at
the last auction Nov. 16.
   The rates were the lowest since June 30, 1988, when the one-year
bills sold for 7.04 percent.
   The new discount rate understates the actual return to investors
_ 7.66 percent with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,278.10.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MortgageDelinquency     12-15 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mortgage Delinquency,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mortgage Delinquency Rate Highest in Two Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The delinquency rate for home mortgages jumped
sharply to the highest level in more than two years in the
July-September quarter, a trade association said.
   The Mortgage Bankers Association of America said Thursday that
5.00 percent of mortgage payments for one-to-four family residences
were 30 or more days late, up from a second-quarter rate of 4.52
percent, a 10-year low.
   It was the highest delinquency rate since the second quarter of
1987, when 5.02 percent of mortgages were past due.
   A jump in late mortgage payments often reflects economic
difficulties among consumers, but Warren Lasko, Mortgage Bankers
executive vice president, said the association found no ready
explanation for the increase.
   Although economic growth has slowed, the unemployment rate has
remained relatively stable, close to 15-year lows, and Americans'
disposable personal income grew during the period, he said.
   Historically, the rate sometimes jumps in one quarter only to
decline in the next, he cautioned.
   Lasko noted that the foreclosure rate in the third quarter
declined from 1.06 percent to 0.99 percent. Also, the percentages
of loans more than 60 days and more than 90 days past due increased
only slightly.
   By region, the 30-day delinquency rate in the Northeast was 4.34
percent in the third quarter, up from 3.74 percent; in the North
Central states, 5.13 percent, up from 4.36 percent; in the South,
5.53 percent, up from 4.87 percent, and in the West, 4.08 percent,
up from 3.64 percent.
   The mortgage survey covers 13 million loans representing $597
billion in debt, about one-third of all mortgage loans in the
United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
