<FIRST>r f PM-Shearson Bjt   12-15 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shearson, Bjt,0662</SECOND>
<HEAD>Struggling Brokerage Sets $900 Million Recapitalization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $900 million recapitalization plan preserves
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.'s credit rating at a time of weak
profits and layoffs at Wall Street's second-largest brokerage.
   The deal, announced Thursday, also reduces parent American
Express Co.'s stake to under 50 percent and excludes investor and
Revlon Chairman Ronald O. Perelman, who was in talks for a minority
share in exchange for a large investment.
   Moody's Investors Service Inc. confirmed Shearson's senior debt
ratings after the plan was disclosed, removing a major threat to
Shearson's reputation and financial stability. Securities firms
need good credit to borrow money for large transactions.
   Moody's said the recapitalization plan ``will materially
increase Shearson's tangible net worth.''
   ``Continuing efforts to reduce expenses should help boost
Shearson's performance,'' Moody's said in a statement. ``However,
intensifying competition in the global securities business and a
difficult operating environment will remain constraints.''
   The recapitalization includes the issue of 20 million new shares
of Shearson common stock, which would raise $295 million if sold at
Thursday's New York Stock Exchange closing price of $14.75 a share.
   American Express, which bought its Shearson stake in 1981, would
buy 3 million shares of the new issue, pumping about $44 million
into Shearson. The travel, credit card and financial services
company also plans to purchase Shearson cumulative preferred stock
with a liquidation value of $250 million.
   In addition, $300 million in capital would be raised through two
equal stock placements with large institutional investors. Finally,
American Express would buy Ayco Corp., a Shearson financial
counseling subsidiary, for $56 million, bringing the total new
capital to $901 million.
   The institutional investors were not named, but Wall Street
sources said discussions were held to give a minority stake in
Shearson to Perelman.
   ``There were talks. They were preliminary. It really didn't come
to terms,'' one source said.
   The sources, who asked not to be named, said American Express
had not finalized the outside investors, but they said there would
be a number of them.
   The recapitalization is expected to shore up Shearson's balance
sheet but is not expected to guarantee a turnaround during a time
of slumping profits and slow business on Wall Street.
   The plan would achieve American Express' long-desired goal of
reducing its stake in Shearson to under 50 percent from 61 percent
to remove the brokerage's up-and-down performance from its earnings
report.
   Moody's on Oct. 30 said it was considering downgrading
Shearson's ratings on $4.8 billion in bonds and commercial paper
because of the firm's low capital, weak profits and exposure in
commercial real estate loans and investments, as well as the
overall securities industry slump.
   Shearson stock has fallen in recent months because of poor
earnings. The firm recently began laying off 800 workers to reduce
its size to 35,700 employees, reshuffling its senior management and
slashing stockbroker commissions for the first time in 15 years.
   The boards of directors of American Express and Shearson
approved the recapitalization plan late Thursday.
   Under the plan, American Express will remain the largest
shareholder in Shearson. Nippon Life Insurance Co. of Japan,
currently the second-largest shareholder with 13 percent, would
remain in that position, although its new stake would be smaller.
   American Express said it expects to record a one-time charge to
net income reflecting the difference between the value of Shearson
on its books and the value of its holdings based on the share
price. The charge would total $60 million at Thursday's share
price, American Express said.
   Officials said Shearson was willing to part with Albany-based
Ayco, which provides financial planning services to corporate
executives, because it fits more with American Express' operations.
   American Express said it planned to file registration statements
with the Securities and Exchange Commission early next week on the
recapitalization.
</TEXT>
