<FIRST>r f PM-Campeau Bjt   12-15 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Campeau, Bjt,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipment Disruptions Loom After Campeau Says Bankruptcy Filing Possible</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Campeau Glance, BC-Campeau-States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Chetta B'' is cq with no period.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business News</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suppliers to department stores owned by
financially distressed Campeau Corp. are taking a cautious approach
regarding future merchandise shipments.
   One of the companies that act as middlemen between manufacturers
and retailers, known as factors, said Thursday it no longer would
extend credit on goods bound for Campeau's stores.
   Meanwhile, several apparel and accessory manufacturers said they
were keeping in close touch with executives in charge of Campeau's
U.S. retailing operations. Bills have been paid on time so far,
they said.
   The suppliers, whose fates are tied to retailers, expressed hope
that business wouldn't be disrupted as Campeau copes with a
worsening cash shortage.
   ``I'm very worried about the situation,'' said Howard Bloom,
president and chief executive of Chetta B Inc., a clothing maker.
``It gets progressively worse looking every day. I'm taking a
wait-and-see posture.''
   Retail analysts said disclosures by Campeau's Federated
Department Stores Inc. and Allied Stores Corp. of deepening
financial difficulties were unsurprising given the fierce
competition in the industry.
   Federated and Allied said in documents submitted to the
Securities and Exchange Commission that their cash could run out by
March or sooner and that they might seek protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code.
   The move would permit Campeau-owned retailers to remain
operating while their Canadian parent company sorted out its
financial problems. At the heart of the trouble is the massive debt
Campeau acquired in taking over Federated in 1988 for $6.7 billion
and Allied in 1986 for $3.4 billion.
   A threatened inability to meet interest payments on junk bonds
sold to pay for the acquisitions forced the Toronto-based retail
and real estate company to turn to outsiders for help earlier this
year.
   Canada's Olympia &amp; York Developments Ltd. came to the rescue
with a $250 million loan to Campeau. As part of a deal for an
additional $800 million next year from Olympia &amp; York, Campeau put
the Bloomingdale's department store chain up for sale in September.
About a half dozen bidders are evaluating the chain and Campeau has
said a final sale could be arranged by February.
   In the SEC filings, made public Wednesday, Federated and Allied
said bankruptcy court protection would be an alternative if lenders
won't ease repayment terms. Federated owes creditors $1.15 billion
by the end of April and Allied faces debts of $633.7 million due by
the end of March.
   Failing a rescheduling of the payments, Campeau said it would
consider selling additional holdings, raising money by taking out
mortgages on its stores or possibly seeking bankruptcy-court
protection.
   In addition to the 17-store Bloomingdale's chain, Federated
operates Abraham &amp; Straus, Burdines, Lazarus, Rich's and
Goldsmith's. Under the Allied umbrella are The Bon Marche, Jordan
Marsh, Maas Brothers and Stern's. Combined, the two have about
100,000 employees and 260 stores.
   Vendors, such as clothing makers Bernard Chaus Inc., Ellen Tracy
Inc., Liz Claiborne Inc., that do business with many of the stores
said they would continue to monitor developments at Campeau and
that up to now they've been satisfied with how promptly the company
has paid for goods.
   Another yardstick of Campeau's relationship with vendors could
come when some manufacturers seek credit in coming weeks to ship
spring merchandise to the stores.
   Bernard Chaus, chairman and chief executive officer of the
ready-to-wear clothing company that bears his name, said: ``We
certainly are going to support them on all fronts.'' Chaus added,
however, that he assumes Federated and Allied stores would ``have
some major problems with merchandise shipments.''
   Chaus doesn't use factoring, which involves companies buying
accounts receivable and taking over the job of collecting the money
due.
   The second-largest factor in the country, Chicago-based Heller
Financial Inc., shut off credit lines to Campeau suppliers as of
Thursday morning, spokeswoman Laura Jiracek said.
   CIT Group-Factoring Manufacturers Hanover Inc., the biggest in
the business, said it was continuing to assess the situation.
Francis X. Basile, chairman of the CIT unit, said he was concerned
there might be an undue reaction in the retail community.
   He said the only new development was Campeau's public
acknowledgement that bankruptcy-court protection might be
necessary. Basile said in an interview that outsiders have thought
all along that was a possibility.
   But, he noted, ``There's a lot of things that we're going to
have to resolve before we can approve any future orders.''
</TEXT>
