<FIRST>r f AM-NewMexican-Gannett 1stLd-Writethru f0310J3-$ieda</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Mexican-Gannett, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0310,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>McKinney Purchases New Mexican From Gannett</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 5th, `Neither McKinney ..., to UPDATE
with McKinney Q-and-A. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert McKinney, the former owner of The
Santa Fe New Mexican, regained control of it Thursday from Gannett
Co. Inc., less than one month after going to court to block
Gannett's attempt to sell the newspaper.
   Thursday's purchase by McKinney and his daughter, Robin McKinney
Martin, ended a nearly 14-year association McKinney had with
Arlington, Va.-based Gannett, including a bitter nine-year legal
battle over day-to-day control of the newspaper. McKinney sold the
daily newspaper to Gannett in 1976.
   Douglas H. McCorkindale, vice chairman and chief financial and
administrative officer for Gannett, told a meeting of security
analysts in New York City on Thursday the transaction value was in
the mid-$30 million range.
   Sheila Gibbons, Gannett's public affairs director, said the
newspaper group decided to sell The New Mexican because ``we felt
this was a good idea. I can't comment beyond that.''
   Neither McKinney of Santa Fe and Middleburg, Va., nor Martin of
Santa Fe, owner of the weekly Taos News in northern New Mexico,
returned telephone calls to The Associated Press seeking comment on
the purchase.
   McKinney, in a question-and-answer piece scheduled to appear in
Friday's editions, said, his relationship with Gannett ``has been
long and stormy.
   ``In the course of the current negotiations, Gannett's conduct
has been proper in my opinion and I think that Gannett would say
that my conduct has been equally proper,'' McKinney wrote. ``I
think, however, that both of us will now be happier going our own
separate ways.''
   Among the reasons for buying back the publication, he added, was
``I did not want to see the New Mexican owned by or sold again to
another chain operation.''
   Gannett agreed in September to sell The New Mexican to Donrey
Media Group of Fort Smith, Ark., in a deal valued at $35 million,
according to court records filed in a lawsuit brought by McKinney
to block the sale.
   Gannett said in court documents it terminated the agreement with
Donrey after McKinney filed a complaint alleging that Gannett had
violated an employment agreement with him.
   The employment agreement, under which McKinney remained the
newspaper's publisher for five years and editor-in-chief for 10
years, was part of the transaction in which McKinney sold The New
Mexican to Gannett in February 1976.
   McKinney alleged Gannett failed to honor a stipulation that if
Gannett wanted to sell the paper it would have to give McKinney the
opportunity to purchase it first by matching terms of the
prospective buyer's offer.
   Gannett, in a counterclaim, denied McKinney's accusations and
alleged ``bad faith'' by McKinney to manipulate his right to refuse
an agreement to sell the paper.
   State District Judge Steve Herrera said he signed a
one-paragraph order Thursday dismissing McKinney's complaint as
well as a counterclaim filed by Gannett at the request of both
parties because the issues in the case had been settled.
   The purchase of The New Mexican, which said it has a daily
circulation of 20,088 and a Sunday circulation of 21,189, involved
the transfer of 800,000 shares of Gannett stock by McKinney and
Martin to Gannett.
   Gannett said in a news release the shares were being transferred
in a tax-free exchange for the stock of The New Mexican.
   McKinney, who first bought the newspaper in 1949, was quoted in
a New Mexican story announcing the sale as saying department heads,
managers and staff members would continue in their present
positions.
   Sale of the newspaper leaves Gannett with 82 daily newspapers,
including USA Today.
</TEXT>
