<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-MediaOutlook     12-15 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Media Outlook,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Affiliated Sees 1989 Profit Decline; Other Media Companies Expect
Increase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affiliated Publications Inc., publisher of The
Boston Globe, expects lower earnings from continuing operations
this year, but four other media companies indicated they will post
profit increases.
   Gannett Co. Inc., Dow Jones &amp; Co. Inc., Washington Post Co. and
McClatchy Newspapers Inc. each told securities analysts at
PaineWebber Inc.'s annual media outlook conference Thursday that
their earnings will be up this year.
   Boston-based Affiliated stated that it expected earnings per
share from continuing operations for 1989 will be 61 cents to 64
cents, down from 75 cents a share in 1988.
   Affiliated Chairman William O. Taylor said he expects the
company will do ``a little better next year'' as the decline in
advertising volume levels off, costs of newsprint remain low,
previous efforts to cut costs show results and the Globe introduces
more zoned editions.
   Douglas McCorkindale, Gannett's vice chairman and chief
financial officer, said analysts who were estimating earnings per
share in the ``mid-$2.40 range are on the right track.'' Gannett,
based in Arlington, Va., earned $2.26 a share in 1988.
   Those results include a loss of ``a couple of million dollars''
at Gannett's national newspaper, USA Today, in contrast with a loss
of about $25 million a year earlier, according to USA Today
President Thomas Curley.
   He said his aim was to make the newspaper profitable for all of
1990.
   The company, which owns more than 80 daily newspapers as well as
television ands radio stations and an outdoor advertising company,
declined to estimate 1990 earnings.
   Dow Jones, based in New York, said it expects to report 1989
earnings per share of $3.13 to $3.18, up from $2.35 a share in 1988.
   The publisher of The Wall Street Journal said that excluding
non-recurring gains, its earnings will be off by about 4 percent to
$1.49 to $1.54 a share for the year from $1.65 a share a year
earlier.
   Those results have been depressed by losses connected with the
foreign exchange trading service operated by its Telerate unit and
retrenchments in the financial community that have led to sharp
declines in financial advertising volume, said Chairman Warren H.
Phillips.
   Washington Post, which has properties that include its namesake
flagship newspaper, Newsweek magazine, television stations and
cable TV operations, said it expects its earnings per share will
rise 20 percent to $15.50 from $12.90 on a pro forma basis in 1988.
It said its operating income will be up 33 percent.
   Richard D. Simmons, president, said 1990 should be a good year
although the company could not hope to reach the same level of
earnings growth as in 1989.
   McClatchy, based in Sacramento, Calif., and publisher of the
Sacramento Bee, Anchorage Daily News, Tacoma News Tribune and
others, expects to reach analysts' earnings estimates of $1.15 a
share to $1.20 a share this year, up from $1.02 a share in 1988,
said James P. Smith, vice president and treasurer.
   Smith declined to forecast 1990 earnings prospects other than to
say they should produce ``good but not spectacular results.''
   But he noted 1990 results will be depressed by 20 cents a share
due to the recent acquisitions of three daily and two weekly
newspapers in South Carolina and that McClatchy expects to have a
loss of $4.5 million to $5 million next year on its investment in
the startup of a newspaper mill in Washington state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0247 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0158EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-SEC-France     12-15 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SEC-France,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>SEC, French Securities Watchdog Sign Cooperation Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. and French securities regulators will be
exchanging more than pleasantries now that they've signed a new
mutual assistance agreement to investigate fraud and other market
abuses.
   Under the agreement, the SEC and its French equivalent _ the
Commission des Operations de Bourse (COB) _ will assist each other
by providing information in their respective files, taking
statements from individuals and obtaining documents.
   Both agencies also agreed, in a separate document, to consult
each other ``about subjects of common interest in order to
coordinate market oversight and resolve differences that may
exist'' between the two countries' regualtory system.
   The agreement was signed Thursday in Paris by SEC Chairman
Richard C. Breeden and COB President Jean Saint-Geours.
   In prepared remarks for the signing, released by the SEC in
Washington, Breeden said the agreement provides ``a specific means
for the United States and French regulators to exchange information
for use in investigating securities laws violations.''
   The statement continued: ``Under the agreement, the SEC and COB
will use their own securities enforcement powers to the greatest
possible extent in providing mutual assistance. This will help us
to achieve greater stability and integrity in our markets.''
   U.S. investors' transactions in French corporate stock increased
from $1.2 billion in 1985 to $4 billion last year. During the same
period, French transactions in U.S. corporate stock doubled, from
$6 billion to $12 billion.
   Breeden noted that he reached a similar agreement Monday with
Dutch securitiees regulators.
   The statement added that the SEC has undertaken several moves
``designed to stimulate international capital formation and
cross-border activities of securities professionals.''
   They include a July regulation easing registration requirements
for foreign broker-dealers to conduct some activities in this
country; and a new proposal, Rule 144-A, that would facilitate the
sale of foreign securities in the private placement market without
normal U.S. registration procedures.
   ``Even as we eliminate barriers to international securities
transactions. we must be alert to the increased risks of
cross-border fraud,'' said Breeden, adding, ``the agreement signed
today strengthens our ability to prevent and detect these types of
unlawful activities conducted across national borders.''
   The agreement allows either U.S. or French securities officials
to take statements and testimony from individuals in their own
country and supply them to the other country's officials.
   Information supplied to the foreign authorities is to be
subject, in most cases, to the confidentiality rules of the
supplying country.
   Unlike the Dutch agreement, the new pact does not confine
applicability to French territory in Europe.
   The agreement, however, limits the exchange of information to
events that occurred after the pact goes into effect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 0204EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Xerox-Apple Bjt   12-15 0706</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Xerox-Apple, Bjt,0727</SECOND>
<HEAD>Xerox Suit Claims Apple Stole Pioneering Machintosh Software Design</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY McGRATH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $150 million federal lawsuit alleges
Apple Computer employees saw pioneering Xerox Corp. graphics
programs at a trade show in 1981 and pirated the design to create
the revolutionary Macintosh computer.
   The suit, filed Thursday in U.S. District Court, also alleges
then-Apple President Steven Jobs saw a demonstration of another
Xerox program, Smalltalk, at Xerox's Palo Alto Research Center in
1979, and that he and other Apple employees were ``very impressed
with the unique and revolutionary user-friendly design.''
   Jobs was ousted from Apple in 1985 and founded Next Inc., which
makes workstation computers.
   ``Xerox never licensed Apple to use the Star computer program or
its distinctive graphics or its unique design and appearance or its
unique concept and feel,'' the suit said. It also claims Apple
gained unauthorized access by hiring several Xerox employees in the
late 1970s and early 1980s, including Star software developers.
   The suit, the first of its kind ever filed by Xerox, claims
Apple's now-defunct Lisa computer system and Macintosh Finder, both
copyrighted in 1987, were derived from the two Xerox programs.
Smalltalk was developed in the mid-1970s, and Star was copyrighted
in 1981.
   The lawsuit says Apple employees saw the Star program at the
trade show, in Houston in June 1981, and copied substantial
portions in its Lisa and Macintosh Finder programs, including the
design and appearance of the main application windows, dialogue
boxes and menu, and some of the exact icons, or symbols, used in
the program.
   Apple was granted a license in June 1981 to participate with
Xerox in a project to implement Smalltalk into a hardware system to
be developed by Apple, the suit said.
   Thomas C. Abbott, a spokesman for Stamford, Conn.-based Xerox,
said the civil suit was filed after efforts beginning a week ago to
reach an agreement were rebuffed by Apple.
   ``We sought a settlement with Apple and we resorted to these
legal means only when it became absolutely necessary,'' said Abbott.
   Officials of Apple, based in Cupertino, said Xerox's software
graphics concepts are not protected by copyright any more than
depictions of birds and trees are protected by the copyright on a
painting.
   ``We believe the case is without merits,'' said Apple
spokeswoman Carleen LeVasseur. ``The complaint confuses the
difference between ideas and expression; the copyright protects
expresssion, not ideas.''
   She said Apple has always recognized Xerox and others as
responsible for ideas, including computer graphics devices called
mirrors and windows.
   ``Copyright covers artistic expression but not the ideas. In
art, it does not cover the trees and birds in a picture, only the
picture ... what Apple has done is take those ideas and spend a lot
of money in research and development and make our own original
expression.''
   The suit, which asks for a jury trial, said the Star program
``is widely recognized in the computer industry as being the first
to introduce fanciful desktop workstation graphics to allow the
user to interact with the computer,'' a development that took Xerox
``millions of dollars and years of creative effort.''
   The suit claims a total of $50 million in damages from unfair
competition under state and federal laws, plus punitive damages
under state law of an unspecified amount. It also seeks at least
$100 million from Apple for unjust enrichment from licenses and
royalties for its products.
   Macintosh graphics replaced complicated word codes with simple
symbols, vastly streamlining the way users ranging from
schoolchildren to office workers select programs, issue commands
and perform other functions.
   In a similar suit, Apple sued Microsoft and Hewlett-Packard Co.
in the same court in March 1988, claiming infringement of Lisa and
the Macintosh Finder copyrights, among others, and alleging both
were original to Apple.
   Apple claimed that Microsoft's Windows 2.03 and a
Hewlett-Packard program called NewWave, which is based on it, too
closely resemble the ``look'' of screen displays on the Macintosh.
   A federal judge in July issued a tentative ruling that greatly
narrowed Apple's suit by deciding the items covered in a 1985
licensing agreement between Apple and Microsoft could not be used
as evidence against Microsoft's and Hewlett-Packard's versions of
the products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
