<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was little changed in light European
trading early today as the foreign exchange market awaited the
latest U.S. trade figures. Gold prices were higher.
   Dealers said the market was positioning itself before the
release of U.S. trade figures for October. Analysts predicted the
deficit would widen to around $8.8 billion from $7.9 billion in
September.
   Dealers said that unless the figures were out of the ordinary,
the dollar should trade within a narrow range for the rest of the
session as markets wind down before the weekend.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.23 Japanese yen to a closing 144.30
yen. Later, in London, it fell back to 144.04 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.7349 West German marks, down from 1.7375;
1.5555 Swiss francs, down from 1.5630; 5.9330 French francs, down
from 5.9420; 1.9605 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9565; 1,293.50
Italian lire, down from 1,295.75; and 1.1605 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1585.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6016 from $1.5970 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $409.50 a troy ounce, up
from $407.50 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $410.35.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $410.50, up from $408.50 bid late
Thursday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose 65 cents to close at a bid $409.30.
   Silver rose in London to a bid price of $5.62 a troy ounce, up
from $5.58 bid late Thursday.
