<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-15 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nikkei Hits New High, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite worries about the almost uninterrupted rise
in the market's key index for the past few weeks, share prices on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange posted a new closing high today, while the
dollar remained higher in a narrow range.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 90.34
points, or 0.23 percent, to finish the week at a record closing of
38,271.04.
   The index's previous record closing was 38,180.70 points set
Thursday. It breached 38,000 points on Wednesday, when it gained
258.89 points.
   The market needed only 16 trading days to see the index gain
more than 2,000 points. It first rose above 36,000 on Nov. 21.
   ``Last-minute arbitrage buying by foreign securities firms
pushed up the index'' after the Nikkei index generally remained
weak throughout the day, Hiroshi Bando of Yamaichi Securities Co.
said.
   An arbitrage deal is a common technique to make profits out of
price differentials between the spot and futures markets.
   The Nikkei index has climbed almost without pause in the last
three weeks.
   Bando said there were some investors taking a cautious attitude
over a continued advance in the index, while others were still
expected for higher prices ahead.
   A total of 800 million shares, the same amount traded Thursday,
changed hands on the first section.
   In currency market, the dollar closed at 144.30 yen, up 0.23 yen
from Thursday's close of 144.07 yen. After opening at 144.30 yen,
the dollar ranged betwen 144.25-144.38 yen.
   Yoshitsugu Hanada, a dealer with the Mitsui Bank Ltd., said the
dollar-yen trading was slow the whole day, with many market players
awaiting a series of U.S. economic data, including the October
trade figures, producer prices and industrial production data for
November, all due out later today in Washington.
</TEXT>
