<FIRST>u f PM-UAL     12-15 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wall Street Finds No Cheer In UAL Moves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As UAL Corp. stock continues to tumble, industry
analysts are warning investors not to expect any buyout deal for
the airline company to develop soon.
   ``I suspect it probably will drag on for some time because it's
not an easy package to put together,'' analyst Robert Joedicke of
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. said Thursday, one day after UAL's
board announced it was still searching for a deal to boost the
company's stock price.
   Investors registered their disappointment on Wall Street. UAL,
the parent of United Airlines, fell $5.50 to $163.25 a share
Thursday on the New York Stock Exchange after dropping $8 on
Wednesday.
   Nonetheless, airline industry analysts said they were intrigued
by the board's statement that it would seek discussions with
Coniston Partners, an investment group that owns an 11.8 percent
stake in the company and is pushing for a sale or restructuring.
   Some said the move could indicate a greater willingess by the
board to listen to Coniston's ideas.
   But other observers said UAL directors may simply be trying to
discern how much clout Coniston really carries in its threat to
solicit shareholder consents to overthrow UAL's board.
   UAL spokesman Joe Hopkins would not comment on when a meeting
might be held.
   Paul Tierney, one of Coniston's general partners, said it was
impossible to interpret the board's intentions. But he said
Coniston was concerned about UAL's slow progress in putting
together a transaction to increase shareholder value.
   The New York-based partnership says it will launch its consent
solicitation ``if and when we conclude it would be advantageous.''
   Airline analysts say Coniston probably would have the support of
other stock speculators who suffered steep losses on their UAL
holdings when a $6.75 billion buyout bid by United's pilots and UAL
management collapsed in October.
   But Coniston's three general partners are believed to have
little desire to actually take control of Chicago-based UAL as they
have threatened, since they would then face the same problems that
are hampering the current board's efforts to put a deal together.
   UAL management has drafted a new employee-buyout plan that
reportedly values the company at $240 a share, or $5.43 billion,
but the proposal has not been endorsed by United's pilots or flight
attendants, and the powerful Machinists union has said it would
oppose such a deal.
   ``If you're going to have a meaningful ESOP (employee stock
ownership plan), you must must have the three unions involved,''
Joedicke said.
   Opposition from the Machinists helped scuttle the $6.75 billion
pilot-management bid, in which British Airways PLC also was to have
participated as an equity partner.
   Meanwhile, the United chapter of the Association of Flight
Attendants opened a two-day meeting Thursday in Chicago to elect
new officers.
   Local President Patricia Friend and Vice President Carol Holmes
announced earlier this month that they were stepping down, a move
expected to reduce friction between management and the flight
attendants and perhaps smooth the way toward an employee buyout
agreement.
</TEXT>
