<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Inflation     12-15 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Inflation,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Rate Climbs to 7.7 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's annual inflation rate rose to 7.7
percent in November from 7.3 percent in October, pushed up by
higher mortgage rates, the government said Friday.
   The underlying inflation rate, excluding mortgage payments, was
unchanged at 6.1 percent, the Central Statistical Office said.
   The financial markets had little reaction to the latest
inflation rate, which was better than had been expected.
   Economists had braced themselves for a rise to 7.9 percent after
Chancellor of the Exchequer John Major recently announced that more
expensive home loans would push the retail price index up.
   The government has pushed up interest rates sharply to fight
inflation, but the policy has the ironic effect of inflating the
inflation rate.
   Major and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher have said repeatedly
that fighting inflation is their No. 1 economic priority, and that
interest rates will stay high as long as is necessary.
   Prices rose 0.9 percent in November, the statistical office
said. Half the month-to-month rise was the result of the mortgage
rates, it said.
   The index, which uses a January 1987 base of 100, stood at 118.5
in November, 117.5 in October, and 110.0 in November 1988, it said.
   Mortgage rates have climbed following the government's latest 1
percentage-point hike in base interest rates to 15 percent in
October.
   The statistical office said there was a sharp rise in food
prices concentrated among seasonal foods in November, partly
because of poor crops caused by the dry summer. There also were
price increases in leisure goods and clothing, it said.
   But there was a small drop in gasoline prices, and some price
discounts for alcoholic beverages, it said.
</TEXT>
