<FIRST>r f PM-Stroh-Guinness     12-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Stroh-Guinness,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guinness Buys Share of Stroh Sparkling Juice Business</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British brewing giant Guinness PLC says it will
tap a fast-growing non-alcoholic beverage market with the purchase
of a $58 million share of Stroh Brewery Co.'s carbonated juice
business.
   The companies said Thursday that creation of New Era Beverage
Co., in which each will own a 44.5 percent share, is expected to be
completed by the end of the year. The joint venture will make and
sell Stroh's Sundance Natural Juice Sparklers.
   ``In a market that's not growing, we're seeing alcoholic
beverage suppliers turn more to non-alcoholic beverages,'' said
Benjamin Steinman, associate publisher of the trade publication
Beer Marketer's Insights.
   New Era's president and chief executive officer will be Charles
L. Jarvie, former chief executive officer of Dr. Pepper and of
Schenley Industries. Guinness acquired Schenley in 1987.
   Jarvie will head an investor and management group that will hold
the remaining 11 percent of New Era Beverage.
   Also pending at Stroh, the nation's No. 3 brewer behind
Anheuser-Busch Cos. Inc. and Miller Brewing Co., is a September
agreement in principle to sell most of its beer brewing and
container facilities and brands to No. 4 Coors Brewing Co. for $425
million.
   A definitive agreement with Coors is expected early next year,
although that transaction has been challenged by smaller brewers as
anti-competitive and also awaits U.S. Justice Department review,
Stroh spokeswoman Lacey Logan said.
   The transactions are independent, Stroh Senior Vice President
George Kuehn said. The Coors agreement provides Stroh would retain
the Van Nuys, Calif., and Memphis, Tenn., plants that produce
Sundance.
   Guinness already markets non-alcoholic products such as Kaliber
lager and Malta malt beverage and wants to expand in that area,
said Chris Davidson, a spokesman at the company's London
headquarters.
   Sundance has more than 50 percent of a U.S. juice and sparkling
water market that is growing at 20 percent a year, Davidson said.
   Sundance is the only nationally marketed sparkling fruit drink.
There are no immediate plans to expand marketing beyond the United
States, Davidson said.
   Privately-held Stroh doesn't divulge sales or earnings, but
analysts estimated 1988 sales at $1.4 billion, including $75
million to $80 million in Sundance sales.
   Guinness, selling products including Guinness Stout, Johnny
Walker and Dewar's White Label Scotch whisky, Tanqueray and
Gordon's gin and I.W. Harper bourbon in 200 countries, had 1988
sales of $4.5 billion, Davidson said.
</TEXT>
