<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   12-15 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Weather Helps Boost Soybeans; Grains Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices rose moderately in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, bolstered by
cold-weather concerns, but grain futures were mixed.
   Frigid temperatures in the nation's mid-section have supported
the soybean market all week amid perceptions that the cold has
boosted demand for soybean meal as a high-energy livestock feed.
   This morning's temperatures were among the lowest yet this
season, with sub-zero readings across Nebraska, Kansas and much of
the Midwest.
   The cold snap also supported the corn market, but wheat prices
were slightly lower amid profit-taking after moderate gains in the
past week.
   The cold weather was expected to continue for at least another
week but analysts said its influence would fade if new export
business emerges.
   ``It's a market that's waiting for more Russian business, that's
the best way to characterize it,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of
Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   In early trading, wheat futures were 1 cent to 1{ cents lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.15\ a bushel; corn
was unchanged to \ cent higher with December at $2.35\ a bushel;
oats were \ cent lower to \ cent higher with March at $1.55{ a
bushel; soybeans were { cent to 2} cents higher with January at
$5.85 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle futures were .10 cent to .22 cent higher with
December at 77.62 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent lower
to .40 cent higher with January at 83.95 cents a pound; live hogs
were .12 cent lower to .33 cent higher with December at 52.85 cents
a pound; frozen pork bellies were .43 cent to 1.20 cents higher
with February at 50.75 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures ended mostly higher on Thursday while pork
bellies fell.
</TEXT>
