<TEXT>
   Stock prices slipped a notch today as the market
absorbed the impact of the quarterly ``triple witching hour.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 10.88 to
2,742.75 by noontime on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 544 up, 788 down and
563 unchanged.
   Prices were buffeted around a bit by orders from professional
traders engaged in computer-program strategies involving individual
stocks and a series of expiring options and futures on stock
indexes.
   The witching hour, which comes on the third Friday of the last
month of each calendar quarter, did not appear to have more than a
passing effect, however.
   Analysts said investors also seemed uncertain what to make of a
spate of new government figures on the state of the economy.
   Reaction was mildly positive to news that the producer price
index of finished goods dropped 0.1 percent in November. But a
separate report showed a widening of the nation's trade deficit to
$10.20 billion in October from a revised $8.51 billion the month
before.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down \ at
43\; International Business Machines, down ] at 94}; DuPont, down {
at 124{, and USX, down ] at 35].
   Bank of New England tumbled 2} to 9|. The company announced
projected increases in its loan-loss reserve and non-performing
assets, and said it would report a substantial loss for the year.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
.57 to 193.40. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down .29 at 376.53.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 123.01 million shares at
noontime, up from 91.98 million at the same point Thursday.
