<HEAD>Scripps Buys Back Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E.W. Scripps Co. says it has paid $39.6
million to buy its stock from the estate of John P. Scripps as part
of the 1986 acquisition agreement for his seven newspapers.
   The sale announced Thursday included 581,763 shares of E.W.
Scripps' Class A Common Stock and more than 1.7 million shares of
Common Voting Stock.
   Scripps, who died March 15, founded John P. Scripps Newspapers
and was a former director of E.W. Scripps.
   Scripps and his family had received the E.W. Scripps shares in
the agreement when his newspapers merged with the company.
   E.W. Scripps operates 19 daily newspapers, nine television
stations, five radio stations and cable television systems. The
company also licenses and syndicates news features and comics, such
as ``Peanuts'' and ``Garfield.''
