<FIRST>u f PM-Kodak 1stLd-Writethru f0076 12-15 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kodak, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0076,0419</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Says Restructuring To Reduce Earnings $500 Million</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: New grafs 1-3 to ADD pretax charges, recast; picks up 3rd graf
pvs bg'ng, Kodak in ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. said today its 1989
earnings would be reduced by about $500 million because of costs
from a restructuring earlier this year.
   The $500 million in net charges for the year translates to about
$850 million before taxes, Kodak spokesman Henry Kaska said.
   The photography giant said $273 million of the reductions would
be charged to fourth-quarter earnings, significantly more than had
been anticipated. Kodak had already charged $227 million against
earnings for the second quarter and had predicted that the
fourth-quarter charge would be lower.
   Kodak in August announced a major corporate restructuring that
includes between 4,500 and 5,000 job cuts _ about 3 percent of its
worldwide work foce _wage freezes, the sale or consolidation of
many businesses and other cost-cutting measures.
   ``This action reflects our efforts to sharpen the focus if the
Kodak organization by withdrawing from businesses and activities
that do not contribute to shareowner value,'' Kodak Chairman and
Chief Executive Colby H. Chandler said in a statement.
   Chandler said annual earnings would be reduced because of
provisions for write-offs of equipment, materials and inventories
for various businesses. Additional charges will come from special
payment to departing employees.
   ``Our business units and support organizations are clearly
concentrating on value-adding operations and activities,''
Chandler's statement read. ``As a result, Kodak will enter the new
decade as a stronger, more competitive company.''
   Kodak earnings have declined in three straight quarters. The
Rochester-based company reported a 25 percent third-quarter drop to
$329 million, or $1.02 per share, compared to $435 million, or
$1.35 per share, in the same 1988 quarter.
   Earnings fell 23 percent in the first quarter and 85 percent in
the second quarter compared to year-ago figures. The April-June
quarter included expenses of the restructuring.
   Kodak has blamed its weakness in part on higher operating costs
and no improvement in productivity, deapite strong sales.
   Net earnings for the first three quarters were $589 million, or
$1.82 a share, down 46 percent from $1.09 billion, or $3.35 a
share, in the first three quarters of 1988. The second-quarter
earnings already reflected the $227 million in restructuring costs.
   Sales for the first nine months of the year rose 8 percent to
$13.5 billion from $12.5 billion a year earlier.
</TEXT>
