<HEAD>London Shares End Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices drifted lower in lackluster trading
Friday on the London Stock Exchange, with dealers content to follow
Wall Street's weak lead.
   News that Britain's annual inflation rate rose to 7.7 percent in
November from 7.3 percent in October was shrugged off by the market.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended the day
22.3 points, or 0.9 percent, lower at 2,344.7, slightly above its
session low of 2,341.5.
   Volume totaled 444.9 million shares, down from 486.8 million on
Thursday. Dealers said volume dropped sharply in the afternoon,
when interest evaporated.
   Despite the market's bearish tone, traders said selective buying
helped some shares. The bank sector, in particular, stood out from
the rest of the market, although dealers said there were no special
reasons for gains there.
   The Financial Times 30-share index lost 19.7 points to close at
1,851.7. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 12.22 points to
1,273.97.
