<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-LuxuryPens Bjt   12-15 0783</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Luxury Pens, Bjt,0808</SECOND>
<HEAD>Expensive, Aristocratic Pens May Be The Season's Hottest Gift</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Propelled by the strength of a single human
hand, it glides with ease. Its fit feels custom-made. And it's one
of the season's hottest selling items: Behold, the pen.
   But not just any pen. These are luxury pens, the new must-have
accessory for the Rolex-watch set.
   Sales of fine writing instruments are skyrocketing this
Christmas, with some retailers reporting increases of up to 70
percent.
   ``It's incredible,'' said Bill Wendell, marketing manager for
Waterman pens. ``We can sell every pen we make, and we'll double
sales this year.''
   Unlike fad gifts of Christmases past _ the pet rock, the
Walkman, Giorgio perfume _ the pen is a time-honored piece.
   After all, Puccini used a Parker to write La Boheme, and it was
a Waterman that scripted the end of World War I with the signing of
the Treaty of Versailles.
   Updated to the '90s, the fancy pen is an affirmation of success.
The more aristocratic in design, the better. And the price? It can
be anywhere from three figures to four.
   Wendell calls the pen trend a ``cultural phenomenon'' sparked by
the growing importance of ``high-quality, functional accessories.''
   ``Some people say it's a rebellion against computers,'' said
Lisa Sawyers, manager of Pen &amp; Paper in Nashville, Tenn. ``People
are tired of everything being faxed and computerized. The art of
letter writing is coming back again.''
   A fine pen is more than a nostalgic return to personal
expression. It is ``a status symbol,'' said Jeannette Brewster, a
pen buyer for Cole National Corp., which sells fine pens through
its Things Remembered and HQ Gifts stores nationwide.
   ``Maybe the president (of a company) has one, and when he goes
to a business meeting, everybody wants to have it,'' she said.
   Among the growing menagerie of expensive pens, Cartier, the
master jeweler, is offering its ``Pasha'' fountain pen complete
with 40 coats of lacquer and an 18-karat gold nib, or point, for
$775.
   Then there's Parker Pen's Duofold, a $300 pen drilled from a
solid block of acrylic, trimmed in 22-karat gold and guaranteed not
to explode under airplane pressure.
   For those seeking something more contemporary, there's the Fendi
pen, from the Italian designer of the same name, which is encased
in tiny rings of pale grey rubber and sells for a measly $35.
   The year's best seller may be the Montblanc, the product of an
81-year-old West German company. Topped with a signature white
``snowcap'' reminiscent of its namesake, Europe's highest peak,
Montblanc pens sell for $100 to $7,000 each.
   Retailers say some of Montblanc's success comes from several
years of advertising in magazines like Architectural Digest, Vanity
Fair and Connoisseur. Now that America's appetite for pens has been
whetted, others are riding the wave.
   Waterman, acquired by Gillette Co. in 1987, is spending $5
million a year to market its French-made writing instruments.
   The best pens come in ball point, though they are at the lower
end of the spectrum. Rollerball pens use liquid instead of paste
ink, and therefore are more expensive. The most prestigious is the
fountain pen.
   ``Although the U.S. is a ball-point society, people are finding
the enjoyment of going back and writing with a fountain pen,'' said
Richard Mattes, vice president of marketing for Koh-I-Noor
Rapidograph Inc. of New Jersey, the exclusive North American
Montblanc distributor.
   Fountain pens are the fastest growing category of writing
instruments. About 12 million were sold in 1987; a year later the
number jumped to 21 million.
   ``If you're going to write a love letter ... doesn't it look
better with a fountain pen?'' Mattes asked.
   Because they require special care _ refilling the ink and
occasional professional cleanings, fountain pens have a very
special cachet.
   ``You have to have a bit more leisure time to deal with a
fountain pen,'' said Waterman's Wendell. ``Isn't that the upscale
imagery being projected by the user?''
   All pens must be chosen carefully. But in the case of a fountain
pen, selecting a nib can take hours. Nib widths vary to produce
fine to very broad scripts, and the shape of one's penmanship
depends on the pressure exterted on the nib and the angle it is
held against the paper.
   Over time, the nib conforms to an individual user, and for that
reason, ``one should never lend it,'' Wendell said.
   But despite a luxury pen's ability to elegantly paint words, how
they write often is less important than how they look. Parker's
marketing planner Greg Watts said one businesswoman told him, ``I
don't use this pen to write with. I wear it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
