<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   12-15 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed; Profit-Taking Offsets Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade as pre-weekend profit-taking
offset buying related to the weather.
   Wheat futures finished moderately lower across the board and
corn was narrowly mixed.
   Soybeans closed mostly lower although the contracts for
near-term delivery continued to find support in the bitter cold
Midwestern weather that has boosted domestic demand for soybean
meal as a high-energy livestock feed.
   The cold weather is expected to continue for at least another
week but analysts said its influence will fade if new export
business emerges.
   The weather's market impact is ``more psychological than
anything,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager of Balfour Maclaine Corp.'s
floor operations at the Board of Trade.
   ``It isn't going to change the world supply and demand,'' he
said.
   At the close of trading, wheat futures prices were 1{ cents to
3\ cents lower with the contract for delivery in December at $4.13
a bushel; corn futures were } cent lower to 1 cent higher with
December at $2.35} a bushel; oats were { cent lower to \ cent
higher with December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents
lower to 1\ cents higher with January at $5.83{ a bushel.
