<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Gillette     12-15 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gillette,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gillette Announes Realignment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co., trying to rebuild profits hurt by
recent takeover battles, announced Friday it would realign its
operations and sell some of its European business, affecting about
750 workers in the process.
   Gillette said it was creating a North Atlantic Shaving and
Personal Care Group that would encompass its shaving products and
toiletries segments.
   The reorganization would make the company more efficient,
Gillette said in a statement.
   The move is part of Gillette's strategy to improve its profits.
In recent years, the firm has fended off takeover attempts by
Revlon Group Inc. and Coniston Partners of New York, but its
earnings suffered as a result.
   This fall, Gillette said it was introducing a new razor, called
Sensor, which would be priced higher than the current brands but
also is designed to offer a closer shave.
   Both the new razor and the new corporate alignment are aimed at
improving the company's profits, said David Fausch, a Gillette
spokesman.
   ``The company's strategy is to work to increase efficiency,
increase profits, increase market share,'' he said.
   The merging of shaving and personal care will mean the
elimination of about 250 jobs, Fausch said. Gillette employs about
29,000 people worldwide.
   In addition, the company will sell its Antica Erboristeria line
of toiletries in Italy, La Toja bath products in Spain, plus
European hair care products. Those operations employ about 500
people.
   Those products have not been as successful as the company had
hoped, Fausch said.
   The operations to be sold represented about $100 million in
sales last year, compared with about $1 billion in worldwide
toiletry sales.
   Proceeds from the sales were expected to offset the costs from
the realignment.
</TEXT>
