<FIRST>u f AM-AutoIncentives Bjt   12-15 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Incentives, Bjt,0652</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Announces New Incentives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. announced an
incentive program Friday designed in part to maintain production at
its two minivan plants before shutting them down to retool for a
new version.
   The program includes a guarantee that the company will make up
any difference in rebate programs through the first three quarters
of next year _ a time Chrysler has said will include some of the
toughest months in recent automotive history.
   The guarantee is aimed at consumers who may be waiting for more
attractive incentives later in the year, Chrysler Motors Chairman
Ben Bidwell said Friday at a news conference.
   ``We want some (showroom) traffic now,'' Bidwell said.
   Sales Manager Louis Payne of Keensport Chrysler-Plymouth outside
Pittsburgh, Pa., said his dealership could use some traffic.
   ``It's real slow this month,'' he said Friday. ``At this time of
year, it's hard to compete with Santa Claus.''
   Typically, vehicle sales pick up a little in January and fall
off again in February before rebounding in March and April as
weather improves.
   In the past, when one of the Big Three U.S. automakers issued a
new incentive program, the other two soon followed. General Motors
Corp. and Ford Motor Co. had no immediate reaction to Chrysler's
move.
   Chrysler's new incentives range from $500 to $2,000, depending
on model, or low-interest financing ranging from 6.9 percent to 9.9
percent, depending on length of loan. Some minivans have an option
of cash rebates or interest rates as low as 3.9 percent on a 2-year
loan.
   The program, which expires Jan. 31, 1990, covers two-thirds of
the cars and light trucks Chrysler makes.
   The incentives on Chrysler's minivans represent the first time
in six years that an enticement has been offered on the popular
vehicles. Since their introduction, Chrysler has commanded more
than 50 percent of the minivan market.
   But that share is being eroded by recent introductions of new
minivans from GM and Mazda Motor Corp. and those already in
showrooms from Ford and a half-dozen or so Japanese companies.
   Chrysler expects to introduce a new version of its Dodge Caravan
and Plymouth Voyager next fall for the 1991 model year.
   Production at Chrysler's minivan plants in Windsor, Ontario, and
St. Louis, Mo., will be shut down in the third week of June and the
third week of July, respectively, to change equipment for the new
models.
   The changeovers will take about four weeks, Bidwell said.
   Analysts have speculated that automakers, faced with swelling
inventories and waning demand, may cut their supplies of unsold
cars by curtailing production during the first quarter of 1990.
   Chrysler said this week that it would shut down its car plant
near St. Louis, causing about 3,400 layoffs, for four weeks
beginning Monday because of slow sales of the Chrysler LeBaron and
the Dodge Daytona. The company also said 3,000 employees of its
Belvidere, Ill., plant, which makes five full-size cars, would be
laid off for two weeks beginning Jan. 2 because of falling sales.
   Bidwell said that won't be the case for Chrysler's minivan
plants, which make a product that's responsible for much of the
company's shrinking profits.
   ``We absolutely do not face downtime except for the
changeover,'' Bidwell said. However, he added, some overtime at the
two plants may be cut.
   Analysts and industry officials have agreed that demand for
minivans will remain strong during next year while the industry as
a whole weakens.
   Chrysler has forecast that 14.2 million cars and light trucks
will be sold in 1990, down from the 14.8 million or so that will be
sold this year. Ford has forecast a slightly slower year in 1990
while GM has forecast the industry will sell 15 million vehicles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
