<DOCNO> AP891215-0277 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1631EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-GAFTrial     12-15 0554</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GAF Trial,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Lawyers Charge Perjury; Say Sherwin Rejected Plea Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GAF Corp. lawyers alleged Friday that government
witnesses lied in testimony during the company's lengthy stock
fraud trial and said GAF Vice Chairman James T. Sherwin rejected a
last-minute offer that would have cleared him of criminal charges.
   Only hours after the government offered the deal Wednesday, a
federal jury convicted Sherwin and GAF on all eight counts of stock
manipulation, securities fraud and other charges in an alleged 1986
scheme to boost Union Carbide Corp.'s stock price.
   Under the deal, GAF would have pleaded guilty to all counts and
Sherwin would have been released of all charges in the deal,
according to lawyers involved in the case. The company reportedly
had approved the deal.
   But as part of the deal, Sherwin would have had to sign a
statement saying he was acting on behalf of the company in the
unlawful activities alleged by the government.
   Lawyers for Sherwin and GAF plan to appeal the verdict.
   The GAF verdict, which was viewed as a major victory for the
government, came after two mistrials earlier this year.
   Lead GAF attorney Arthur Liman in a statement said WATS line
telephone records from the Jefferies &amp; Co. brokerage, which
allegedly conducted the manipulation for GAF, refuted testimony
that calls were made to Sherwin to discuss the October 1986 scheme.
   ``(Sherwin) is a man of principle who sat through three trials
that were tainted by brazen perjury that was finally exposed by the
WATS records,'' Liman said in a statement. ``We were under no
illusions as to the likely verdict. It was visible on the jurors'
faces.
   ``But the government insisted on a corporate allocution which
would have stripped Jim Sherwin of all self respect and condoned
the perjury. This he could not let the corporation do and he has no
regrets about the decision he made to allow the jury deliberations
to proceed to verdict.''
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Carl H. Loewenson Jr. declined to
comment on the perjury allegation.
   The government based its case on testimony by admitted felon and
former stockbroker Boyd L. Jefferies, who testified that he agreed
to bid up the price of Union Carbide at Sherwin's request. GAF was
seeking to sell 5 million shares of Union Carbide after a failed
takeover bid.
   Jefferies also said Sherwin promised to reimburse the brokerage
for any losses. Evidence included an allegedly phony invoice for
$40,000 investment banking advisory services that represented a
trading loss.
   Jefferies &amp; Co. chief trader James Melton and trading assistant
Maureen O'Connor testified about the alleged phone calls.
   Melton claimed he called Sherwin at the end of three consecutive
trading days to discuss the upward manipulation of Carbide stock.
The WATS line records indicated no such calls were made. O'Connor
said she overheard the calls.
   Records for regular phone lines also did not indicate that the
calls were made.
   Also, Jefferies' testimony was contradicted during the second
trial and Liman in his closing arguments said Jefferies' testimony
was ``filled with inconsistencies and contradictions.''
   Sherwin faces up to 40 years in prison and up to $2 million in
fines, but his sentence is expected to be far less than the
maximum. GAF could be fined up to $4 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1638EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MediaOutlook     12-15 0741</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Media Outlook,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder, Tribune Co., NY Times Co. Discuss Earnings Outlooks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Media giant Knight-Ridder Inc. said Friday it
expects to post higher earnings this year and that savings from its
recently-enacted newspaper joint operating agreement in Detroit
will boost 1990 earnings.
   Tribune Co., meanwhile, said it expects a profit increase for
1989 but said earnings growth would be more difficult to achieve in
1990 due to impending labor negotiations, slow advertising revenue
growth and weak newsprint prices.
   New York Times Co. said a gain on the sale of its cable
operations would mean record 1989 earnings, but earnings from
continuing operations _ excluding the cable sale gain _ would be
down substantially. It expects higher earnings in 1990 excluding
the cable sale gain.
   The companies discussed their earnings prospects before
securities analysts attending the annual PaineWebber media outlook
conference.
   Advertising revenue growth from Miami-based Knight-Ridder's 29
daily newspapers, lower newsprint prices and lower interest costs
were cited for contributing to the company's stronger 1989 earnings
outlook.
   James K. Batten, chairman and chief executive, declined to offer
a specific projection of earnings.
   But securities analysts have estimated 1989 earnings per share
from continuing operations will amount to between $2.80 and $2.90
compared with net income of $2.59 a share in 1988 and 1990 earnings
per share from continuing operations of $3.40 to $3.50.
   Batten said one major contributor to earnings growth in 1990
would be the recent enactment of the joint operating agreement
between Knight-Ridder's Detroit Free Press and the Detroit News,
owned by Gannett Co. Inc.
   He said the agreement, which combined business operations of the
newspapers while news and editorial staffs operate separately,
means an end to 11 consecutive years of operating losses at the
Free Press.
   Batten said the Free Press was expected to lose between $13
million and $16 million in 1989, excluding corporate charges but
that the company ``won't lose money in Detroit next year.''
   Batten said the end of losses at the Detroit newspaper,
contiunued soft newsprint prices, improvement at The Miami Herald
and strong results from business information services will help
1990 earnings.
   Chicago-based Tribune Co. said strong growth in its broadcasting
and entertainment businesses as well as increases from newspapers
should help it post earnings per share of $3.10 in 1989, up from
$2.78 in 1988.
   But Scott Smith, senior vice president and chief financial
officer, although the company would like higher earnings per share
in 1990, ``this may be a difficult goal to achieve.''
   He said the company faces ``difficult labor negotiations''
involving workers at the Daily News in New York. He said contract
talks also will occur next year involving newsprint production
workers in Canada and major league players. Tribune Co. owns the
Chicago Cubs baseball team.
   Smith said newspaper ad revenues were up 4.5 percent to 5
percent in 1989 and should be slightly higher in 1990. But he said
weakness in newsprint prices may persist, hurting Tribune's results
from newsprint operations.
   New York Times Co. earned $2.08 a share in 1988 and posted a
gain of $2.46 per share this year on the sale of its cable system.
   It announced earlier this week it intended to charge 57 cents a
share against fourth-quarter earnings, reflecting estimated costs
of voluntary staff cuts at its flagship newspaper due to a weak
advertising climate in New York, further automation of production
facilities and a decline in its valuations of its investment in
forest products operations.
   Walter E. Mattson, president and chief operating officer, said a
7 percent decline in ad linage at the Times offset the effects of
tighter cost controls. That combined with lower newsprint prices in
1989 will produce flat operating results from newspapers, excluding
special charges taken in 1988.
   He said results from magazines would decline from 1988, showing
a loss for the year due to acquisitions, but that broadcast and
information services were up and regional newspapers had a record
year. Newsprint business results also are down sharply, he said.
   Mattson said with the charges, the company lost money in the
fourth quarter and that earnings from continuing operations ``will
be down substantially for the year.'' Including the cable gain,
however, the company will have record earnings for the year.
   He said he agreed with analysts who have predicted ``another
year of low earnings'' in 1990 but said earnings should top 1989
results, excluding the cable sale.
</TEXT>
