<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2031EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HenleyRestructuring     12-15 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Henley Restructuring,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Henley Group Split Into Two Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMPTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of directors of The Henley Group
Inc. on Friday approved splitting the conglomerate into two
companies.
   The division continues a program that Henley has pursued of
creating new publicly held companies.
   The two new companies are Henley Properties Inc., specializing
in real estate, and a new company called The Henley Group Inc.,
which will hold all the remaining assets.
   ``Separating our extensive real-estate operations from Henley's
other businesses and investments continues our policy of grouping
complementary assets in public companies so these assets can be
better understood and evaluated by investors,'' said Michael
Dingman, chairman and chief executive officer of the existing
conglomerate.
   Stockholders will get one share of the new Henley Group as a
tax-free distribution for each share they hold in the existing
company as of Dec. 20. The remainder will be renamed Henley
Properties.
   Henley Properties, with assets of $650 million, will own the
existing company's real estate developments and acreage in southern
California, Hawaii, Wisconsin, Michigan and New Hampshire.
   The new Henley Group Inc. will own the existing company's
remaining assets of about $3.5 billion. Included are two wholly
owned subsidiaries: Fisher Scientific Group Inc., which makes and
distributes laboratory and medical products; and Pneumo Abex Corp.,
which makes equipment for aircraft and friction-braking products
for cars, trucks and other vehicles. Cape Horn Methanol Ltd., now
mostly owned by Henley, will be part of the new company.
   Cape Horn Methanol makes methanol from natural gas in Chile.
   Henley Properties will include the existing company's wholly
owned subsidiary Signal Landmark Holdings Inc., which the company
described as a major developer of residential commercial and
industrial real estate, mainly in southern California and Hawaii.
Henley said Signal Landmark also owns more than 300,000 acres of
recreational and residential real estate in northern Michigan and
Wisconsin.
   The company said Henley Properties also will own the existing
company's half-interest in Wentworth by the Sea, an oceanfront
project in New Castle, N.H., consisting of a planned hotel at the
site of an old resort hotel; a 200-slip marina; a golf course; and
restaurants and homes.
</TEXT>
