<FIRST>u f AM-GM-Saab Bjt   12-15 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM-Saab, Bjt,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM, Saab In Auto Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. will buy half of Saab-Scania
AB's troubled car business for about $600 million, in a deal
analysts described Friday as a good one for both companies.
   The analysts' endorsement of the association is far different
from the concern some voiced seven weeks ago when Ford Motor Co.
announced it would buy all of British automaker Jaguar PLC for $2.5
billion.
   ``GM paid about $3,000 per unit and Jaguar went for about
$40,000 per unit,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp;
Co., referring to the ratio of investment price and the sales of
Saab and Jaguar cars.
   ``One way to look at the $600 million is that's how much it
takes to build a new car,'' he said.
   GM and Saab will form a new independent Swedish car company
called Saab Automobile AB which will produce cars under the Saab
name for worldwide distribution and some GM models for the European
market.
   In Sweden, Saab-Scania President Georg Karnsund said in a
statement that times are tough for low-volume automakers. Saab's
car operations lost $186.1 million during the first eight months of
this year.
   ``Soaring costs for research and development and ever-increasing
international competition make it difficult for small-volume makers
to survive on their own in a longer perspective,'' he said.
   ``For GM,'' said analyst John Kirnan of Kidder, Peabody Inc. in
New York, ``I think there are some definite benefits. They get
greater access to the Scandinavian market and the European market
in general.
   ``The days of the smaller, niche-oriented companies are getting
fewer and farther between,'' he said.
   Under their agreement, GM and Saab will invest $100 million in
the new venture. Each company will nominate five members of the
10-member board, and GM will nominate the chairman.
   The company will manufacture and distribute cars under the Saab
name for sale through Saab's independent dealer network and produce
GM cars for sale through GM's Europe organization, GM said in a
statement.
   ``Saab products are considered a premium brand. They have a good
image for high technology and performance,'' said GM spokesman Jack
Harned in Detroit.
   Also under the agreement, Saab will form a new Saab-Scania
Automotive Electronics AB, in which GM will have a minority share,
to research, develop and manufacture advanced auto electronics
systems.
   Saab-Scania's Karnsund also said an agreement had been reached
between Saab Missile and GM Hughes Aircraft Co., a GM subsidiary,
to develop and produce tactical missiles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
