<FIRST>u f AM-Coors-Stroh     12-15 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coors-Stroh,0501</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coors-Stroh Letter of Intent Expires With No Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter of intent for Coors Brewing Co. to buy
Stroh Brewing Co.'s domestic beer making operations for $425
million expired Friday with no sale, freeing Stroh to seek other
buyers, the companies said.
   Chris Sortwell, Stroh vice president for corporate planning and
development, said the companies agreed not to discuss details, such
as whether the price or antitrust considerations were stumbling
blocks to the buyout.
   But Coors President Peter Coors cited unresolved issues in the
transaction as originally contemplated and concern with antitrust
issues.
   ``We felt it best for both parties to take a fresh look at
things and explore other alternatives,'' he said.
   Stroh Chairman Peter Stroh said his company expects to continue
discussions with Coors, although on terms different from those in
the letter of intent. Stroh Brewing also will consider discussions
with others, he said.
   ``Apparently they have opened up the negotiations to anyone,''
said Allan Kaplan, beverage analyst with Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in New
York. ``It does sound like the deal is off. I think they must have
disagreed on price,''
   Stroh officials wouldn't discuss whether others have made
overtures, Sortwell said.
   Stroh has argued that combining with Coors would increase
competition by creating an effective No. 3 competitor to go against
Anheuser-Busch Cos., the leader with 41 percent of the market, and
No. 2 Miller Brewing Co., which has 21 percent.
   Stroh now is No. 3 with an 11 percent market share and Coors is
No. 4 with just under 8 percent, followed by G. Heileman &amp; Co. with
about 7 percent.
   ``Although we continue to believe that consolidation in the
brewing industry would be good for long-term competition, we are
taking aggressive steps to strengthen our ability to compete
independently,'' Stroh said.
   Preparations for possible independent operation included recent
employment cuts and sales of Stroh assets, Sortwell said. ``As of
right now, it would appear to be somewhat likely,'' he said.
   On Thursday, the 139-year-old Detroit company said it had agreed
to sell its Sundance Natural Juice Sparkler business for $58
million to a partnership in which Stroh and Guinness PLC each would
hold a 44 percent interest.
   Stroh has sought potential partners since February and announced
Aug. 31 it was laying off 300 of its 1,500 white-collar employees
nationwide because there had been no suitable offers.
   Members of Wisconsin's congressional delegation asked the U.S.
Justice Department in November to prohibit the Coors-Stroh
transaction as anti-competitive. The department's antitrust
division was reviewing the deal.
   Also pending is a federal lawsuit by S&amp;P Co., a Mill Valley,
Calif., company that owns several smaller breweries, including
Pabst Blue Ribbon Hamms, Olympia and Falstaff and commands a 4
percent market share. The suit contends the combination would
overwhelmingly increase the market share of the nation's four
largest brewers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
