<FIRST>u f AM-BankofNewEngland 1stLd-Writethru f0147 12-15 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank of New England, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0147,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bank of New England Announces Buildup of Loan Reserves, Corporate
Shakeup</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pv, `Bank of ...' to UPDATE with closing stock
price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A regional real estate slump prompted Bank of New
England Corp. to announce Friday it will sharply boost reserves
against bad loans and that it expects a substantial loss for the
year.
   The bank also announced it had reassigned a senior executive
overseeing its real estate group, that it was considering the sale
and merger of some operations and that it may rescind its common
stock dividend declared Nov. 27.
   ``In my history of following bank stocks, that action is
unprecedented,'' said James Moynihan, senior vice president of
Advest Inc. in Boston, referring to the stock move. ``I think what
it tells you is the deterioration of the real estate market is
getting faster. It goes from bad to worse every day.''
   ``It may be in the best interest of the company to preserve its
capital, even at the expense of shareholders,'' he said.
   Marcia Ryan, a spokeswoman for the bank, said a dividend of 34
cents a share had been declared for the fourth quarter ending Dec.
31. ``What we're saying is we're looking at a very large addition
to our reserves and that is going to change the (dividend)
calculations,'' she said.
   Bank of New England, which had a loan loss reserve of $354
million at the end of the third quarter, said it would boost that
total to more than $1 billion in the current quarter.
   The company already had taken provisions for problem loans
totaling about $207.3 million in the nine months ended Sept. 30.
   Bank of New England stock tumbled $3.37{ to $9 a share in
consolidated New York Stock Exchange trading Friday.
   The company, owner of the region's second-largest bank,
indicated in late November that it expected a substantial loss for
the fourth quarter due to the sluggish area economy and a soft real
estate market. At that time, Bank of New England announced the sale
of a major portion of its leasing operations to the Bank of Tokyo
as part of a strategic restructuring.
   The latest move follows similar steps taken by other financial
institutions.
   Bank of Boston, the largest bank in New England, reported a $125
million loss in its third quarter after setting aside money to
cover problem loans.
   Much of the trouble stems from the region's real estate market,
which boomed during the middle 1980s but now has gone sour. As a
result, banks have found many developers are having trouble making
loan payments.
   Bank of New England Chairman Walter J. Connolly Jr. issued a
statement saying the additional money placed in reserves was
appropriate to the quality of the bank's loan portfolio and
existing economic conditions in New England.
   Non-performing assets are expected to increase to $1.6 billion,
but the company said it projects its capital ratios will exceed
regulatory minimums.
   Connolly also said the bank's senior management, along with a
special committee of the board of directors, was addressing the
company's loans and assets.
   Executive Vice President James Sweeney, who had been head of the
real estate group, has been removed from that position and assigned
to other duties in the company.
   ``The finger has to point at someone,'' Moynihan said. ``These
problems are real estate related. Some changes had to be made.''
   The bank announced that Executive Vice President Hugh Taylor,
head of the corporate banking group, will take over the real estate
division until a permanent head is selected.
   Bank of New England also announced the special committee and
management will look at steps to increase shareholder values,
including possible mergers and sales of assets.
   The company posted a profit of $121.6 million in the nine months
ended Sept. 30, down from $207.7 million in the same period a year
earlier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
