<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-15 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower In Thin Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mostly lower Friday in
dealings that remained thin despite the release of key economic
data.
   Gold prices gained more than $5 an ounce, mostly on speculative
buying.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery rose $5.60 a troy ounce to settle at $413.90. Republic
National Bank in New York quoted a late bid for gold even higher at
$414.50 an ounce, up $6.20 from Thursday's late bid.
   The government's latest reports on the economy proved bearish
for the dollar. The Commerce Department said the U.S. trade deficit
widened to $10.2 billion in October, greater than the $9 billion
traders had expected.
   A large deficit makes a case for a lower dollar, which helps
improve the trade gap by making imports more expensive and exports
cheaper.
   Separately, the government said producer prices slipped 0.1
percent in November, bucking predictions that called for a 0.1
percent gain.
   After the figures were released, ``the dollar came off fairly
substantially,'' said Bob Morrissey, senior trader at the Bank of
Boston's New York office. The dollar fell below the critical 1.7210
level against the West German mark, leading traders to believe the
currency is gathering momentum to move lower.
   News of Panama declaring that a ``state of war'' exists with the
United States helped the dollar strengthen a bit and gave gold
prices a boost.
   But another mild tremor shook the currency market late in the
session when the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was briefly
down 45 points. The dollar finished at lower levels in sparse
trading.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.23 Japanese yen to a closing 144.30
yen. Later in London, it was quoted at 144.10 yen. In New York the
dollar closed at 144.15 yen, unchanged from late Thursday.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6055 from $1.5970 late
Thursday. In New York one pound cost $1.6030, more expensive than
Thursday's $1.6010.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.7190 West German marks, down from 1.7344;
1.5480 Swiss francs, down from 1.5630; 5.8785 French francs, down
from 5.9285; 1,283.50 Italian lire, down from 1,292.50, and 1.1608
Canadian dollars, up from 1.1598.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.7225 West German marks, down from 1.7375; 1.5485 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5630; 5.8885 French francs, down from 5.9420;
1.9480 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9565; 1,286.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,295.75, and 1.1606 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1585.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $412.25 a troy ounce
from $407.50 bid late Thursday. In Zurich, Switzerland, the metal
rose to a closing bid of $412.50 from $408.50 bid late Thursday.
Earlier in Hong Kong, gold rose 65 cents to close at a bid $409.30.
   Silver rose in London to a late bid price of $5.62 a troy ounce
from $5.58 bid late Thursday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery finished at $5.607 an ounce, up from
Thursday's $5.557.
</TEXT>
