<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-15 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Soar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blast of frigid air pushed heating oil futures
prices to a four-year high Friday, while crude oil futures surged
on reports of new political moves in Panama.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
No. 2 heating oil jumped 3.14 cents to 70.42 cents a gallon in
active trading. Domestic heating oil last closed higher on Jan. 10,
1986, when it hit 72.53 cents a gallon, according to John Santana,
statistical analyst for the New York Merc.
   The contract closed out the week with a gain of 4.05 cents from
its 66.37-cent finish last Friday.
   West Texas Intermediate, the main grade of U.S. crude oil,
jumped 45 cents to end at $21.15 per 42-gallon barrel. It was the
highest level since April 26, when the near-term crude contract
closed at $21.19 a barrel.
   ``Today, Panama was definitely the major factor in the crude
market,'' said James Steel, energy analyst for Refco Inc.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for January ended the session at
52.80 cents a gallon, a gain of 1.19 cents on the session and 0.65
cent for the week.
   Sub-freezing temperatures throughout much of the nation have
boosted demand for heating oil in recent days and spurred buying in
crude and gasoline markets, analysts said. Logistical problems in
Europe due to the low water level of the Rhine River also
contributed to the demand spurt.
   ``The River Rhine rose a foot this week, but the situation still
had a moderating impact on U.S. markets this week,'' said Peter
Beutel, energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc.
   Meanwhile, Manuel Antonio Noriega's rubber-stamp legislature
Friday named him chief executive of Panama and gave him sweeping
powers to confront U.S. efforts to oust the combative general.
   Refco's Steel said events in Panama prompted concerns about the
possible closure of the Panama Canal and disruption of oil
shipments.
   ``A lot of oil goes from the Gulf Coast and Middle East through
the canal to the West Coast,'' he said.
</TEXT>
