<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesRdp     12-15 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Rdp,0702</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama News Helps Boost Gold, Oil Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's latest declaration of hostility against the United
States sent gold prices up sharply Friday and contributed to a
dramatic rise in energy prices by sparking fears of a disruption in
shipments through Panama.
   On other commodity markets, livestock and meat futures advanced
and grains and soybeans were mixed.
   Gold futures settled $5.50 to $5.60 higher on New York's
Commodity Exchange with the contract for delivery in December up
$5.60 at $413.90 a troy ounce. Silver finished 4.7 cents to 5.7
cents higher with December at $5.607 a troy ounce.
   Gold initially drew strength from news that the U.S. trade
deficit widened to $10.2 billion in October. The Commerce
Department report prompted a weakening of the dollar against other
major currencies, which is frequently a buy signal for gold.
   News of the passage of a resolution by the Panama People's
assembly of a resolution stating that Panama is in a ``state of war
while the (U.S.) agression lasts'' reached the gold market late in
the session and triggered fresh buying.
   The rally reflected investor flight to the perceived safety of
gold and other precious metals, which is typical during periods of
heightened international tensions.
   ``I think the markets at the moment are in somewhat of a bullish
trend and susceptible to bullish moves on any news of this nature
that comes out,'' said Anne Orton, a vice president of Deak
International Inc., a New York-based dealer of precious metals and
currencies.
   The gold runup also was a response to a sharp drop in stock
prices in the middle of the afternoon, reminding observers that a
stock-market dive on Oct. 13 had marked the starting point of
gold's recent surge from levels near $360 an ounce.
   Spot gold has been trading within a range between $400 and $420
for more than a week but analysts said the market's pronounced
behavior on Friday indicated underlying bullishness.
   ``Even if it goes down to $390, the trend remains up,'' said
Bernard Savaiko, senior metals analyst with PaineWebber Inc. ``The
dollar's weak and I think that will be a long-term bullish backdrop
for gold.''
   Heating-oil futures surged mightily on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, the market's 12th rise in the last 13 sessions, in
anticipation of bone-chilling cold weather in the Northeast
   Sub-zero temperatures were recorded Friday in the nation's
mid-section, and the cold front was expected to invade the populous
Northeastern United States during the weekend.
   The Panama news was supportive but represented only ``a blip of
maybe 30 points'' in heating oil's 314-point gain, said analyst
Peter Beutel of Elders Futures Inc. in New York.
   However, the possibility of oil supply disruptions through the
Panama Canal helped boost crude oil prices, analysts said.
   Heating oil settled 1.04 cents to 3.14 cents higher with January
at 70.42 cents a gallon; West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 10
cents to 45 cents higher with January at $21.10 a barrel; unleaded
gasoline was .96 cent to 1.19 cents higher with January at 52.80
cents a gallon.
   Cold weather has slowed livestock marketings and continued to
support livestock and meat futures on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle finished .02 cent lower to .52 cent higher with
December at 77.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .55
cent higher with January at 84.27 cents a pound; live hogs were .05
cent to .20 cent higher with December at 52.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .50 cent to 1.10 cents higher with
February at 51.42 cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade as pre-weekend profit-taking offset
weather-related buying.
   Wheat futures settled 1{ cents to 4{ cents lower with December
at $4.13 a bushel; corn futures were } cent lower to 1 cent higher
with December at $2.35} a bushel; oats were \ cent to { cent lower
with December at $1.43{ a bushel; soybeans were 2} cents lower to 1
cent higher with January at $5.83\ a bushel.
</TEXT>
