<FIRST>u f AM-Arby's     12-15 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arby's,0452</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arby's Gets New President, Franchisees Call Truce</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Belatti was named president and chief
operating officer of Arby's Inc. Friday in a move hailed by a group
of dissident franchisees as a step toward ending their feud with
the fast-food chain's parent.
   Belatti was the chain's executive vice president for marketing
and has in the past been critical of industrialist Victor Posner,
who controls DWG Corp., the Miami Beach, Fla., parent of Arby's.
Particularly, Belatti opposed a plan to move Arby's headquarters to
Florida.
   Posner, however, praised Belatti on Friday as a company man who
would maintain Arby's growth. Belatti was recommended by Jay
Darling, a former president of Burger King Corp. who had been
retained as a consultant in DWG's search for a new Arby's president.
   The possibility of moving the headquarters out of Atlanta has
been among major points of contention in a quarrel that has been
raging since the summer between Posner and many of the chain's
franchisees.
   Renee Mottram, a spokeswoman for DWG, said that Posner still
plans to move Arby's headquarters to Miami Beach by 1991.
   The franchisee group, headed by former Arby's President Leonard
H. Roberts, sought to buy Arby's, a move resisted by Posner.
   The group charged that a variety of legal and financial problems
faced by Posner was threatening the stability of the chain, which
specializes in roast beef sandwiches.
   Roberts said Friday that Belatti's appointment signaled an
apparent end to the friction within the company.
   Roberts said he was stepping down as president of A.P.
Association, an organization of franchisees representing about 75
percent of the chain's 2,150 restaurants.
   But he took a parting shot at Posner.
   ``I hope the stability achieved this week by the Arby's system
is permanent,'' Roberts said. ``But I urge you to be mindful of
what has happened to other companies that Posner has controlled.
   ``And if instability returns, I urge you to recall the values of
unity and mobilization. They do get results,'' he said.
   Roberts, who was popular with the chain's franchisees, was
ousted from Arby's in September after he clashed with Posner over
the $200 million takeover bid. The two had been in a verbal war
ever since, with Posner at one point accusing Roberts of waging a
misinformation campaign with ``ugly press releases.''
   Posner acquired Arby's in 1984 as part of Chesapeake Financial
Corp.'s $400 purchase of Royal Crown Companies Inc. Posner's DWG
owns 60 percent of Chesapeake.
   The fast-food chain had total revenues of $153.8 million last
year and operating profit of $20.7 million.
</TEXT>
