<FIRST>u f AM-WarnerBankruptcy     12-15 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner Bankruptcy,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Stalls Warner's Bankruptcy Settlement Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Friday froze the
distribution of funds in financier Marvin L. Warner's $16 million
personal bankruptcy settlement to allow more time to consider a
government appeal.
   The former Ohio financier won approval of the plan from a
federal bankruptcy judge in Jacksonville, Fla., Dec. 4, following
two years of legal wrangling. But the major creditor, the Internal
Revenue Service, filed an immediate appeal.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeal ruled to hold off on
paying creditors indefinitely while it considers the IRS arguments
that Warner's assets could be gone before it gets paid.
   Under the Chapter 11 bankruptcy plan, the IRS is to receive a
total of $13 million in six annual installments. If the appeals
court had not made some kind of ruling by Friday, the plan would
have gone into effect.
   Warner, 70, a former U.S. ambassador to Switzerland whose
fortune crumbled after his Home State Savings Bank in Cincinnati
collapsed, said he did not have an immediate comment on the ruling.
Warner lives on an Ocala, Fla., horse ranch.
   ``I believe ultimately the plan will be confirmed,'' said
court-appointed bankruptcy trustee Ronald Mowrey in Jacksonville.
``As it stands now, no payment has been made to anybody yet.''
   The bankruptcy plan also included $3.6 million in fees to
attorneys and accountants who spent thousands of hours analyzing
Warner's financial transactions since Home State's 1985 collapse.
   Warner filed for protection from creditors in October 1987 under
federal bankruptcy law to halt $4 billion in claims against him.
   A jury in Ohio found Warner guilty in March 1987 on charges
resulting from Home State's collapse. Warner was sentenced to 3{
years in prison, but a state appellate court recently rejected the
convictions.
   Ohio prosecutors plan to ask the state Supreme Court to
reinstate the convictions.
</TEXT>
