<FIRST>u f AM-MackLoans     12-15 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mack Loans,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Truck Firm Not in Compliance With Financial Agreements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALLENTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mack Trucks Inc., which lost more than
$100 million in the first nine months of the year, announced Friday
it is in technical default of $309 million in loans.
   A Mack subsidiary, Mack Financial Corp., has violated
stipulations of the loans and the company asked the lenders to
waive the requirements, said Walter Meck, chief financial officer.
Mack already has renegotiated $147 million in loans.
   The company is still making payments but has not complied with
the stipulations that require the company to maintain financial
health.
   Stock market analysts said technical defaults are not uncommon
among companies losing money.
   Mack's stock closed down $1.25 at $6.25 per share on the
over-the-counter market Friday.
   ``Mack has borrowed more money than lenders are comfortable with
and they want them to renegotiate the credit lines,'' said Frank
Prezelski, a stock analyst with Deutsche Bank in New York. ``The
bottom line doesn't mean very much. It means only that Mack will
refinance and begin to make money again, hopefully, by the middle
of next year.''
   Prezelski said he is confident the company will succeed.
   ``I don't think there's any reason to think that they will go
bankrupt. The company is in better shape than most people give them
credit for,'' he said.
   The company's largest single stockholder, Renault Vehicules
Industries, has offered to supply short-term loans to Mack as long
as it can renegotiate its other loans to make the requirements less
strict, said Gary McManus, an analyst with Merrill Lynch.
</TEXT>
