<FIRST>r f AM-WinnebagoManagement     12-15 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winnebago Management,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Winnebago Names Conner President, Makes Other Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN P. ROSENFELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnebago Industries Inc. ended its
experiment in management by committee on Friday, naming Richard
Conner president and chief executive of the company that makes
recreational vehicles and trucks and offers satellite delivery of
television commercials.
   Winnebago, which is trying to recover from a series of losses,
also announced other executive appointments, replacing the
10-person management council that had governed the Forest City
company since September 1988.
   Conner said his task would be ``downsizing'' Winnebago to make
it more efficient, so it could better ride out swings in gasoline
prices and the economy _ two major factors that influence sales of
motor homes.
   He said no layoffs are planned but that the company might reduce
its payroll by not filling all vacancies created by workers leaving
or retiring.
   Efficiencies mostly would come by being more careful with
inventories and getting rid of excess raw material.
   ``We've got a lot of work to do,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
   The appointments were announced by John K. Hanson, Winnebago's
founder and chairman, a day after a vote on the changes by the
company's board of directors.
   The announcement also followed by a day the company's report of
a $4.6 million loss and a 38 percent slide in revenue in the first
quarter of its fiscal year compared with the same period a year
earlier. The loss followed a fourth-quarter sea of red ink, an
$11.3 million loss that was the largest of any quarter in the
company's history.
   Conner said that in addition to strengthening the management
team and moving to control expenses, Winnebago also will try to
turn things around by doing a better job designing and selling its
products.
   The company is financially strong because of its low debt, but
Conner said, ``the strongest thing is the reputation and name.
Winnebago seems to stand for quality and we're going to live up to
that.''
   Conner, 57, has been a member of the company's board since 1985
and was chief executive of Winnebago's Cycle Sat subsidiary since
August. Cycle Sat delivers commercials to television stations by
satellites.
   The election of Conner as president was no surprise. He was
marked for advancement in August when he was elected deputy
chairman of the board to replace John V. Hanson, the founder's son,
who resigned as a director and officer of the company.
   ``I understand he (Conner) gets along with John K. Hanson, which
is a necessary in the job,'' said Frank Rolfes, an analyst who
follows Winnebago for the Minneapolis securities firm of Dain
Bosworth.
   Rolfes said the appointment would help improve Winnebago's image
because ``I don't think anybody likes to see a company run by a
committee.''
   Winnebago stock closed down 25 cents at $5.25 a share in trading
Friday on the New York Stock Exchange. The announcement of the new
management team came at the end of the trading day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
