<FIRST>u f AM-Bonds     12-15 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonds,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonds Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices were mostly lower Friday as traders
had little response to government data giving further mixed signals
on the economy.
   The U.S. Treasury's 30-year bond fell 1-32 point, or less than
$1 for every $1,000 in face value. Its yield was unchanged from
late Thursday at 7.85 percent.
   Analysts said the credit markets shrugged off a Commerce
Department report that the nation's merchandise trade deficit
soared to $10.2 billion in October, a 19.8 percent jump from
September's $8.51 billion imbalance.
   Meanwhile, the Labor Department's Producer Price Index dipped
0.1 percent last month following a 0.4 percent gain in October and
a 0.9 percent rise in September.
   Analysts said the producer-price index figure was better than
expected while the trade deficit growth was worse. The reports
negated each other in impact on the credit markets.
   ``The general gist of all the evidence we've had over the entire
week is that we have a pretty sluggish situation in the conomy,''
said Jean Buckley, an economist at BankAmerica Capital Markets
Group in San Francisco.
   ``But there was nothing either great or harmful to get things
moving,'' she said. ``The market is very quiet. There aren't that
many positions in the Street now.''
   Bondholders have welcomed recent news of a slowing economy
because it implies less demand for goods and services, easing the
risk of inflation, which erodes the value of bonds.
   Slower growth also encourages the Federal Reserve to take steps
that would lower interest rates to stimulate the economy. Lower
rates make fixed-income investments such as bonds more valuable.
   Economists said they believe the Fed could ease interest rates
next week.
   In the secondary market for Treasury securities, prices of
short-term issues were down 1-32 point to 1-16 point,
intermediate-term maturities were 1-16 point to 3-32 point lower,
and long-term issues were unchanged to down 1-32 point, according
to figures provided by Telerate Inc., a financial information
service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, was down 0.34 at 1,195.65.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 7.88 percent as the
discount gained 2 basis points to 7.64 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 7.78 percent while the discount rose 1 basis point to
7.40 percent. Yields on one-year bills issued at auction Thursday
were at 7.63 percent with the discount off 1 basis points to 7.13
percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, was quoted at 8{ percent, down from 87-16 percent late
Thursday.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds closed at 93 23-32, up 1-32 point. The
average yield to maturity was unchanged at 7.24 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
