<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit surged to
$10.2 billion in October, the worst imbalance in 10 months, as a
record level of imports swamped a small rise in exports, the
Commerce Department said.
   The October deficit was a sharp 19.8 percent higher than the
September imbalance of $8.51 billion, reflecting a higher foreign
oil bill and big increases in imports of food and industrial
supplies, the government said Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp drop in gasoline costs helped push
wholesale prices down in November for the third time in five
months, the government reported.
   The annual rate of inflation, as measured by the Labor
Department's Producer Price Index released Friday, was 4.6 percent
for the first 11 months of the year, up from 4 percent for all of
1988 but much lower than was feared earlier this year.
   The index dipped 0.1 percent last month following a 0.4 percent
gain in October and a 0.9 percent spurt in September. It declined
0.5 percent in July and 0.4 percent in August.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industrial production was little changed in
November despite rebounding from a major strike and a devastating
earthquake, the government said.
   The Fed attributed the 0.1 percent gain Friday to a rebound from
the Boeing Co. strike and from lingering effects in the computer
and related industries from the San Francisco Bay-area earthquake
in October, when output slumped 0.6 percent.
