<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 1932EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Pru-BacheFined     12-15 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pru-Bache Fined,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASD Fines Brokerage $100,000 For Crash-Related Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brokerage firm Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. has agreed to pay a $100,000 fine and be censured for stock
pricing violations following the 1987 market crash, the National
Association of Securities Dealers said Friday.
   In addition, Prudential-Bache ``made adjustments'' of
$235,901.50 in the prices customers paid in connection with the
questioned transactions, the association said in a statement.
   In settling the matter, Prudential-Bache neither admitted nor
denied the allegations, the statement said.
   The association's market surveillance committee said
Prudential-Bache received sell orders involving 20 securities for
which it was the market maker on Oct. 19, 1987, but failed to
complete the sales while the market was open.
   It said the firm subsequently bought the securities from the
customers at prices that were at least 8 percent below the lowest
reported price of the day.
   As a result, the committee said the 186 customer accounts
placing the sell orders received $235,901.50 less than what they
would have received had the orders been executed at the lowest
price of the day.
   The allegations involve activities on Black Monday when the Dow
Jones industrial average plunged 508 points in its biggest one-day
loss ever.
   Prudential-Bache was unable to execute the trades until after
the close of the market because of the extraordinary market
conditions.
   But the association said that the firm had access before it made
the deals to information that indicated the intra-day trading range
for these securities.
   The National Association of Securities Dealers is a
self-regulatory organization for the over-the-counter markets. Its
surveillance committee is responsible for maintaining the integrity
of those markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891215-0298 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-15-89 2255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CircleK     12-15 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Circle K,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Phoenix Corporation Announces Loss, New Debt Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debt-ridden Circle K Corp. on Friday reported
that it has arranged short-term debt relief in an attempt to get
ahead of its interest payments.
   Company spokesman Ray Cox said the new agreement was made
possible when a syndicate of banks waived compliance with the
required-profit-level covenants covering Circle K's $325 million
credit agreement. The company has drawn on $260 million, Cox said.
   In addition, Circle K received a $60 million, 100-day extension
of credit, he said.
   Cox also announced a $4.99 million loss, amounting to 16 cents
per share, for the second quarter of its 1990 fiscal year.
   In the Aug. 1-Oct. 31 period, Circle K had revenues of $937.2
million, Cox said.
   Last year, the company reported a $13.30 million profit, or 25
cents per fully diluted share, on sales of $851.67 million.
   Part of the loss stemmed from a $2.2 million charge in the
company's failed attempts to find a buyer for itself. Circle K
began the effort in May and abandoned it several months ago after
Chairman Karl Eller decided not to bid on a buyout.
   Cox added that the operating results also included an after-tax
loss of just over $1 million for its 50 percent share of a joint
venture in the United Kingdom.
   Cox's secretary said he was unavailable for comment on the
status of the corporation, which last month announced a
restructuring that includes refinancing of debt, a salary freeze,
layoffs and the sale of up to 590 stores deemed unprofitable.
   On Dec. 7, Circle 7 announced a Dec. 15 deadline to get ahead of
its debt service with $20 million in credit.
   It said the banks which are part of its revolving-credit
agreement agreed to make $10 million available, and American
Financial Corp., Circle K's largest stockholder, agreed to advance
the same amount.
   The new agreement includes the banks, American Financial and
``certain issuers of letters of credit (which) ... have consented
to refrain from taking actions to reduce their extensions of credit
during the term of the short-term agreement,'' Cox said in his
statement.
   The covenants apply to $200 million in senior secured notes due
Oct. 15, 1993. They require Circle K to maintain at the end of each
quarter a minimum fixed-coverage ratio for the preceding 12 months,
Cox said.
   ``Funds to make such payment are not presently available to the
company,'' Cox said.
   He said failure to meet the profit levels or negotiate the
agreement struck late Friday would have forced the company to buy
back $20 million of the long-term debt.
   According to company figures, Circle K has long-term debt of
about $1.1 billion, up from $844 million the year before, and paid
$96 million in interest and debt expenses during the 1989 fiscal
year.
   The company's financial woes followed explosive expansion which
saw Circle K grow from about 1,000 convenience stores in 1984 to a
high of 4,685. The financial statement Friday said the total had
dropped to 4,677.
   The company owns about 12 percent of the stores; the others are
franchised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
